[Event "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600: Introduction - The Best 1.e4 Openings Under 1600"]
[Date "2025.12.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B00"]
[Opening "King's Pawn Game"]
[StudyName "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600"]
[ChapterName "Introduction - The Best 1.e4 Openings Under 1600"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/w8FPB8TI/v1F3rIME"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2025.12.26"]
[UTCTime "15:52:01"]

{ Hello chess friends! I am GM Max Illingworth, and in this Study, I will show you the best scoring lines for White after 1.e4 below the 1600 level on Lichess.

By discovering these lines, seeing why they work and playing them in your games, you will improve your results with the White pieces, through learning how to punish the most common mistakes your opponents are making in the opening. }
1. e4 { As for how this Study is structured: I have begun with the analysis chapters (Chapter 2-8) so that you can see:
- what the best openings below 1600 are;
- why they work;
- how to punish the most common mistakes your opponents are making!
After that, I've included 14 Exercises (Chapters 10-23) in the 'Test Yourself' to help you remember the key ideas and also adapt to unexpected moves by the opponent.
Enjoy the Study and please click the heart symbol just below the bottom right of the board if you found this Study helpful! } *


[Event "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600: Vs. 1...e5"]
[Date "2025.12.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C34"]
[Opening "King's Gambit Accepted: MacLeod Defense"]
[StudyName "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600"]
[ChapterName "Vs. 1...e5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/w8FPB8TI/7PCME9HQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2025.12.26"]
[UTCTime "15:52:07"]

1. e4 e5 { You will face this, the Open Games, in about half your games. } 2. f4 { The King's Gambit scores 55.5% (factoring in the draws) in practice, and it's extremely effective at lower levels, because less advanced players particularly struggle when dealing with early aggression and initiative. } (2. Nf3 { is the most common move by far. }) 2... exf4 { A plurality of players take the pawn, but tend to follow up the pawn grab poorly. } { [%cal Gd8h4] } (2... Nc6 { is the 2nd most common below 1400, but after } 3. Nf3 { Black most often plays } 3... exf4 { anyway, transposing to a worse version of 2...exf4 (as we'll see via. the 2...exf4 3.Nf3 Nc6 move order). }) (2... d6 3. Nf3 Nc6 { is another passive but common sequence, which can be met in several ways. I'll suggest } 4. Bc4 { as a relatively straightforward attacking system, in the style of the Vienna Game (2.Nc3). If } { [%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3,Gb1c3] } 4... Bg4 { a good reply is } 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3 { , breaking the pin with the bishop pair and space advantages in tow. } 6... Nd4 7. Qd3 { covers the Nxc2 threat. We will kick out their knight with c3, and we can still meet Qh4 with g3 to protect our kingside. } { [%csl Gh4,Gg3][%cal Gd3c2,Gc2c3] }) 3. Nf3 { The best move, developing the knight but also stopping ...Qh4. Now Black has a wide choice - they actually will play a decent move a lot of the time from here (there are a lot of them, after all), but usually misplay the follow-up, giving us an advantage. } 3... Nc6 { This is a strategic error, as it doesn't interfere with our general plan of d4 and Bxf4, regaining the pawn with a strong centre. } (3... Nf6 { might actually be Black's best move, but below 1600 they follow it up incorrectly. } 4. e5 { Kicking the knight with tempo. } 4... Nd5 { The most common below 1600, playing in Alekhine style. But we obtain a strong initiative with our next, rather creative, continuation. } (4... Nh5 { is the correct move, but only played in 6% of games below 1600, so you don't have to worry about it. }) 5. Nc3! { We accept doubled pawns to accelerate our development. } 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 { Most of the time it's better to recapture toward the centre, but here the priority is regaining our pawn with Bxf4. } { [%cal Gc1f4] } 6... Nc6 7. Bxf4 { We are two moves away from castling long, with a big lead in development and space advantage that gives us a promising initiative. } { [%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] }) (3... d6 { is another good move for Black that's handled poorly below 1600. } 4. d4 { Now Black should hang on to the extra pawn at all costs with 4...g5, but most of the time they let us regain the pawn with Bxf4 for a pleasant advantage. } 4... Bg4 { This pin is quite ineffective. } 5. Bxf4 { We are clearly better, with a dominant centre and better development to boot. Such positions are the dream of any King's Gambit player. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Gb1c3] }) (3... g5 { The old main line, to hang on to the f4-pawn at all costs. It would be more effective if we weren't able to undermine their kingside structure right away. } 4. h4 { Queen's Gambit players may know a similar idea on the other side of the board, where the attempt to hang on to the extra pawn with ...dxc4 and ...b5 is undermined by a2-a4! } 4... g4 5. Ne5 { Now the f4 and g4-pawns are weak, although White is also not without weaknesses (like the h4-pawn), making for a very interesting fight. } 5... d6 { One of Black's best moves, but they don't play it well on the next move. } (5... h5 { is the second most common move, trying to defend g4. But it leaves f4 wanting: } 6. Bc4 Nh6 7. d4 d6 { Our knight is not trapped! } 8. Nd3 { We will regain the pawn on f4 next turn, with a pleasant advantage. } { [%csl Gf4] }) 6. Nxg4 { Now Black should play ...Nf6 or ...Be7, but these moves are rarely seen below 1600. } 6... Bxg4? { Seen in a whopping 50% of games below 1600, this exchange is hugely favourable for White. } 7. Qxg4 { We are ready to capture the f4-pawn, with an extra pawn for nothing. } 7... Nf6 8. Qxf4) 4. d4 { Not just threatening to regain the pawn with Bxf4, but also setting up d5 to kick their knight around like a football. } 4... d5 { You have to give the sub-1600 players some credit for collectively finding a counterattacking move, but it doesn't quite work for Black here. The best move is 4...g5, but it's rarely played, probably because 5.d5 and Qd4 looks so strong. } (4... d6 { is, as usual, too passive after } 5. Bxf4 { , when the massive centre gives White a clear advantage. } { [%cal Gb1c3] }) (4... Nf6 { is a little tricky, but } 5. Qe2 { is a creative reply, neutralizing ...d5 because of the discovered check down the e-file. After } 5... Bb4+ 6. c3 Ba5 7. Bxf4 O-O 8. Nbd2 { , White has the dream centre of pawns on e4/d4 and the development to back it up. It's not such an issue that our f1-bishop is blocked in, because we're castling long next move in any case. } { [%cal Ge1c1] }) 5. exd5 { When they play ...d5, we should generally take it. } 5... Qxd5 6. Nc3 { Much like in the Scandinavian (see Chapter 6), we punish them for developing the queen too early by attacking it with our knight. } 6... Qe6+ { Black really should pin the knight with ...Bb4, but White's doing well even after that. } 7. Be2 { We aren't just blocking the check, but have a threat of our own, that's almost always missed in practice. } 7... Bb4 { Falling into it. } 8. d5 { We fork the queen and knight to win a piece, with a decisive advantage.
Note that there are a few other moves for Black that I didn't cover here, but which will be covered in Exercises 1-6 later. } { [%cal Gd5c6,Gd5e6] } *


[Event "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600: Vs. 1...c5"]
[Date "2025.12.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B22"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Alapin Variation"]
[StudyName "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600"]
[ChapterName "Vs. 1...c5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/w8FPB8TI/RUcNiXZk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2025.12.26"]
[UTCTime "15:54:33"]

1. e4 c5 { The Sicilian Defence is historically the most popular defence to 1.e4 at master level, but you'll only see it about 12% of the time below 1600. Still, the players who do play it below 1600 tend to be a little more experienced, so it's good to have something against it. } { [%cal Gc5d4] } 2. c3 { The Alapin Sicilian, which scores 51.5% for White - which may not seem like much, but when Black already had a tiny plus score in the sub-1600 database after 1...c5, it's a small achievement to tip the odds even slightly back in our favour.
Anyhow, the idea of 2.c3 is to renew the threat of d4, taking over the centre with pawns to establish the 'dream centre' of d4/e4. It's easy to understand, yet Black almost always responds poorly to it below 1600. } (2. Nf3 { followed by the Open Sicilian with d4 is the predominant choice. But Black has a lot of playable defences, so it takes more work to play this way as White. } { [%csl Gc6,Ge6,Gd6][%cal Gd2d4] }) 2... Nc6 { The most common below 1600 (played about 40% of the time), but it plays into our hands. } (2... d6 { , the most common move after 2.Nf3, now looks rather passive after } 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 { , with a very strong centre for free for White, who is already clearly better. A schematic development from here would be Nf3, Bd3 and 0-0, possibly with h3 at some point to avoid a ...Bg4 pin - it may not be absolutely the most critical, but it will make it hard for your opponents to create counterplay. } { [%cal Gg1f3] }) (2... e6 { is a better move than 2...d6, but faces similar issues: } 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 d5 { Black strikes back in the centre in French style. } (4... Nc6 { is actually more common below 1600, but we'll see it via. the 2...Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.cxd4 e6 move order. }) 5. e5 { We have an improved Advance French for White, because Black exchanged on d4 too soon, giving us the active c3-square for our knight. We can even use it immediately: } { [%csl Gc3] } 5... Nc6 6. Nc3 { and the usual ...Qb6 pressure on d4 is less effective when we can eventually kick it away after first Nf3, a3 and then Na4. }) (2... d5 { is one of the main lines for Black at master level, but only seen in 7% of the games. But this chapter was a bit short, so I added the main lines so that you're ready even as you start to face more advanced players (sub-2000). } 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 { Now Black is still playing } 4... cxd4 { in half the games below 1600, and after } 5. cxd4 Nc6 { we transpose to the 2...Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.cxd4 d5 5.exd5 Qxd5 line below. }) (2... Nf6 { is perhaps the most reliable move for Black, but only seen in 5% of games. Still, I've added a few basic ideas for when you start facing players in the 1600-1999 range. } 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3 { We can delay the recapture on d4 to set the opponent more problems. } 5... Nc6 (5... e6 { If they defend the knight, just take back the pawn with } 6. cxd4 { and prepare short castling. } { [%cal Gf1c4,Ge1g1] }) (5... dxc3 { is a blunder after } 6. Qxd5 { , but still seen about 20% of the time at the sub-1600 level. }) 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 { This is a promising gambit (in the style of the Smith-Morra Gambit) that gave me a lot of headaches as Black when I was a junior (even up to around 2200 FIDE). }) 3. d4 { As expected, we occupy the centre with both pawns, negating 1...c5's attempt to stop d4. } 3... cxd4 4. cxd4 { Still keeping the dream centre. } 4... e6 { Seen in about a third of all the games below 1600, but it can also arise via. the 2...e6 move order as noted before. } (4... d5 { This spirited counterattack in the centre also fails to solve Black's problems. } 5. exd5 Qxd5 { Our d4-pawn is under attack, so we defend it. } 6. Nf3 Bg4 { This pin on the knight seems annoying, but we can break the pin. } 7. Be2 { Now we will play for Nc3, d5 and 0-0, with a nice initiative. Note that Black cannot win the d4-pawn: } (7. Nc3 { is also possible, but gets complicated very quickly, whereas Be2 is a lot simpler. }) 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 { loses the queen after first removing the defender: } 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qxd4 { . A lot of players have fallen into this trap below 1600 on Lichess, so it's a good one to know! }) 5. d5 { The most critical, hitting the knight and increasing our space advantage. We also set a couple of nasty traps along the way. } (5. Nc3 d5 6. e5 { is also a decent choice for those who liked the improved Advance French from before. }) 5... exd5 6. exd5 Ne5 { The best move, keeping the knight in the centre. } (6... Nce7 { was actually the most common move in the very early days of the Lichess database (late 2017), but is still seen in nearly a quarter of the game. It loses to } 7. d6 Nc6 8. Qe2+ { , winning a piece as they are forced to block the check with a piece on e7. }) 7. Qe2 { Objectively not the best move, but Black handles it very badly at the sub-1600 level. } (7. Nc3 { gives a small edge for White, as does }) (7. Nf3 { - as you might expect, these moves can be interchanged. }) 7... d6 { A blunder, but seen in half of the games. Black loses a piece after } (7... Qe7 { is a better defence, but the best move is } 8. Be3) (7... Bb4+ { then ...Qe7, after which our queen feels a bit odd on e2. But almost no one finds this in sub-1600 practice. }) 8. f4 { due to the e-file pin. } *


[Event "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600: Vs. 1...e6"]
[Date "2025.12.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C09"]
[Opening "French Defense: Tarrasch Variation, Open System, Main Line"]
[StudyName "The Best 1.e4 Openings For White Below 1600"]
[ChapterName "Vs. 1...e6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/w8FPB8TI/ZV7wP2ex"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2025.12.26"]
[UTCTime "15:56:59"]

1. e4 e6 { The French Defence is only seen in 8% of games below 1600. So we don't need to memorize too much against it, having a natural, practical system will do the trick. } 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 { The Tarrasch Variation, which is only seen 2% of the time below 1600, but scores a neat 53.5% for White. The main idea of this move is that we avoid the pin on the knight with 3.Nc3 Bb4, and can also support our centre with c3 in some lines. } (3. Nc3 Bb4 (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4)) 3... c5 { An unusual case for us where the most common move by the opponent is the best one, exploiting that our d4-pawn is left undefended. But they usually misplay it over the next several moves. } (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { is the Rubinstein Variation, which can also occur via. 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4. I've faced this in a ton of games online and my experience matches pretty well with the Lichess database - that Black almost always misplays it from here. } 4... Nf6 { The most common move by far, but the knight exchange leads to concessions for Black. } 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { The queen is vulnerable to attack here, but the pawn recapture would have permanently damaged Black's structure. } 6. Nf3 { We develop and overprotect our d4-pawn. } 6... Nc6 { The most common move, but the same ideas for White will work against other replies. } 7. Bd3 { We set up two clever traps with this. } 7... Bd6 { After this or most 'normal' moves, we can trap their queen with } (7... Nxd4 { does not win a pawn for Black - } 8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. Bb5+ { discovers the attack on the queen to win it. }) 8. Bg5 { , with an easy win. I've lost count of how many times I've got this queen trap on the board in my online games. }) (3... Nf6 { is seen in about 20% of the games, inviting a closed structure with } 4. e5 Nfd7 { . But this is the best version of the closed structure for White, as the knight is misplaced on d7 and we can overprotect our centre with } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ne2 { . The reason our knight develops to e2, rather than the more natural f3 square, is so that after } { [%csl Ge2,Gd4] } 7... Qb6 { , threatening d4, we have } 8. Nf3 { to guard our pawn with both knights and completely neutralize the pressure on d4. Note that forcing play doesn't really help Black here; after the most common } { [%cal Ge2d4,Gf3d4] } 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 O-O 12. O-O { , White is clearly better as they have better development, the superior bishop by far, and Black is still without real counterplay against our centre. } { [%csl Gd3,Gc8] }) 4. exd5 { Releasing the tension early makes our next several moves easy to play. } 4... exd5 5. Ngf3 { We defend our d4-pawn and prepare to castle short ASAP. } { [%cal Gf1b5,Ge1g1] } 5... Nc6 (5... Nf6 { is just as common, and I have to give some credit to the sub-1600s - they mostly play it well from here as Black. Still, after } 6. Bb5+ Bd7 (6... Nc6 { will be seen via. the 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Nf6 move order. }) 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. O-O Be7 { So that Re1 doesn't come with check. } 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Re1 O-O { Black hasn't made any mistakes to this point, but we still have a pleasant position against their IQP with } 11. Nd4 { , blockading the d5-pawn and potentially setting up attacking ideas with a later Nf5. The engine thinks it's fine for Black, but any human would rather play White. }) 6. Bb5 { Pinning their knight. } 6... Bd7 { I'm not entirely sure why over a third of all sub-1600 players want to break the pin like this, but it works well for us. } (6... Nf6 { This is a bit inaccurate, as Black will run into some problems completing their kingside development. } 7. O-O { We can castle as Black isn't threatening to take our d4-pawn anyway. } 7... Be7 8. dxc5 { As usual, we want to exchange on c5 once they move their king's bishop. Either they let us hang on to the extra pawn with Nb3, or they lose time taking it back, as we'll see. } 8... Bxc5 9. Re1+ Be6 { Now White should be slightly precise to prove their advantage: } (9... Be7 10. Qe2 { is very unpleasant for Black as they can't castle: } { [%cal Ge2e8,Gb5c6] } 10... O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Qxe7 { wins a piece. }) 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nbd4 { and the pins against c6 and e6 give us a strong initiative. } { [%cal Gb5c6,Gb5e8] }) (6... Bd6 { is the main line in master play, but only seen 2% of the time at the sub-1600 level. }) 7. O-O { Now Black is not in time to deal with the Re1 check effectively. } 7... Nf6 8. Re1+ Be7 9. dxc5 { Black is unable to recapture the c5-pawn, due to the pin. } { [%cal Ge1e8] } 9... O-O 10. Nb3 { White is up a pawn, and Black is without compensation for it. } { [%csl Gc5] } *


