1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann is only seen in 5% of all games at the sub-1600 level, compared to 8% in the master database. But it's a very serious system and it also scores the best for Black in the Lichess sub-1600 database. So it's a good idea to have something against it that shifts the practical advantage back to us. } 2. d4 d5 3. f3 { The Fantasy Variation, which scores 52.5% for White - a big improvement from 48.5% after 1...c6! I believe part of the reason it's so effective is because the main idea of the Caro-Kann is to actively develop the c8-bishop, and our last move stops that plan. } (3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 { is the old main line. }) (3. Nd2 { is shown as scoring the best, but after } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { it just transposes to 3.Nc3 anyway, so that's why I recommended 3.f3. }) 3... dxe4 { Seen in nearly half the games, but now White obtains the 'dream centre'. } (3... e6 { is a solid move for Black, seen about 16% of the time. I suggest } 4. Nc3 { when we get a French-style position where I feel f3 is slightly more useful than c6, as it means that our centre is shored up against the standard tries of ...Bb4 or ...Nf6. } { [%cal Gf3e4] }) (3... Nf6 { leads to an improved French structure for White after } 4. e5 Nfd7 5. c3 { . Our f3-pawn may look a bit out of place for now, but we can remedy that easily with f4 and Nf3. And compared to the Tarrasch French with 3...Nf6 that we saw last chapter, Black is much slower to attack our centre. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf3f4,Gg1f3] }) 4. fxe4 { The one thing we need to be careful about here is the open e1-h4 diagonal, but once that's taken care of, Black will be the one under attack. } { [%cal Gh4e1] } 4... e5 { This is the only good reply for Black. It's seen about 1/5th of the time below 1600 but is the main line at master level, so I've shared a few ideas to help you play White's attack. } { [%cal Gd8h4] } (4... Nf6 { is seen in nearly half the games, but White is much better after the next move, taking the initiative. I've made it a sideline despite being more common as there's a lot less for White to know here in comparison. } 5. e5! { The key move, taking the centre with tempo like in the Alekhine. } 5... Nd5 6. c4 Nb6 7. Nc3 { White is much better with the strong centre an can develop normally to consolidate that advantage. } { [%cal Gg1f3,Gc1e3,Gf1e2,Ge1g1] }) 5. Nf3! { A good move to remember - we stop the true threat of ...Qh4 and intend to play it as a promising gambit with our lead in development. } 5... exd4 (5... Bg4 { is also popular, but } 6. c3 { is a good reply, shoring up our centre so that we keep the 'dream centre' after exd4 cxd4. } { [%cal Gc3d4] }) 6. Bc4 { Our subsequent 'focus fire' on f7 is quite similar in spirit to the King's Gambit, and it helps that we keep an advantage even if Black defends correctly (spoiler alert: they usually don't). } 6... Bg4 { The most common move by a small margin, but unlike after the previous move, here it's just a blunder. } (6... Nf6 { A better defence (seen 21% of the time), but even this won't solve Black's problems. } 7. O-O { We castle, as it would be suicidal to take on e4 and open the floodgates to f7. } 7... Bc5 { The most common (seen in 33% of the games) but a bit of a tactical error, as the next sequence shows. This is already a bit more advanced as even a lot of players in the 1600-1999 range fall for this trap as Black, but I'll show it anyway. } 8. Ng5 { The key move, setting up the attack on f7. } 8... O-O { Now we win material with a tactic: } 9. Bxf7+ Rxf7 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Qh5+ { They can't take our queen because of the pin on the knight! } { [%cal Gf1f7] } 11... Kg8 12. Qxc5 { White is up the exchange, with a winning position. }) 7. Bxf7+ { A typical trick in these open positions. } 7... Kxf7 8. Ne5+ { We regain the piece with a decisive attack on Black's uncastled king. } { [%cal Gd1g4] } *


