1. e4 e5 { The Open Games - you'll face it in half your games, which is why there are 6 Exercises for it! } 2. f4 (2. Nf3 { This is the main line at master level, but in this repertoire I am recommending the King's Gambit with 2.f4. }) 2... exf4 { Black accepts our gambit. } 3. Nf3 { We prevent ...Qh4 and prepare to regain our sacrificed pawn with d4/Bxf4. If we achieve this, we will dominate the centre. } 3... Nc6 { The knight is misplaced here, as you may recall from the analysis before. } 4. d4 { We establish the 'dream centre' with pawns on d4 and e4 and threaten to regain the pawn with Bxf4 next move. } 4... d5 { Black counterattacks in the centre! } 5. exd5 { Luring their queen into the open. } 5... Qxd5 6. Nc3 { A great move, attacking the queen with tempo. } (6. Bxf4 { Regaining the pawn is not bad, since 6...Qe4 7.Qe2! saves our bishop with the pin to the king - well done if you spotted that. But my recommended move gives us more of an initiative by attacking their queen with tempo. }) 6... Qe6+ 7. Be2 { We block the check and develop. } 7... Nf6 { A new move for us, but the ideas are the same as usual for White. } 8. d5 { Winning a piece! } 8... Qe7 9. dxc6 *


