1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e5 Ng4 { This semi-common move is far trickier than I initially realized, so I included it as an Exercise. } 5. h3 { It's important to kick away the knight immediately, to avoid d4 Ne3 ideas. But this only works because of 5...Nxe5 6.Qe2! and then d4 to win the knight - so bonus points if you saw that when playing 5.h3! } (5. d4 { This move doesn't work as well because Black can play ...d6 or ...Ne3 to mess up our plans a bit. }) 5... Nh6 { A sad retreat, but there's nothing better. } (5... Nxe5 6. Qe2! { is a key to making 5.h3 work - well done if you saw this intermezzo to win a piece! } { [%cal Gd2d4,Ge2e8] }) 6. d4 { We occupy the centre and threaten Bxf4 to regain our pawn. } 6... d6 7. Bxf4 { White is somewhat better with their central space. While the variations can get somewhat interesting after 7...dxe5, there are too many good options for White from there to keep an edge, so it doesn't really fit as an exercise. } *


