1. e4 e5 2. f4 d5 { This is a bit of a tricky move, so even though it's only seen 5% of the time below 1600, I've made sure to cover it briefly in this exercise! } 3. exd5 (3. fxe5 { Please don't fall for this! 3...Qh4 is totally winning for Black. }) (3. Nf3 { This isn't as good here due to 3...dxe4, deal with that threat first. }) 3... exf4 { The best move, although advanced players will likely want to check 3...Qxd5, 3...e4 and the very tricky 3...c6!? in their own time later. } (3... Qxd5 4. Nc3) (3... e4 4. d3 Nf6 5. dxe4 Nxe4 6. Nf3 Bc5 7. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2e8] }) (3... c6 4. Qe2 cxd5 5. fxe5 Nc6 6. Nf3) 4. Nf3 { It's important to prevent ...Qh4. We'll gain a lot of time on their queen if they take on d5 } 4... Qxd5 (4... Nf6 { is the move played at master level, but rarely seen below 1600. } 5. c4 { is one decent reply, not so much to hang on to d5 but rather to buy time to develop and use our central space in the middlegame. } { [%cal Gd2d4,Gb1c3,Gf1d3,Ge1g1] }) 5. Nc3 { We attack their queen with tempo. } (5. d4 { This is playable but 5...Bd6 is a good defence to hang on to f4. Try attacking their queen first }) 5... Qe6+ 6. Be2 Nf6 { This is not the best move by Black, but it is the most common below 1600. } 7. O-O Bc5+ { This is not a good move at all (depsite being played 46% of the time below 1600), but why? } 8. d4 { We attack the bishop with tempo! } 8... Bb6 9. Bb5+ { A great move to prepare Re1 winning the queen. } (9. Bxf4 { This is good too, but look for a way to open up the e-file for our rook }) (9. Re1 { This gives Black time to castle, so throw in a check first }) 9... c6 10. Re1 { Black loses the queen for not enough material compensation. } *


