1. e4 c5 { Now we move on to the Sicilian! I've only included 1 exercise for each of the remaining chapters because you won't face any of these moves individually more than 12% of the time below 1600 on Lichess } 2. c3 { We prepare d4 to take over the centre and set up the 'dream centre' of pawns on d4 and e4! } (2. Nf3 { This is the main line, but I'm recommending the Alapin Variation with 2.c3 here }) 2... Nc6 { Now it's time to take the centre with our pawns! } 3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 e6 5. d5 (5. Nc3 { This is a reasonable choice, but I'm giving the more ambitious 5.d5 for this Exercise }) (5. Nf3 { This is a reasonable choice, but I'm giving the more ambitious 5.d5 for this Exercise }) 5... exd5 6. exd5 { Now all of Black's knight moves have problems. In this Exercise we'll see the worst of them } 6... Nce7 { Black shuts in his own kingside pieces, which we can immediately punish! } 7. d6 Nf5 { I didn't cover this move in the analysis, but we meet it the same way as usual. } 8. Qe2+ Nge7 9. dxe7 *


