1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 { This is not a common move below 1600, but it's popular at higher levels, so I've included it as an Exercise. } 3. exd5 { We should take their pawn so that they don't have two pawns side by side in the centre. } 3... Qxd5 4. d4 (4. Nf3 { This is also decent, intending d4 next move. Now play 4.d4. }) 4... cxd4 { This capture is dubious, as after the recapture we can kick away their queen with tempo via. Nc3. Advanced players will play 4...Nf6 or 4...Nc6 instead, but we can still get into the game with a decent position with a simple Nf3/Be2/0-0 setup in the worst case. } 5. cxd4 Nc6 { Attacking our d4-pawn! } 6. Nf3 { We defend our pawn and prepare to kick their queen away with Nc3, which is a good reply to moves like 6...e5, 6...e6 or 6...Nf6. } (6. Be3 { This runs into some small problems after 6...e5, defend the pawn with your knight instead }) (6. Ne2 { This is too passive, blocking in our f1-bishop. Play 6.Nf3 instead as the Exercise will show why we don't have to fear the ...Bg4 pin. }) (6. Nc3 { A bit too early because we lose a pawn after 6...Qxd4. Defend the d4-pawn first }) 6... Bg4 7. Be2 { We break the pin, as it turns out Black can't just win a pawn with ...Bxf3 and ...Qxd4. } (7. Nc3 { This is a good alternative but it gets very messy after 7...Bxf3. Play 7.Be2 instead to keep things simpler, it turns out you aren't losing a pawn there }) (7. Be3 { This is too passive as we're letting them double our pawns with ...Bxf3. Play 7.Be2 instead } { [%cal Gg4f3] }) 7... Bxf3 (7... e6 { is better but we can still play Nc3/0-0/h3 for a good game in this IQP position where they developed their queen a little bit early } { [%cal Gb1c3,Ge1g1,Gh2h3] }) 8. Bxf3 Qxd4 { A blunder, but Black was already in bad shape. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4d5] } 9. Bxc6+ { Removing the defender with an intermezzo! } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6e8] } 9... bxc6 10. Qxd4 { We won their queen and have a trivial win. } *


