[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann! Do you remember what to do when they don't put a pawn in the centre or attack our e4-pawn? } 2. d4 { Yessir, we occupy the centre with both pawns. } 2... d5 3. f3 (3. e5 { The Advance Variation, which is the main line at master play. But I recommend the Fantasy Variation with 3.f3 for this repertoire }) (3. exd5 { This is a safe option, but I recommend the Fantasy Variation with 3.f3 for this repertoire }) (3. Nc3 { The old main line and not a bad choice at all. But I recommend the Fantasy Variation with 3.f3 for this repertoire }) (3. Nd2 { This is similar to 3.Nc3, now play the Fantasy with 3.f3 }) 3... dxe4 4. fxe4 { We're ready to meet ...Nf6 with e5 to take even more central space. } 4... e5 5. Nf3 (5. dxe5 { This is a mistake because of 5...Qh4, and our king is too weak in the centre }) 5... exd4 { Black took our pawn, now how do we develop? } 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 { This leads to a slightly worse endgame after 6...Qxd4 due to our isolated e4-pawn. Look for a more dynamic approach where we complete our kingside development fast }) (6. Nxd4 { We have to watch out for ...Qh4 forks when we moved our f-pawn! Just like in the King's Gambit }) 6... Bg4 { This pin is common, but not a good idea - can you show why? } 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Ne5+ (8. Ng5+ { This is not the same as 8.Ne5 because after 8...Qxg5! Black will be up a piece when the exchanges conclude. } 8... Qxg5 9. Bxg5 Bxd1 10. Kxd1 Nd7) 8... Ke8 { I stopped earlier in the analysis, but i've gone a bit further in this Exercise so you know how to finish off the game. } 9. Qxg4 (9. Nxg4 { This is safe, but taking with the queen gives us a greater attack. }) 9... Nf6 { How to continue the attack on Black's king? } 10. Qe6+ { A great move - 10...Be7 11.Qf7 would be an immediate checkmate. } 10... Qe7 11. Qc8+ { This wins material by force. } 11... Qd8 12. Qxd8+ (12. Qxb7 { Also good, now play 12.Qxd8 and the knight fork }) (12. Qe6+ { Also good, now play 12.Qxd8 and the knight fork }) 12... Kxd8 { It's important to find the next move here as White! } 13. Nf7+ { The rook in the corner's a goner! } 13... Ke8 14. Nxh8 { White is up a rook and easily winning. } *


