1. e4 d5 { The Scandinavian! What do we do when our e4-pawn is under attack right away? } 2. exd5 { We take the pawn, naturally. } (2. e5 { isn't a great idea because after } 2... c5 { our e5-pawn comes under attack quickly and Black gets a super-charged Caro-Kann/French type position. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gb8c6,Gc8g4] }) 2... Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 { A bit passive, but also the most common move online by a fair margin. } 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 { Black is trying to play solidly - how might we place our bishops from here? } 6. Bd3 (6. Bg5 { This move order works just as well - now play 6.Bd3 }) 6... Be7 { Breaking the pin - now what? } 7. Bg5 (7. O-O { This is definitely possible too, but I'd rather castle long and attack their king in the middlegame, so play 7.Bg5 }) 7... O-O { Their king seems safe - for now. How should we develop from here? } 8. Qd2 (8. Qe2 { The queen is also reasonably placed here, but I prefer the queen on d2 to take the sting out of ...h6 }) (8. O-O { Safe, but not so consistent with 7.Bg5 - play 8.Qd2 instead }) 8... h6 { Not a good move - but do you remember why? } 9. Bxh6 { I love this bishop sacrifice, ripping open Black's king! Black really shouldn't take our bishop, but if they don't, they are a pawn down with a bad position. } (9. h4 { This is a creative 'Fishing Pole' attacking idea to open the h-file, but did you consider that Black is not forced to take on g5? Points for creativity, but 9.Bxh6 is already a winning attack for White, so play it } { [%cal Gh4g5,Gh6g5] }) 9... gxh6 10. Qxh6 { I covered the position to this point in the Analysis, but there's a tricky defence for Black that I want to test you on. It will help you not just with the repertoire but with your attacking skills in general! } 10... Re8 { White to play! This one requires some precision so take your time on it! } 11. Ng5 { A great move, preparing Bh7. In fact, it's already a forced mate. } (11. O-O-O { You're missing a forced mate, besides ...Bf8-g7 now keeps the king somewhat safe for Black and we are a piece down after all! }) 11... Bf8 { How to deal with the attack on our queen? } 12. Bh7+ { Great move! } { [%cal Gf6h7,Gh6h7] } 12... Kh8 13. Nxf7# { Checkmate! It's obviously not a guarantee by any means that we will checkmate them in 13 moves or less with our repertoire, but it's certainly a nice demonstration of what we're aiming for with our opening! } *


