1. e4 d6 { You won't face the Pirc a ton, but I still included an exercise with it, as people often feel a bit lost when facing it at first. } 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 (3. Bd3 { This is playable, going for a Geller Setup with Nf3, 0-0, c3 and Re1. But I recommend the more critical 3.Nc3 } { [%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1,Gc2c3,Gf1e1] }) 3... g6 { The main line Pirc. } 4. Be3 (4. Nf3 { This is playable too, but I recommend 4.Be3 }) (4. f4 { Also an ambitious approach, but I recommend 4.Be3 }) (4. Bg5 { Playable but I recommend 4.Be3 as being a bit more flexible }) (4. Bf4 { Playable but I recommend 4.Be3 as being a bit more flexible }) 4... Bg7 5. Qd2 (5. Nf3 { A reasonable alternative, but I recommend 5.Qd2 as the most flexible move }) (5. f3 { A reasonable alternative, but I recommend 5.Qd2 as the most flexible move. Since 5...Ng4 6.Bg5 doesn't lead anywhere for Black }) 5... O-O 6. O-O-O (6. f3 { This avoids ...Ng4 but this exercise will show you why you don't need to fear it. Play 6.0-0-0 }) 6... Ng4 { A new move for us - it's relatively rare for your opponents to play ...Ng4 but it's a question you're likely to ask at some point, so let's see how to deal with it and why this really isn't scary for us at all. } { [%cal Gh4h5] } 7. Bg5 { A nice move to leave their g4-knight a bit stranded. If 7...h6 8.Bh4 or 8.Bf4 and they don't really have a good follow-up. } { [%csl Gg4] } (7. Bf4 { Also playable but I like 7.Bg5 slightly more }) (7. h4 { A creative engine alternative, but 98% of the time you don't want to trade your DSB for their knight in the king's fianchetto systems, so play 7.Bg5 } { [%cal Gh5g6,Gh4h5] }) 7... f6 { Attacking our bishop - what now? } 8. Bh4 (8. Bf4 { This is also playable but we can play 8.Bh4 safely as 8...Bh6 doesn't win our queen }) 8... Bh6 9. f4 { We have blocked the check and threaten h3 to win their estranged g4-knight. } (9. Bc4+ { We can't get away with this intermezzo as 9...d5! 10.Bxd5 e6 crashes the party }) 9... e5 { A final attempt to stir things up with the attack on f4. } 10. Nge2 { We have covered the attack on f4 and enjoy a huge advantage. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh4f2,Gh2h3] } (10. dxe5 { This is also good, now play 10.Nge2 }) (10. Bc4+ { Not the best but not bad either, White is still much better. Now play 10.Nge2 }) (10. Bg3 { Not the best but not bad either, White is still much better. Now play 10.Nge2 }) *


