{ Let's see if you remember the Geller Setup! }
1. e4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 { We defend our bishop with the bishop. } (3. Nc3 { This is also fine, but it allows Black to somewhat justify their setup with ...e6 and the ...Bb4 pin, which is easier to just avoid }) 3... Nf6 4. Qe2 { I recommend this queen move because it allows us to still play the Geller Setup which is easy to play and remember. } (4. e5 { We have to be careful and make sure we played Nf3 before e5 because now ...Bxg2 wins our rook on h1! }) (4. Nf3 { I tricked you with the move order - Black wins a pawn now with 4...Nxe4. So defend your pawn first }) (4. Nc3 { Also a decent defence of the e4-pawn, now play 4.Qe2 }) (4. Nd2 { Also a decent defence of the e4-pawn, now play 4.Qe2 }) (4. f3 { Technically playable, but I'd rather develop a piece while defending e4 }) 4... e6 5. Nf3 (5. c3 { Also part of the Geller Setup, but 5.Nf3 is more flexible so start with that }) (5. Nh3 { The knight is on the edge here, it's not that bad but 5.Nf3 fits better with our setup }) 5... Be7 { A new move for us - how would you deal with it? } 6. O-O (6. e5 { This is actually the best move, well done! But the purpose of this exercise is to help you remember the Geller Setup which works against almost anything they do, so play 6.0-0 }) (6. c4 { Also not bad, now play 6.0-0 to continue the Geller Setup }) 6... O-O 7. c3 (7. c4 { An interesting alternative to grab more space in the style of the Queen's Gambit. Now play 7.c3 }) (7. Re1 { Also fits with the Geller Setup, now play 7.c3 }) (7. Nbd2 { Also fits with the Geller Setup, now play 7.c3 }) (7. e5 { Also works here, now play 7.c3 }) 7... d6 8. Nbd2 { We have completed the Geller Setup and enjoy a clear advantage with our extra space and no bad pieces. Our attacking plan will start with e5 and bringing our pieces over steadily toward their king. } (8. e5 { A really promising alternative to start an attack against their king. Now play 8.Nbd2 }) (8. Re1 { Also fits with the Geller Setup, but I slightly prefer 8.Nbd2 first as being more flexible }) (8. h3 { Sometimes you see this move in the Geller Setup, but play 8.Nbd2 first as it's a bit more useful }) *


