{ I'll use this game to answer questions on the lines in the Study }
1. e4 e5 (1... Nf6 { Not so much a question but someone suggested the Exchange Variation as a possible alternative against the Alekhine. It's also fine, I've recommended it in the past. } 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 { Black does have a small plus score in Lichess, probably because Black's plans are quite clear (pressure d4). } { [%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] } 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O { This approach works quite well for White though, as we've stopped ...Bg4 to increase the pressure on d4. ...e5 is well met by the unpleasant intermediate move Bg5! and ...d5 is well met by c5, so Black struggles a little bit to get a central pawn break and thus direct counterplay. } { [%csl Gd5,Gc5][%cal Ge7e5,Gc1g5] }) 2. f4 Nf6 { Alixxy's question: Should we meet 2...Nf6 with 3.d3 or 3.Nc3?
MI: Both moves to defend e4 are playable but I'd recommend } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gd2d3] } 3. fxe5 { (we can play this now that ...Qh4 is impossible) } 3... Nxe4 4. Nf3 { as Black has to find a quite difficult move not to end up in a bad position } 4... Ng5! { Only this move (preparing ...Nxf3 and ...Qh4+) gives Black a reasonable game. Against more common moves on Lichess like } (4... d5 5. d3 Nc5 6. d4 Ne4 7. Bd3 { we get a much better game with our strong centre and fast development. }) *


