1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 { Black plays the King's Indian, but we can still play the 'same' Catalan setup. } 3. g3 (3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { is just a transposition. }) 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 { Anish Giri recently quipped 'you can have equality or winning chances against the Fianchetto Variation, but not both'. } 5... d6 6. O-O { White has secured his king against a potential kingside attack by 'building a home' for his king on the kingside. Meanwhile, the g2-bishop is on a beautiful open diagonal, and the pawns on c4 and d4 give White a small space advantage. } *


