1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 { We will consider 4...dxc4 later. } 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 (6... dxc4 { is Black's best move, releasing the central tension so that he can subsequently place his light-squared bishop (his most passive piece in the Catalan) on the long diagonal later with ...b5/...b6 and ...Bb7. }) 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 { White positions his pieces to support the e4 break, placing a third pawn in the battle for the centre. } (8. Nc3 { is weaker: } 8... dxc4 { makes it tricky for White to regain his c4-pawn. }) 8... b6 9. e4 { White is slightly better, as he either gets a nice French structure after e5/cxd5, or after } 9... dxe4 { Next chapter, I will explain what transpires if Black keeps the central tension (i.e. doesn't play ...dxe4 or ...dxc4) } (9... dxc4 10. Nxc4 { sees White obtain the 'dream centre' with pawns on d4 and e4. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd4][%cal Gf1d1] }) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Bb7 12. Rd1 { , White has an obvious space advantage, and the pressure down the long diagonal makes it hard for Black to achieve his thematic freeing ...c5 break. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf3][%cal Gc1f4,Ga1c1] } *


[Event "The Basic Catalan: 2025 Update - An Improved French Structure"]
[Date "2025.10.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E09"]
[Opening "Catalan Opening: Closed, Main Line"]
[StudyName "The Basic Catalan"]
[ChapterName "2025 Update - An Improved French Structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/x75NW8ek/ZV0EL7NV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2025.10.21"]
[UTCTime "23:56:26"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 { We already saw these moves in Chapter 4. } 9... Bb7 { But what if Black keeps the tension? } (9... Ba6 { may be met with } 10. b3 { to neutralize the pin on the c4-pawn. } { [%cal Ga6c4] }) 10. e5 { We transiition to an improved French Defence structure. } 10... Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 { The usual recapture, when we have a pawn structure resembling the French Defence (d4/e5 vs. d5/e6). However, the reason that structure works for Black in the French is that he has pressure against our d4-pawn with moves like ...Nc6/...Qb6/...Nh6-f5, which is clearly not the case here. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gd5,Ge6] } (11... exd5 12. Re1 Nc7 13. Nf1 { gives White healthy play with his central majority and space advantage. He will obtain excellent attacking chances with a subsequent Ne3-f5, exploiting the square left behind by the prior ...exd5. } { [%cal Gf1e3,Ge3f5] }) 12. Re1 { We play Re1 so that if Black tries to challenge our centre with ...f6, we discover an attack on the e6-pawn after exf6. Furthermore, it gives our knight a nice square on f1 in some lines, enabling us to develop our queenside. } { [%csl Gf1,Gc1,Gd2][%cal Ge1e6] } 12... Rc8 { Where do you think the queen should move from here? } 13. Qa4 { This was recommended in Avrukh's 'GM Repertoire' many years ago, attacking the a7-pawn to not give Black time for ...Qc7-c2, as the exchange of queens would help Black to negate White's space advantage. } (13. Qd1 { is also possible, but after } 13... Qc7 { we need to know a rather difficult move: } 14. Nb1! { with the idea that } 14... Qc2 { now fails to } 15. Qxc2 Rxc2 { [%csl Gc2] } 16. Nc3 { , trapping the rook. But 14.Nb1 is a very easy move to forget (or think you misremembered), so it's more practical to just avoid the whole ...Qc7-c2 idea with 13.Qa4. } { [%csl Gc2] }) 13... a5 14. Nf1 Ba6 15. Qd1 { White is clearly better, and will continue with a kingside attack in the spirit of the King's Indian Attack vs. the French, with h4, Bf4, Ne3 (or N1h2), Ng5 and so forth. Note that } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gc1f4] } 15... Qc7 { is no longer effective, as we can easily prevent the liquidating ...Qc2 with } 16. Ne3 { , in the worst case. } *


