[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/x75NW8ek/9xNoY6I5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2019.01.07"]
[UTCTime "12:55:27"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 (5. Qa4+ { regains the pawn, but loses some time with the queen. It's more critical to leave the pawn for now and continue with our setup. }) 5... a6 { Black plays this move to meet Qa4 with ...b5, defending his c4-pawn. } (5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 a5 { is a major line, which was played in the Anand-Topalov match. } 7. Qc2 { is a good reply, hitting the c4-pawn and intending } 7... b5?! 8. a4 { to undermine Black's central structure. }) (5... Nc6 6. Qa4 { is a typical reply, to regain the c4-pawn. } 6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Nd5 8. Qb5 { White obtains very good compensation for the pawn after } 8... Bxd2+ 9. Nbxd2 c3 10. bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qd3 Nd5 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfc1 { , much in the spirit of the Benko Gambit - his rooks have open lines, he dominates the centre, and it's not easy for Black to relieve the piece pressure after e.g. Ne4-c5. }) 6. O-O b5 { Black tries to hang on to the pawn, but at the price of falling well behind in development, and weakening the long diagonal. } 7. Ne5 { A thematic move in this opening, unleashing the strength of the g2-bishop. } 7... Nd5 8. a4 { We undermine Black's structure as close to the base of the pawn chain as possible. } 8... Bb7 9. b3 { An interesting idea, sacrificing a pawn to accelerate White's development and open the position. } 9... cxb3 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Qxb3 { White has some initiative for the pawn already. } 12... c6 13. e4 Nc7 14. Be3 { I prefer White's position despite the pawn deficit, as the c6-pawn is weak, Black has no pawn break, and White can easily increase the pressure with Rc1/Nd2. } *


