1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5 6. O-O Nc6 { We saw a similar setup in Game 3, but here the inclusion of 0-0/...e6 gives White some extra ways to deal with the pressure on d4. } 7. Qa4 { We can ignore Black's threat, much in the spirit of the Grunfeld. } 7... cxd4 (7... Bd7 8. Qxc4 { regains the pawn, with some theory after both 8...cxd4 and the dynamic 8...b5. }) 8. Nxd4 { Discovering an attack on c6. } 8... Qxd4 9. Bxc6+ Bd7 { How should we deal with the threat of Bxc6? } (9... bxc6 10. Qxc6+ { wins the rook on a8. }) 10. Rd1 { A nice move - we can ignore Black's threat with a threat of our own! } 10... Bxc6 11. Qxc6+ { The whole point. } 11... bxc6 12. Rxd4 Rd8 13. Rxc4 { White's position is strategically superior, as Black is saddled with two isolated pawns on the queenside. } *


