1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6 7. e3 Bd7 8. Qe2 b5 9. b3 cxb3 10. axb3 Bd6 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Rc1 { White has very good positional compensation for the pawn, as Black's a6 and c7 pawns are backward, weak and hard to advance. Meanwhile, White has a very harmonious piece placement, and can increase the pressure with Nd2 followed by Ne5(e1)-d3-c5. } *


