1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 (3... c6 4. Bg2 d5 { This is a very solid setup for Black, and the main choice at the elite level. } { [%cal Gg1f3,Gc4d5] }) 4. Bg2 d5 { Usually the Grunfeld is based on playing ...Nxd5xc3, saddling White with a backward c3-pawn. However, in this line, there is no knight for Black to capture on c3. } 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3 { White can claim a slightly improved version of a normal Grunfeld, as his structure is more solid and Black wasn't able to achieve his usual ...c5 break. } 9... Re8 { A waiting move, preparing ...e5. } { [%cal Ga2a3,Gh2h3,Gd1e2,Gf1e1,Gd4d5] } (9... e5 { is well met by } 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 { , with a good version of a King's Indian Defence, as White's c-pawn was already traded for Black's d-pawn, plus Black's knights are both misplaced in this structure, dominated by White's pawns on light squares. Note that the ...f5 break that's so typical for the KID would be asking for trouble after Ng5-e6. }) 10. Nh4 { This was Avrukh's recommendation in his 'GM Repertoire 2A: 1.d4' book, with the idea of either preventing ...e5 with f4, or meeting ...e5 with d5/e4, as we saw in the previous note. } { [%cal Gf2f4] } *


[Event "The Basic Catalan: The Main Line"]
[Date "2019.01.07"]
