{ The Catalan can also be played from other move orders, though as usual, they have both merits and disadvantages. }
1. d4 (1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 { This move order can be used to try and reach Catalan type positions. But Black can play ...c5 or ...e5 for an entirely different game, in English territory. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] }) (1. Nf3 Nf6 (1... d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 { would be a Grunfeld with a strong extra tempo! } 4... Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. c4 { then transposes back into Catalan territory. } { [%cal Gc4d5,Gd5c4] }) 2. g3 (2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 { This position is a Neo-Catalan, where White has gone without d4. One advantage of this move order is that } { [%csl Gd2,Gd4] } 4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ { is a bit more effective here than after 1.d4, as after } 5... Nbd7 6. Qxc4 { White has some extra options connected with delaying d4, or even spurning it altogether in favour of d3. } { [%cal Gd2d3,Gd2d4] }) 2... d5 3. Bg2 { This is the King's Indian Attack. } 3... c6 (3... c5 4. O-O Nc6 5. c4 d4 { In this move order, White couldn't get in both d4 and c4, because Black met c4 with ...d4, reaching a Benoni structure with colours reversed. }) 4. O-O Bg4 { White can still play d4 and c4 in this opening, though it would not be an exact transposition to the Catalan, because Black played a unique Slav setup. } { [%cal Gd2d4,Gc2c4] }) 1... Nf6 (1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 { This move order is considered a bit too permissive. } 3... c5 (3... Bf5 { and playing it like a Slav is also very sensible. } { [%cal Ge7e6,Gc7c6,Gb8d7] }) 4. Bg2 cxd4 { Black gets a nice version of a reversed Grunfeld, as after } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 5. Nxd4 e5 { White loses a lot of time moving his knight, unlike a Grunfeld, where White could play Nxc6/c4 without loss of time. } { [%cal Gb8c6,Gd4c6] }) 2. Nf3 (2. c4 e6 { White could play either 3.Nf3 or 3.g3 to reach the Catalan, though they allow different options for Black. }) 2... e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 (4... b5 { is an extra option in this move order, preventing c4 and forcing White to come up with another plan, such as } 5. O-O Nbd7 6. a4 { [%cal Gb5b4,Gc2c4] }) 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 { We have transposed to the 4...Be7 Catalan. } *


