1. d4 Nf6 (1... f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. c4 d5 5. Nf3 (5. Nh3!? { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gh3f4] }) 5... c6 6. O-O Bd6 { The Catalan can be used against the Stonewall Dutch (as Black played here). Note that our bishop on g2 is a bit stuck against Black's wall of pawns on the light squares. } { [%csl Gg2,Gd5,Gc6,Gb7,Ge6][%cal Gg2d5] } 7. b3 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc1a3,Ga3d6] } 7... Qe7 { White has a few options here, each leading to an interesting strategic battle } 8. Ne5 { [%cal Gb7b6,Gg2a8] } (8. Bb2 { [%cal Gb1d2] }) (8. a4 { Insisting on the trade of the dark-squared bishops, albeit at the price of weakening b4. } { [%csl Gd6,Ga3][%cal Gc1a3,Ga3d6] }) (8. Bf4 { Forcing the trade of bishops, but at the price of loosening the kingside after } 8... Bxf4 9. gxf4 { [%csl Gg1,Gf4] })) 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 (6... Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Bb7 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. Rd1 Qc8 { Do you see a strong positional idea for White in this middlegame? Hint: What is Black's next move? } 13. c5! { Yes, we give d5 for the knight, but we prevent the freeing ...c5 break, fix c6 as a weak pawn, and maintain our grip over the centre, which is more important. } 13... Nd5 14. a3 { [%csl Ge5,Gc5][%cal Gf3e5,Gb2b4] }) 7. Qc2 b6 { This is a very reasonable line, known as the Bukavshin Variation. The idea is to play ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5, balancing the position in the centre. } 8. Ne5 Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 { Black has good compensation for the exchange, as Qxc4 runs into ...Ba6 and e2 is hit by the skewer. See Ding-Caruana, FIDE Candidates 2018. } *


