1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 (3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 { If White wants to meet ...Bb4 with Nd2, this is the better move order, as } 5... dxc4?? { would now lose a piece to } 6. Qa4+! Nc6 7. Bxc6+! bxc6 8. Qxb4) 3... d5 4. g3 Bb4+ { This is a very popular line at the Grandmaster level. The point only becomes evident some moves later.
You're unlikely to see this system below the 2000 FIDE level, but if you really want to avoid this system, you can play a move order from Chapter 10 that delays either d4 or c4 past move 4. } 5. Bd2 Be7 { This may appear to lose a tempo, but the point is that the bishop on d2 interferes with the plan of Qc2/Nbd2/e4 that we saw in Chapter 4. } (5... a5 { is a popular line among modern Indian GMs, and can in fact transpose to the 4...dxc4 5.Bg2 Bb4 6.Bd2 a5 lines after } { [%cal Ga5b4,Ga8a1] } 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O (7. Qc2 { avoids that transposition, but then } { [%cal Gc2c4] } 7... c5 { becomes more effective, with a lot of modern computer theory from here. } { [%cal Gc8c2] }) 7... dxc4) (5... Bd6 { is the Ukranian Variation, which plays in a Semi-Slav style, but again avoiding the plan of Nbd2 and e4. } { [%cal Gc7c6,Gb8d7,Ge8g8] } 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Bg5 { is in turn an interesting attempt to exploit Black's move order, in case one is not satisfied with the standard development. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge2e4] }) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Qc2 b6 { In the other variation we were playing Nbd2 and e4 to take the centre, but here that is not possible. } { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gb1d2] } (8... Nbd7 { will often (but not always) be followed with ...b6 anyhow. } { [%cal Ga7a5] } 9. Bf4 b6 10. Rd1 { would then transpose to 8...b6. }) 9. Rd1 { This move may appear enigmatic, but it helps in some lines to have the rook opposite the opponent's queen for potential tactical blows. See the note to move 11 for such an example. } { [%cal Gd1d8] } 9... Nbd7 10. Bf4 { The most active diagonal for our bishop.
Now Black can choose where to develop their bishop, but White's plan is the same in both instances - to obtain the bishop pair advantage. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gc8b7,Gc8a6] } 10... Bb7 (10... Ba6 11. Ne5! { This is the key move to remember in this setup, preparing cxd5 and Nc6. } { [%cal Ge5c6] } 11... Rc8 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d8,Gc6e7] } 13... Nh5 14. Bc1 Nb8 { [%cal Gc8c2] } 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qd2 { The position is objectively equal, but White can slowly press for a win without much risk, due to his bishop pair advantage. } { [%cal Gb2b3,Gc1a3,Gb1c3] } (16. Nc3 { seems more natural, and is certainly not a bad move. But here it will be more difficult to activate our c1-bishop. } { [%csl Gc1] })) 11. Ne5! { This is the key move to remember in this setup, preparing cxd5 and Nc6. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gc4d5,Ge5c6] } 11... Nh5 { Other moves fail to disrupt White's harmonious setup, and } (11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 { just helps White activate the rook. This explains why we place the rook opposite Black's queen on move 9, so that Ne5 gains in strength. } { [%cal Gd1d8] }) 12. Bd2 { [%cal Ge2e4] } 12... Nhf6! { Already we see a practical disadvantage of Black's setup - against a higher-rated player, White could repeat moves with 13.Bf4, and Black would either have to accept the draw by repetition, or play an inferior move that leaves them objectively worse. } 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nc6 { Now it's up to Black to decide which bishop he'd rather part with. } { [%csl Gb7,Ge7] } 14... Bxc6 15. Qxc6 Rc8 16. Qb5 { White has the bishop pair advantage, and thus can try to exert some long-term pressure. That said, if Black knows the manoeuvre } 16... Ne8! { [%cal Ge8d6] } 17. Qd3 Nd6 { , he will be able to gradually equalize, as Black has no weaknesses and no bad pieces after } 18. Nc3 Nf6 19. b3 Qd7 $10 { This is admittedly a rather high-level variation, so I wouldn't try to remember this unless you're rated 2000+ FIDE/2200+ Lichess. But for those wondering how the subtleties of top-level chess look, I hope this chapter gave you a better understanding of why many of the world's top players play this way with both colours. } *


