[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Basic Principle 1"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "Basic Principle 1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/4lZeRBbs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:25:08"]

{ The Basic Opening Principles Are:

1. Fight For Control Of The Centre (see the highlighted squares d4/d5/e4/e5 in the middle of the board).

Why do we want to control the centre?

Because our pieces have more mobility in the centre of the board. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge5,Ge4,Gd4] }
 *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Basic Principle 2"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "Basic Principle 2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/WrDSkdWg"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:30:58"]

{ 2. Develop your pieces as quickly and as actively as possible.

We do this for two reasons:

1. To give our pieces as much mobility (possible moves) as we can.
2. To clear the way for our other pieces to move.
3. To have our pieces working together as a team (like in football or any other team sport). }
 *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Basic Principle 3"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "Basic Principle 3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/Br1UVcgg"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:31:03"]

{ 3. Get Your King Castled To Safety.

Why is this important?

When our king is in the centre of the board, our king can be attacked from the centre, the left and the right. (see arrows above)

However, when we castle our king, it's much harder for our opponent to threaten our king.

In most cases, they will need to reposition their pieces to the side we have castled if they want to threaten our king. } { [%cal Ga4e8,Gh5e8,Ge4e8] }
 *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: The Advanced Principle"]
