{ Now let's see the 'theory' in practice with some moves and examples!

What is the best first move for White?

I recommend the following first move for beginners: }
1. e4 { This is the most common move, and with good reason.
White controls one of the 4 central squares (d5) and occupies a second (e4).
This move, 1.e4, also helps with rapid development - our bishop and queen have much greater mobility.
What is Black's best reply to this move, to follow Basic Principle 1 (control the centre)? } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4] } (1. d4 { This move, 1.d4, controls two of the four central squares - d4 and e5.
This move actually does the best job of all for controlling the centre. It is the second most common move for White at all levels.
The price White pays for this (compared to 1.e4) is that his piece mobility and development is slightly slower, and it also takes longer for White to get his king castled. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Ge1][%cal Gd1d3] }) 1... e5 { This symmetrical move is the most common reply below the 1600 level (and the 2nd most common overall). Black's ideas with 1...e5 are the same as I mentioned for White with 1.e4.
(Advanced - the side that manages to keep their central pawn, while exchanging/eliminating the opponent's central pawn, has better chances to obtain the advantage out of the opening.) } { [%cal Gf8a3,Gd8h4] } (1... a6 { This is a much weaker first move for Black, as it doesn't follow any of the basic principles, and allows White to control more of the centre uncontested. } 2. d4 { Now White controls three of the four central squares. He has obtained the 'dream centre' of pawns on d4 and e4. (For Black, the 'dream centre' is pawns on d5 and e5). } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4,Gd5] } 2... h6 3. Nc3 { Now White controls all four of the central squares (d4/d5/e4/e5). He is ready to develop his other pieces and prepare castling his king to safety. } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gc3e4] }) *


