{ You know about the second basic principle - develop your pieces quickly and actively.

How do you do this in practice?

Let's find out. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { This is the most active square the knight can develop to - it can move to up to 8 squares from the circled region. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd3,Ge3,Gf3,Gf4,Gf5,Gf6,Ge6,Gd6,Gc6,Gc5,Gc4,Gd4,Gd5,Ge5,Ge4][%cal Gf3e5] } (2. Nh3 { The knight can only move to up to 4 squares from the edge of the board - that's why the knight is misplaced here. }) (2. Ne2 { The knight is more passive on this square, and also blocks the development of the f1-bishop. } { [%csl Ge2][%cal Gf1a6,Gd1h5] }) (2. Nc3 { This is a reasonable developing move.
But 2.Nf3 is more precise because it also follows Basic Principle 3 (bringing White one move closer to kingside castling) and The Advanced Principle (by threatening the e5-pawn, limiting Black's options). }) 2... Nc6 { Black defends his e5-pawn from the attack, while developing his knight.
(Advanced - It's usually quite clear in the early moves where your knight should develop, but it may take more moves before the best square for the bishop becomes clear). } 3. Bc4 { White develops his bishop to the most active square possible - it has more mobility on this diagonal than after any of the other bishop moves.
This is the most common move at the 1600 level and below and is known as the 'Italian Game'.
Another advantage of this move is that White is ready to castle his king to safety on the next move. } { [%csl Gf1,Gg1][%cal Gc4g8,Gc4a2,Gc4a6,Gc4f1] } (3. Bb5 { This is the 'Ruy Lopez' and we will talk more about this move later. }) (3. Nc3 { This is also a reasonable developing move. However, compared to 3.Bc4 or 3.Bb5, it does not help White castle his king. }) 3... Bc5 { The ideas of this move for Black are the same as 3.Bc4 for White. He is now one move closer to castling short. } { [%csl Gf8,Gg8][%cal Gc5g1] } 4. O-O { White has castled his king to safety (Basic Principle 3).
Now, he can focus even more on the other principles. } 4... Nf6 { Black prepares kingside castling by developing the knight.
He also follows The Advanced Principle by making a threat (attacking the e4-pawn).
This last point is why it's better to develop the knight to f6, than any other square, in this position. } 5. d3 { White defends the e4-pawn, while clearing the way to develop his c1-bishop. } { [%csl Gd3,Ge4][%cal Gc1h6] } 5... O-O { Black has also castled his king to safety. Now we move closer to the middlegame phase, where both sides have their chances.
I share a few possible moves for White from this position, to give you a taste of the available options. } 6. c3 (6. Bg5 { (Advanced - The knight on f6 cannot move safely in this position, as then White will play Bxd8 and win the queen. This is known as a 'pin' - specifically, the g5-bishop is pinning the f6-knight). } { [%cal Gg5d8] }) (6. Nc3) 6... d6 *


