[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "King Safety - What To Avoid (Four Move Checkmate)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/BRijyTOb"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:26:01"]

{ In the previous example, we learned how to develop our pieces rapidly and actively.

We also learned how to clear the way for our king to castle to safety in the opening.

Let's now understand the dangers that can arise when one fails to protect the king against an early attack. }
1. e4 e5 2. Qh5 { This is the 'Parham Attack'.
Although it follows the Advanced Principle at first (creating threats), developing the queen early has the disadvantage that the queen will often get kicked around by other pieces.
The result is that White will lose time, and actually lose control of the game, if Black defends correctly against this early attack. } 2... Nc6 { Black defends the e5-pawn from attack. } (2... g6 { If Black can defend and attack at the same time, it's a good way to take control of the game. But it doesn't work in this exact position, because it doesn't defend against White's big threat. } 3. Qxe5+ { White will take the h8-rook next move, after Black has blocked the check. } 3... Qe7 4. Qxh8) 3. Bc4 { White develops his bishop. In doing so, he threatens the weakest pawn at the start of the game - the f-pawn.
How should Black defend against this? } { [%csl Gf7] } 3... Nf6 { Black fails to see White's checkmate threat. } (3... g6 { This is the best defence, both defending (there's no more Qxf7 checkmate) and attacking (threatening the h5-queen). } 4. Qf3 { White threatens checkmate again, with Qxf7. } 4... Nf6 { Black blocks the attack on the f7-pawn while developing more pieces. } 5. Ne2 { The move ...g6 may look weakening, but it can be used as a preparation for developing the bishop. } 5... Bg7 { This is known as a 'fianchetto', and is a legitimate way to develop the bishop in several openings. } 6. d3 d6 7. h3 O-O { Black has built a 'home' for his king, which is protected by all 3 pawns, the knight, the fianchettoed bishop and the rook. This makes it very difficult for White to successfully attack the Black king. } { [%csl Gg7,Gf6,Gf8,Gf7,Gg6,Gh7] }) 4. Qxf7# { Checkmate! Black cannot take the queen, because it is defended by the c4-bishop.
Another way to avoid this 4-move checkmate (technically known as 'Scholar's Mate') is to block the bishop's diagonal with ...e6.
However, that requires playing a different opening as Black. Furthermore, you'll see in the 3...g6 note that we don't need to fear this early attack, if we know how to defend. } { [%cal Gc4f7,Ge8f7] } *


