{ We already saw an example of how to get the king castled quickly in 'Fast Development In Action'. However, let's see how White can successfully follow the principles against another common opening - the Sicilian Defence. }
1. e4 c5 { This is the Sicilian Defence. It may initially appear inferior to 1...e5, but it's actually the most common move against 1.e4.
The advantage of this move is that, compared to 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3, where we saw the e5-pawn coming under early pressure, it is much harder for White to sensibly attack the c5-pawn.
What this move has in common with 1...e5: It discourages d4 from White, as ...cxd4 would allow Black to exchange White's more valuable centre pawn for a flank pawn.
The disadvantage of 1...c5, compared to 1...e5, is that Black's development will be slower than White's, because it doesn't help him castle more quickly (or develop his bishops, for that matter). } 2. Nf3 { We see the advantage of the Sicilian in action - 2.Nf3 is still the best move for White, but it doesn't threaten a pawn on e5, meaning Black has more good options. } { [%csl Ge5,Gf3] } 2... Nc6 { Black develops his knight and continues to control the central dark squares. } { [%csl Ge5,Gd4] } (2... e6 { This is another option for Black, opening the diagonal for his king's bishop and bringing himself closer to kingside castling.
After this move, it doesn't make as much sense for White to develop his f1-bishop, as it would do nothing on b5, and on c4 it will get kicked around by ...d5. White should instead go for another plan, and postpone the development of his f1-bishop. } { [%cal Gf8a3] } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 { This is the Open Sicilian. White obtains a lead in development and a space advantage, at the price of giving Black a long-term advantage of a 'central majority' (two central pawns to White's one). } { [%csl Gd7,Ge6,Ge4] } 4... Nc6 5. Nc3 { White has many ways to develop the pieces from here - the most natural being to play Be2 and 0-0, getting the king to safety.
(Advanced - This is known as the 'Taimanov Variation' in case you'd like to explore it yourself.) } { [%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1] }) 3. Bb5 { White develops his bishop to b5, pinning the Black knight and preparing short castling, completing kingside development as rapidly as possible.
(Advanced - This is known as the Rossolimo, and it's the second most common move for White, after 3.d4) } { [%cal Ge1g1,Gb5e8] } (3. Bc4 { This bishop development is generally less effective when Black has not played ...e5, because of Black's next move. } 3... e6 { Now the c4-bishop is quite passive, because it hits a pawn on e6 that is defended twice. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc4e6,Gd7e6,Gf7e6] } 4. O-O { White has followed the first three principles, but now Black can take control of the game (The Advanced Principle). } 4... d5 { The c4-bishop is now forced to move a second time to avoid capture. Meanwhile, Black has two pawns side by side in the centre and can claim a comfortable game. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5] }) (3. d4 { This is known as 'The Open Sicilian'. See the note on 2...e6 for a brief discussion of this opening variation. }) 3... d6 { Black prepares to develop his c8-bishop, and also increases his control over the central dark squares. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc8h3,Gd6e5] } (3... a6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 { (Advanced - White is quite happy to exchange his bishop for Black's knight, especially when provoked by ...a6, because Black now has doubled pawns on the c-file. This means that Black's pawn structure is a lot less flexible, while White keeps a central space advantage and a lead in development.) } { [%csl Gc6,Gc5] } 5. O-O { White's king is safe and he is ready to take the centre and claim an opening advantage. }) 4. O-O { White's king has now castled to safety, and he is ready to think about taking more control of the centre and developing his other pieces. For example: } 4... Bd7 5. Re1 { White develops his rook in anticipation of ...Nf6, which would otherwise threaten the e4-pawn. } 5... Nf6 { Black has developed his queenside minor pieces already, so he develops his kingside and moves closer to kingside castling. } 6. c3 { With this move, White prepares d4 to achieve the 'dream centre' of pawns on d4 and e4.
(Advanced - If you want to win with a Grandmaster-strength opening 'repertoire' (set of variations) against the Sicilian, check out my course 'Attacking The Sicilian': https://members.illingworthchessacademy.com/offers/R3Z2rfcZ) } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gd2d4] } (6. d4 { This is less effective here than on move 3, because after } 6... cxd4 { White is unable to recapture with a pawn, to keep two pawns side by side in the centre. } { [%cal Gc3d4] }) *


