{ It's important to understand that the opening is much more than just a transition to the middlegame. There are a lot of hidden dangers lurking for both sides in the early moves of a game!

Those of you who have fallen into opening traps, or watched Youtube videos about opening traps, will know this all too well!

Here, I will show how sometimes the most 'natural' opening moves can also have their dangers! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { This symmetrical response, counterattacking the e4-pawn, is known as the 'Petroff' or the 'Russian Game'.
It's a very solid opening for Black, but only if he follows up correctly. } 3. Nxe5 { The most common and obvious move, capturing the e5-pawn. } 3... Nxe4 { Black continues copying White, but here it is a mistake for tactical reasons, as White now uses his extra move to create powerful threats. } (3... d6 { This is the correct move, throwing in the intermediate move ...d6 before regaining the e4-pawn with ...Nxe4. } 4. Nf3 { The most natural square for the knight. } 4... Nxe4 { Now Black's position is safe, as the Qe2 pin is less effective than in our main line. } 5. Qe2 (5. d4 { Advanced - this is the most common move, taking the centre. } { [%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] }) 5... Qe7 { Black breaks the pin on the knight to the king, safeguarding the knight in the process. } 6. d3 { Kicking the knight back with tempo, just like Black did before with 3...d6. } 6... Nf6 { The position is symmetrical here as well, but the key difference (compared to 3...Nxe4) is that Black's pieces are safe, and the position is quiet.
The result is that the position is equal, as White is unable to harness his extra tempo into a real initiative. }) 4. Qe2 { The problem for Black becomes clear - his knight is under attack, and retreating the knight allows a powerful discovered check/attack along the open e-file. } 4... Nf6 { Protecting the knight, but allowing something much worse. In principle, the open e-file spells trouble for the uncastled king, as the queen or rook can attack the king down this open file. } (4... d5 { runs into a similar problem: } 5. d3 { and Black's knight is again unable to retreat to safety. } 5... Nf6 6. Nc6+) (4... Qe7 { This is the best defence, leaving the e4-knight to its fate. } 5. Qxe4 { White is up a piece, but Black recoups some of the material with his next move. } 5... d6 { Now it is White's knight that finds itself in a pin. } { [%cal Ge7e1] } 6. d4 { White defends the knight while preparing further development and controlling the centre. } 6... dxe5 7. dxe5 { White is up a pawn with a good position. }) 5. Nc6+ { Black cannot take the knight, because the king is in check from White's queen. } { [%csl Gc6,Gd8][%cal Ge2e8] } 5... Qe7 { Otherwise Nxd8 wins the queen. } 6. Nxe7 { White wins a queen for a knight - a decisive material advantage. } *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Sense Of Danger - 2nd Example"]
