[Opening "Italian Game: Two Knights Defense, Fried Liver Attack"]
[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "Sense Of Danger - 2nd Example"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/jGKO7pIs"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:26:28"]

{ Now for a more advanced example of what can happen if you lose your sense of danger in the opening. }
1. e4 { We already talked about the moves up to 3.Bc4 in the game 'Fast Development In Action'. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Do you remember the name of this opening?
That's right, it is the Italian Game - the most common opening at the beginner and junior levels. } 3... Nf6 { Black develops his knight while attacking the e4-pawn. This is known as the 'Two Knights Defence', however to play it successfully, Black must be prepared to sacrifice a pawn out of the opening. } (3... Bc5 { We already saw this move in 'Fast Development In Action'. } { [%cal Gd8g5,Gf3g5] }) 4. Ng5 { White exploits the one disadvantage of 3...Nf6.
You may remember that the f2 and f7-pawns are the weakest pawns at the start of the game, because they are only defended by the king.
If Black had already developed his f8-bishop, this attack would not achieve anything for White, due to the reply of castling kingside. } 4... d5 { Only this pawn move blocks the threat of Nxf7, forking the d8-queen and h8-rook (see the 4...h6 note). } (4... h6 5. Nxf7 Qe7 6. Nxh8 { White is up a rook and pawn - a decisive material advantage. }) 5. exd5 { White captures the pawn. In doing so, he also defends his bishop from attack. } 5... Nxd5 { What could be more natural than recapturing the pawn?
However, this move is very dangerous for Black, because it re-opens the c4-bishop's diagonal, allowing White to pile up heavy pressure against the 'weakest link' on f7 before Black has castled his king to safety.
To see how Black should play instead, check the 5...Na5 note. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc4f7] } (5... Na5 { Advanced - This is the correct move, known as 'Polerio's Counterattack'. The idea is to eliminate or distract the c4-bishop, avoiding the problems on f7 we'll see after 5...Nxd5. } 6. Bb5+ { White gives a check while dealing with the threat to his bishop. This follows the Advanced Principle (creating threats), as Black can't recapture the d5-pawn while his king is in check. } 6... c6 { Black continues attacking White's bishop to continue the fight for the initiative (control of the game). This entails sacrificing a pawn. } 7. dxc6 bxc6 { Once again, Black recaptures with the pawn to keep making threats against White's pieces. } 8. Be2 { There are other retreats for the bishop, but this one is the most natural, keeping the bishop out of the range of any attacks. } 8... h6 { Black forces the White knight to a less active post with this attack. } 9. Nf3 e4 { Black attacks the White knight again, while gaining more space in the centre (central control). } 10. Ne5 Bc5 { Black has excellent compensation for the pawn, because of his lead in development and central space advantage. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd8d4] }) 6. Nxf7 { This is known as The 'Fried Liver Attack'. It leads to very complicated play, where White sacrifices a piece to drag Black's king into the open centre. } (6. d4 { Advanced - This is known as the 'Lolli Attack' and gives White a safer advantage than 6.Nxf7. However, this falls outside the scope of this Study. }) 6... Kxf7 { Black has no good alternative to accepting the piece sacrifice. Now the king is open to checks. } 7. Qf3+ { This is the correct check, because it attacks the f7-king and d5-knight at once.
(Advanced - this double attack is known as a 'fork', and is one of the most important tactics to master to become a strong chess player). } { [%cal Gf3d5,Gf3f7] } 7... Ke6 { Only this move both gets out of check and defends the d5-knight from being captured for free.
The price Black pays is clear - his king is stuck in the centre on e6, and his knight on d5 is in an unpleasant pin from the c4-bishop. } { [%cal Ge6d5] } 8. Nc3 { White increases the pressure on the 'pinned' d5-knight (which cannot move from attack, as then the e6-king would be in check). } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5] } 8... Nb4 { Black defends the d5-knight, while attacking the c2-pawn (threatening a 'fork' on the king and rook).
The position is very complicated and unclear for humans to play, though it's easier to play White, as it's typically easier to attack than defend well, especially at the amateur level. } *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: Fight For The Intiative - Scotch Gambit For White"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Haxo Gambit"]
[StudyName "Opening Principles For Under 1600s"]
[ChapterName "Fight For The Intiative - Scotch Gambit For White"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/47gAGm9l/Ff7W3z3S"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "12:26:50"]

{ In this example, we will see White sacrificing a pawn to take control of the game and make it harder for the opponent to follow the basic opening principles successfully.

(Advanced - Sacrificing material in the opening is known as an 'Opening Gambit' or 'Gambit' for short.) }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { White places his other pawn in the centre, not fearing the capture on d4.
This move is known as The Scotch Game. } 3... exd4 { Black captures the pawn to eliminate White's 'dream centre' of pawns on d4 and e4. } 4. Bc4 { This is the Scotch Gambit. Compared to 3.Bc4, White has sacrificed a pawn to open the position and develop his pieces more quickly. } { [%cal Gc1h6,Gd1d8] } (4. Nxd4 { (Advanced - Simply recapturing the pawn is known as The Scotch Game. This is the most common move for White.) } 4... Nxd4 { This does not win the knight, as White can recapture with the queen. } 5. Qxd4 { Previously, I was critical of developing the queen too early, because it can be attacked easily by the opponent's pieces with tempo (see 'King Safety - What To Avoid as an example).
However, Black is not able to easily attack the d4-queen with his knight, as the queen's knight was already traded.
Therefore, White's lead in development and extra central space gives him an advantage. }) 4... Bc5 { Black defends the d4-pawn from capture, asking White to justify his opening gambit. } { [%csl Gd4] } 5. c3 { A strong move, attacking the d4-pawn. This also sets a trap that many thousands of inexperienced players have fallen for.
(Advanced - Let's see if you can do better. What would you play here as Black?) } (5. Nxd4 { We can see that the d4-pawn is safe from capture by looking at the attackers and defenders of the pawn: } 5... Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Bxd4 { and Black is up a full queen at the end of the exchanges. }) 5... dxc3 { The most natural move, accepting the pawn sacrifice to keep a material advantage.
However, this move has a concrete tactical problem, based on two key points:
1. The f7-pawn is only defended by the king.
2. The c5-bishop is undefended (making it vulnerable to forks).
Based on these hints, what move would you play as White here? } (5... Nf6 { is the correct move for Black - see the link at the end of this game for more information. }) 6. Bxf7+ { Well done if you found this intermediate move! White lures the Black king into an exposed position, setting up a strong fork. } (6. Nxc3 d6 { gives Black time to protect his bishop against the Bxf7 tactic and consolidate his position. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd6] }) (6. Qd5 { This is the right idea, but the wrong move order. } { [%csl Ge7] } 6... Qe7 { Black defends the f7-pawn and bishop at once. Next move, Black will play ...Nf6 to kick back the White queen and take control of the game. } { [%csl Gf7,Ge7,Gc5] } 7. Nxc3 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 6... Kxf7 { Black may as well take the bishop, as otherwise he lost a pawn with tempo. } 7. Qd5+ { The point - White forks the Black king and bishop. } { [%cal Gd5f7,Gd5c5] } 7... Ke8 { Black chooses this retreat square, so that Qxc5 does not come with check.
Now the automatic move is to take the bishop on c5 and regain the sacrificed bishop, but White can do even better. } 8. Qh5+ { A useful intermediate check, as Black is forced to either place his king on a worse square, or weaken his kingside with ...g6. } 8... g6 { Now the long diagonal is opened up. } (8... Kf8 9. Qxc5+ { checks the king, meaning Black does not have time to keep the extra pawn with ...cxb2. } 9... d6 10. Qxc3 { White is much better here, as Black's king remains uncastled, and White has more space and slightly faster development to boot. } { [%csl Ge4,Gf8] }) 9. Qxc5 { White has regained his piece and left the Black king stuck in the centre.
But what if Black keeps the extra pawn? } 9... cxb2 { This is a very risky move, as it increases White's lead in development. } 10. Bxb2 { Black must deal with the threat of Bxh8. } { [%cal Gb2h8] } 10... Nf6 { Blocking with the knight.
From here, there are a lot of good moves for White, who has scored extremely well from this position in practice. The simplest is to play } 11. O-O { , realizing that the e4-pawn is 'poisoned' and Black can't take it: } (11. e5 { is tempting too, attacking the knight with tempo, though I prefer castling. }) 11... Nxe4 { Attacking the queen, but this can be punished in several ways. } 12. Re1 { White pins the e4-knight to prevent Nxc5.
In turn, Black's h8-rook and e4-knight are both under attack, and he must lose at least one of these pieces.
To learn more about how to play the Scotch Gambit as White and beat 1.e4 e5 in general, check out my course 'How To Beat 1.e4 e5': https://members.illingworthchessacademy.com/offers/7Uxx2XNM } { [%cal Ge1e8,Gb2h8] } *


[Event "Opening Principles For Under 1600s: How To Meet Gambits"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
