{ If you are not facing moves other than 1.e4 (like 1.d4) in many games yet, I recommend following this simple setup, known as The Queen's Gambit Declined. It allows you to follow the key opening principles, by getting a pawn firmly in the centre and your king castled by move 5 (unless they exchange pawns or threaten you first). }
1. d4 (1. e4 { For beginning players, I strongly recommend meeting 1.e4 with } 1... e5 { , to master the fundamentals of chess. See the previous games for the key ideas you should remember as Black, when playing 1.e4 e5. }) (1. Nf3 { The Queen's Gambit Declined setup I'm showing you also works against less common first moves, such as 1.Nf3 and 1.c4. An example: } 1... d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O { with a solid position for Black in this King's Indian Attack (incidentally, a system opening for White). }) (1. c4 { The English Opening is a bit tricky, as we don't want to play ...d5 unless we can recapture with a pawn on d5 (to keep our central control). Fortunately, } 1... e6 { is a good answer for us, preparing ...d5. After } 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 { , we have transposed to our main line, with 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3. }) 1... d5 2. c4 (2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. e3 { is what we saw before - the London System. However, against more passive setups by White, Black can consider developing the bishop more aggressively, with } 4... Bd6 { and then ...0-0 for a solid game. } { [%cal Ge8g8] }) 2... e6 { This is the Queen's Gambit Declined. Rather than taking the pawn on c4 (which is difficult to hang on to in any case), Black defends his d5-pawn (so that he can keep a pawn in the centre after cxd5) and prepares kingside development. } 3. Nc3 { White continues consistently, increasing the pressure on the d5-pawn. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gc4d5] } 3... Nf6 { In turn, Black develops his knight while overprotecting the d5-pawn and covering the e4-square.
Black is now one move closer to castling as well, and it's up to White to decide on his setup. } (3... Be7 { and then ...Nf6 is a good alternative move order, if you want to avoid the 'Exchange Variation' lines with 4.cxd5 exd5 5.Bg5 in the note below. } { [%csl Gg5] }) 4. Nf3 { White develops his other knight logically, waiting for Black to show his cards.
Black has a lot of reasonable moves from this position, but I'll be focusing on the most 'classical' approach of the Queen's Gambit Declined, sticking with the 'System Opening' approach. } (4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 { is the Exchange Variation, and White's main alternative. However, Black can continue developing in the same way, starting with } 5... Be7 { . }) 4... Be7 { Black develops his bishop solidly, so that a pin on the knight with Bg5 will not be unpleasant. The most active square for the bishop, in comparison, is b4 - which is another story altogether. } 5. Bg5 { White is trying to put more pressure on the d5-pawn by pinning the defending knight. } 5... O-O { Black has secured his position by stabilizing a pawn in the centre on d5, while completing kingside development.
He typically solves the problem of his passive c8-bishop with a queenside fianchetto (...b6 and ...Bb7).
In the middlegame, he will generally challenge White's centre with ...c5 to equalize the chances. } { [%cal Gh7h6,Gc8b7,Gb7b6,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] } *


