{ Congratulations on reaching the final game of this Study!

I shared a lot of examples with you, so let's summarize the key lessons.

Do you remember the 4 Key Opening Principles?

Let me know your answers in the chat room, before clicking the next move to see for yourself. }
1. e4 { The 4 Key Opening Principles Are:
1. Control the centre;
2. Develop your pieces quickly and actively;
3. Get your king to safety (by castling);
4. (Advanced) Fight for control of the game/the initiative.
Now, do you remember the two main dangers to watch out for in the opening phase?
See the next move for the answer. } 1... e5 { The two main dangers in the opening are:
1. Falling into an early and strong attack on the 'weakest link' on f7 as Black (f2 as White)
2. Being attacked down the open e-file before your king is castled.
Do you remember the two main tactics we learned from our opening examples?
See the next move to find out. } { [%csl Gf7,Gf2] } 2. Nf3 { The 2 main tactics we saw at play were:
1. Forks/double attacks
2. Pins
Bonus points if you remembered the discovered checks/attacks, and the advanced deflection from the Ruy Lopez example!
Next question - Which of these openings are you going to test in your games? } 2... Nc6 { Here are some options from the openings we covered here:
White: Italian Game; Ruy Lopez; Scotch Gambit; Open Sicilian; Rossolimo Sicilian; London System; Queen's Gambit
Black: Berlin Defence; Open Games; Sicilian; Queen's Gambit Declined. } 3. Bc4 { Would you like to learn more from me (GM Max Illingworth)?
Check out my Chess Improvement System to become a strong chess player in the next 12 months: https://members.illingworthchessacademy.com/offers/tM5agbGS } *


