1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 { [%csl Ge5,Ge4] } 6. Ndb5 d6 { Ian came =3rd in this World U20 Juniors - Kasparov won it } 7. Bg5 a6 8. Na3 Be6 { Bird Variation } (8... b5 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Ga3c4] } 9. Bxf6 { [%cal Gd8f6,Gc3d5,Gf6d8] } 9... gxf6 $13 { Black's structure is not ideal - enough active play to make up for it } { [%csl Gf8,Gc8][%cal Gf6f5,Gf5e4] }) 9. Nc4 Rc8 10. Ne3 { White dominates the d5-outpost - good grip on the centre } { [%csl Gd5] } 10... Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 { [%csl Gd5] } 12. Bc4 O-O 13. Bb3 (13. O-O Bg5 $132) 13... Nd4 14. O-O Bg5 15. Ncd5 Nxb3 16. axb3 { For Black's bishops to show their strength - position needs to open
What will be Black's pawn break? (P)
g5-bishop can't control d5 - can still participate in the fight for a square } { [%csl Gd5,Ge3,Ge6,Gg5] } 16... g6 { [%csl Gf5,Ge4][%cal Gf7f5,Gf5e4] } (16... Bxe3 17. Nxe3 Rc6 { [%csl Gd6,Gd2,Gd3,Gd1][%cal Gd8c7,Gg7g6,Gf8d8] }) 17. Kh1 { Ian was also very tactical/ambitious/tricky - sitting on a position was unfamiliar/uncomfortable } { [%cal Gg5e3] } 17... Bh6 18. Qd3 { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8c6] } 18... f5 { [%cal Gf5e4,Gf8f1] } (18... Rc5 { [%cal Gh6e3,Gd6d5] }) 19. exf5 gxf5 { If Black could get in both ...f4 and ...e4 - good attacking chances on the kingside } { [%csl Gd5,Gf4,Ge4,Gh1][%cal Ge5e4,Gf5f4] } 20. f4! { Fixing a target in place (fixing the f5-pawn) } { [%csl Gd6,Ge5,Gf5][%cal Ge5f4,Gd5f4] } 20... e4 (20... Kh8 { [%cal Gf8g8,Gg8g1] } 21. Rad1 Qh4 22. Qe2 (22. c4) 22... exf4 23. Nc4 { Sacrifice for the initiative } { [%cal Ge2e6,Gc4d6] } 23... Bf7 { Our opponent's threats aren't always as dangerous as they seem - what's the most aggressive available counter to their threat? (take the initiative) } { [%cal Gf7h5,Gh5d1] } (23... Bxd5 24. Rxd5 { [%csl Gd6,Gf5,Gf4] } 24... Rce8 { [%cal Ge8e1] }) (23... f3! 24. Qxe6 (24. Qxf3 { Good to ignore White's threats and play our own } { [%csl Ge6] } 24... f4 $13 { [%cal Gc4d6,Ge6g4,Gg4d1] }) 24... fxg2+ 25. Kxg2 Rce8 { [%cal Ge8e2] } 26. Qxd6 Re2+ 27. Kh1 Qe4+ { [%cal Ge4g2] }) 24. Qd3 (24. Nxd6 Bh5 25. Qd3 Bxd1 26. Nxc8) 24... Bh5 { [%cal Gd1e1] } 25. Nxd6! { [%cal Gd6c8,Gh5d1] } 25... Bxd1 26. Nxc8 { [%cal Gf8c8,Gf1d1] } 26... Bh5 27. Nce7 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gd3d4] } 27... f3!? 28. gxf3 { [%cal Gh6g7] } 28... Qh3 { White to play (P) - Kasparov was a very good calculator, very alert } (28... Bg7) 29. Nf4!! { [%cal Gh6f4,Gd3d4,Gd4h8] } (29. Rf2 Bg7 30. c3 Be5 { [%cal Ge5g3,Gd3f1] }) 29... Qh4 (29... Bxf4 30. Qd4+ { [%cal Gh6g7] }) 30. Qd4+ Qf6 (30... Bg7 31. Nfg6+ { [%cal Gd4h4] }) 31. Qxf6+ Rxf6 32. Nxh5 Rf7 33. Nd5 f4 34. Re1 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { More positional/strong defensive player that Kasparov was
If you're a very good attacker - also know how to deal with the opponent's attacks (exchanging the attackers (queen) - counter-attack (ignore the opponent's threats and play our own threats) }) 21. Qd2 $14 { [%csl Gd5,Ge3,Ge4,Gd6][%cal Gc2c4,Gb3b4,Gb4b5] } 1-0


