1. d4 g6 2. c4 Bg7 3. Nf3 d6 4. Nc3 Nd7 5. e4 e5 6. Be2 Nh6?! (6... Ngf6 7. O-O O-O { is best, but not really in the spirit of the Modern Defence - indeed, we've now transposed to the old ...Nbd7 Classical King's Indian. }) (6... c6 7. O-O Nh6 { is a move order I played in 2005 to avoid h4-h5, but then } 8. d5! { gains in strength. }) 7. h4! f6 8. h5 g5 9. d5 O-O 10. O-O (10. Nd2 { is very strong, threatening g4. } 10... f5 11. exf5 Nxf5 12. h6! { A very powerful pawn sacrifice for the initiative. } 12... Nxh6 13. Nde4 Nf7 14. Bd3 { White has a wonderful attacking position and Black has no counterplay, despite being a pawn up. }) 10... a5 11. Nd2 f5 12. exf5 Nxf5 { Now Black is not doing so badly, and Nakamura was able to outplay his opponent from here, using his experience of King's Indian structures. } 13. Nde4 h6 14. Bg4 b6 15. Qd3 Nf6 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Ne4 Qf7 18. Bd2 Nd4 19. Bxc8 Raxc8 20. Ng3 b5 21. Rac1 e4 22. Qxe4 bxc4 23. Rxc4 c5 24. Be3 Be5 25. Qd3 Rce8 26. Rcc1 Kh8 27. Qc4 Rb8 28. b3 Rb4 29. Qd3 Qxd5 30. Qg6 Rf6 31. Qe8+ Qg8 32. Qxg8+ Kxg8 33. Rfe1 Rb8 34. Rc4 Rbf8 35. Ne2 Nc6 36. Rd1 Re6 37. Nc3 Nb4 38. Rd2 Bxc3 39. Rxc3 Kf7 40. Rc4 Ke7 41. Re2 Rf5 42. Kf1 Rfe5 43. Rd2 Nd5 44. Ra4 Nxe3+ 45. fxe3 Rxe3 46. Rxa5 g4 47. Ra7+ Kf6 48. Rf2+ Kg5 49. g3 Rxg3 50. Rg7+ Kxh5 51. Rh2+ Rh3 52. Rxh3+ gxh3 53. Kg1 Re1+ 54. Kh2 Re2+ 55. Kxh3 Rxa2 56. Rg3 Rd2 57. Rc3 Kg5 58. Kg3 h5 59. Rf3 h4+ 60. Kh3 Rd4 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


