1. d4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e4 d6 4. c3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 { This structure may seem very static, but the asymmetry of ...Bg7 vs. Bd3 gives good scope to outplay the opponent. } 10. Nc4 Qe7 11. a4 Nh5 { Bringing the knight to f4 is a typical means of creating counterplay in these structures. } (11... Be6 { is actually possible, on the basis that White will struggle to hang on to the e5-pawn if he takes: } 12. Nxe5 Rad8 13. Qe2 Qd6 14. f4 Nh5! 15. Rd1 Nxf4! 16. Bxf4 Bxe5) 12. Re1 Nf4 13. Bxf4 (13. Bf1 { was better. }) 13... exf4 { Black has successfully unbalanced the position and went on to win the game with the help of his bishop pair advantage. } 14. e5 Be6 15. Bf1 Qg5 16. Nd2 Rfd8 17. Nf3 Rxd1 18. Nxg5 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Bb3 20. a5 b6 21. a6 Rd8 22. Nf3 c5 23. Bb5 h6 24. h3 Kf8 25. Kf1 Ke7 26. Ke2 Ke6 27. Nd2 Bd5 28. f3 Bxe5 29. Nc4 Bc7 30. Rd1 Ke7 31. Na3 Be6 32. Rxd8 Kxd8 33. Kd3 Bd6 34. Nc4 Ke7 35. Nd2 g5 36. Ne4 f6 37. Ke2 Be5 38. Nd2 Bd7 39. Bxd7 Kxd7 40. Kd3 b5 41. c4 b4 42. Kc2 Kc6 43. h4 f5 44. hxg5 hxg5 45. Nb3 Kb6 46. Nc1 Bd4 47. Nd3 Kxa6 48. Kb3 Ka5 49. Ne1 Be5 50. Nd3 Bd6 51. Nf2 Kb6 52. Ka4 Be5 53. Nd3 Bc7 54. Kb3 Kc6 55. Ka4 a6 56. Kb3 Kd6 57. Kc2 Bb6 58. Kb3 Ke6 59. Kc2 Kf6 60. Nc1 Kg6 61. Kd2 a5 62. b3 Kf6 63. Nd3 Ke6 64. Nb2 Bd8 65. Na4 Kd6 66. Kd3 Bf6 67. Nb6 Kc6 68. Na4 Be7 69. Ke2 Kd6 70. Nb6 Ke6 71. Na4 Kf7 72. Kf1 Kg6 73. Nb2 Bf6 74. Nd3 Bd4 75. Nc1 Be3 76. Nd3 Kh5 77. Ne5 Bd4 78. Nd3 Kh4 79. Nc1 Be3 80. Nd3 Kg3 81. Ne1 g4 82. fxg4 fxg4 83. Ke2 Bf2 84. Nd3 Bd4 85. Ne1 Be3 86. Kf1 Kh2 87. Nd3 f3 88. gxf3 g3 89. Ne1 a4 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


