1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. h4 h6 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bf4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. c3 Be7 14. Ne4?! Ngf6 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. b4?! Qd5 17. c4 Qe4+ 18. Qxe4 Nxe4 $15 19. Rb1 O-O 20. Bf4 Rfd8 21. Rb3 b5! 22. c5 { I didn't regard this move as very dangerous but I
kind of dismissed some of white's idea such as playing Bc7 in response to ...
a5 and Ne5 to hit the pawn on c6 and also Ra3 to stop a5 and go Ra6 to hit c6
but I found a solution to all my problems. } (22. Ne5 { I was looking at this
when thinking about ...b5 as it was the only move that tried to make concrete
problems } 22... bxc4 23. Re3 (23. Nxc4 Rxd4) 23... Bxb4+ 24. Ke2 Rxd4 { Looking at
this position from after 21.Rb3 was was a little puzzling as after Nxc6 it
seems like everything is hanging but there was a way to keep everything and
win material } 25. Nxc6 Rd2+ 26. Kf3 Nxf2 27. Rf1 Nd3 $19) 22... Bf6 23. Re3 (23. Rd3 a5 $17) 23... Ng5 24. Bxg5 hxg5 25. g4 a5! $19 26. Ne5 Bxe5 27. Rxe5 axb4 28. h6 Rxa2 29. Rh3 Ra3 30. Rh2 g6 31. Re4 b3 32. Kd2 b2 (32... b4) 33. Kc2 Rb3 34. Rh1 Rb4 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


[Event "49th Tokyo Open"]
[Date "2017.10.08"]
[White "Asaka, Samuel"]
[Black "Mikio, Takahashi"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Asaka,Ryokichi"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense: St. George Defense"]
[StudyName "Craze's Study"]
[ChapterName "Asaka, Samuel - Mikio, Takahashi"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/orsLQx6w/sb2itMrc"]

1. d4 { Junta (and Andrew) would play the Hippo against me } 1... e6 2. e4 (2. c4 b6 3. a3 g6 4. e4 Bg7 5. Nc3 { Baburin-Miles }) 2... a6 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 d6 4. f4 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Be3 Ne7 7. Qd2 { More dynamic } { [%cal Ge1c1] } 7... b6 8. O-O-O { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gh2h5] }) 3... d6 4. c4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 (6. Be2 Ne7 7. O-O O-O 8. Be3 { Classical KID } 8... h6 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 9. Qd2 Kh7) 6... h6 { Not allow Bh6 } 7. Qd2 b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 { Used to play the Hippo against the computer } { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] } 9. O-O (9. h4 { [%csl Ge7] } 9... Nf6!) (9. d5 { [%cal Gd5e6,Ge4e5] } 9... e5 { Bb7 is misplaced - not so easy to get in ...f5 } 10. O-O Ne7 11. Ne1 f5 { [%cal Gf2f4,Ge4f5] } (11... g5 12. Nc2 { b4/c5 (a4-a5) } { [%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5] }) 12. exf5 gxf5 13. f4 e4 { Nc2-d4-e6 - long-term advantage for White } 14. Be2 $16 { [%cal Gg1h1,Gg2g4] }) 9... Ne7 { d5 - when Bb7 - GM Agrest's rule of thumb: without a pawn break, there is no plan } { [%cal Gg6g5,Ge7g6] } 10. h3 { [%csl Gc4,Gc2,Gg6][%cal Gg6g5,Ge7g6] } (10. b4 { [%cal Ga2a4,Ga6a5] } 10... Nd7 { [%cal Gd4d5] }) 10... Nd7 11. Nh2?! { [%cal Gf2f4,Gh2f3] } (11. Ne1 e5 (11... c5 { Bd3 - d6-pawn is covered (Baburin-Miles, 2000 - model Hippo game for Black) }) 12. d5 { [%cal Ge1c2,Ge1d3] }) 11... e5 12. d5 g5?! (12... f5 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 13. f4 (13. exf5 gxf5 (13... Nxf5 { Better to keep control } { [%cal Gg2g4] } 14. Ne4 { bad g7-bishop } { [%csl Ge4] } (14. g4 Nh4 15. f4 { [%cal Ge3h6] } 15... O-O 16. fxe5 Nxe5 { Nef3 } { [%cal Ge5f3] })) 14. f4 e4 15. Be2 { Nf1-e3 (g4 break) } { [%cal Ge8g8] }) 13... exf4 14. Bxf4 g5 { [%cal Ge4f5,Gg5f4] } 15. Be3 f4 16. Bf2 Ne5 $10 { Black has a good grip on e5 - usually we want to avoid these positions }) 13. b4 (13. Rfc1 Ng6 14. Nf1 Nf4 15. Ng3) 13... Ng6 14. Rfc1 Nf4 { Kramnik-Kasparov, 1994 - Bayonet KID where Kasparov played ...Nf4 } { [%csl Gf4] } 15. Nf1! Nf6 16. c5 (16. Ng3 Bc8) 16... O-O 17. Ng3 Bc8 { Trend has been good for White. - Time to open the position and take the initiative } { [%csl Gc1,Gc3,Gd2,Ge3][%cal Gb7c8] } 18. a4?! { [%cal Ga4a5] } (18. cxb6 cxb6 19. Na4 Rb8 { [%cal Ga4b6,Gc1c8] } (19... b5 20. Nb6 { Black can't mate on the kingside without c8-bishop } { [%cal Gb6c8,Gf7f4] }) 20. Rc6 $16 (20. Nxb6 { [%cal Gc8h3] } 20... Rxb6 (20... Bxh3 21. gxh3 Nxh3+ 22. Kf1 Rxb6 23. Bxb6 Qxb6 24. Rc6 { Nf5 (xa6) }) 21. Rxc8 Qxc8 22. Bxb6) 20... Bd7 { [%cal Ga1c1,Gd3a6] } 21. Bxa6 (21. Rac1 Bxc6 22. Rxc6 b5) (21. Rxd6 Qc7 22. Rxd7 Nxd7 23. Bxa6 b5 24. Nc5 $16 { a4 } { [%cal Ga2a4,Gg3f5] }) 21... Bxc6 22. dxc6 d5) 18... h5 (18... b5) 19. a5 b5 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Bb6 Qe8 22. Bf1 { [%cal Gc1c7] } 22... h4 23. Nge2 N6h5 { Prophylaxis against ...f5 - the key is to find what move the opponent will play and anticipate it (Yusupov Chess24 series 'Prophylactic Thinking') } { [%cal Gc3d1,Gd1e3,Ge3f5] } 24. Nd1?! (24. Nxf4 { [%cal Gh5f4] } 24... Nxf4 25. Ne2) (24. f3 { [%cal Gd2e3] }) (24. Qe3 f5 25. exf5 Bxf5 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 26. f3 Nf6 { d5-pawn is vulnerable } { [%cal Gf6d5] }) 24... f5 25. exf5 (25. f3 fxe4 26. fxe4 g4 { [%csl Ge4] }) 25... Bxf5 { [%cal Ge5e4,Gf4d3] } 26. Nec3? (26. Rc7 { [%cal Gg5g4] } 26... e4 (26... g4) 27. Bd4 { Balanced }) (26. Ne3 { [%cal Gf4d3,Ge3f5,Gg5g4] } 26... Nd3 (26... Bg6 27. Rc7) 27. Nxf5 Nxc1 { [%cal Gf5g7,Gc1e2] } 28. Nxd6 Nxe2+ 29. Bxe2 Qg6 { [%csl Gd6] } 30. Nb7 { [%cal Gb7c5,Ge2g4,Gd5d7] } (30. Bxh5 { Qd6 Bc5 } { [%cal Gg6d6,Gb6c5] } 30... Qxh5 31. Ne4 { f3 - full grip on centre (bad g7-bishop) } { [%cal Gf2f3] })) 26... g4 $17 27. hxg4 Bxg4 28. Ne3 Qg6 (28... Bd7) 29. Nxg4 Qxg4 { [%cal Gf4g2,Gf1g2,Gh4h3,Gc3d1,Gd1e3] } 30. Nd1? (30. f3 Nh3+ (30... Qg6 { Dark-squared play (...Bh6) - ...h3 } { [%cal Gh4h3,Gh5g3,Gg2g4] }) 31. Kh1 { [%cal Gh5g3] } (31. Kh2 Qg3+ 32. Kh1 { Ne4 } { [%cal Gh3f4,Gb6f2,Gc3e4] })) 30... Bh6 31. Ne3 Qg6 32. Kh1 Rf6?! (32... Ng3+ 33. fxg3 (33. Kg1 Ne4) 33... hxg3 { [%cal Gg6h5,Gh5h2] }) 33. Rc7 Raf8 34. Qc2 { Black has the attack - no way he should trade queens } { [%cal Gf8f6] } 34... Qxc2? (34... e4 35. Bd4 R6f7 36. Rxf7 { [%cal Gf8f7,Gc2c8] } 36... Kxf7 37. Qc7+ Kg8 38. Qd7 { Qg4 trade queens } { [%cal Gd7g4] }) 35. Rxc2 $16 { Black took too long to build up - didn't strike while the iron is hot } 35... Rg6 36. Rc7 Nf6 37. Rd1 Ne4 38. Nc2 Rf7 39. Rc8+ Kh7 40. Ra8 { [%csl Gh1] } 40... Rfg7 41. Rxa6?! { [%cal Gf4g2] } 41... Nxg2 { Top level chess - if one player strongly believes they are better, the other player also believes it } 42. Ra7?! { [%cal Gf1d3] } (42. Bd3 $18 { I intended to play Ra7 against Nxg2 before I
played Rxa6 and couldn't see this simple move, I only realized seconds after I
played Ra7 that I missed such an easy win. }) 42... Rxa7 43. Bxa7 Ne3?! 44. Bxe3 Bxe3 45. Nxe3 Nxf2+ 46. Kh2 Nxd1 47. Nxd1 { I got to this position with
about 10 minutes left and my opponent, about 50 minutes and I didn't handle it
correctly } { [%csl Gg6,Gd1,Gf1] } 47... Rg4 { CT-ART 6 } 48. Bxb5?? (48. a6 Rxb4 49. Nc3 { Dominate the rook - Kasparian's 'Domination in XXXX Studies' }) 48... Rxb4 { I thought I was winning here and played
too ambitiously } 49. Bc6 { [%csl Ga5] } 49... Rb1 { Constantly annoy White - not let you establish control } { [%cal Gc6a4,Gb1a1] } 50. Ba4?? (50. Ne3 { [%cal Ge3c4] } 50... Rb2+ 51. Kg1 Rb1+ 52. Kf2 Rb2+ { Accept the possible repetition } 53. Kg1 { [%cal Ge3c4,Gc4d6] }) 50... Rb4? (50... Ra1 $19) 51. Bc6 Rb1 52. Nc3 { [%csl Gd6] } 52... Rb2+ 53. Kg1 Rb3 54. Na4 { [%cal Ga5a7,Ga7a8] } 54... e4 { [%csl Ge4,Gh4] } 55. a6?? (55. Bd7 { Very precise } { [%cal Gd7g4] } 55... e3 56. Kf1 { [%cal Gd7h3] } 56... Rb7 57. Bf5+ Kg7 58. Ke2 $10) 55... e3 56. Kf1 h3 57. a7 h2 58. Kg2 e2 59. a8=Q { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


