1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 7. Nbd2 Nge7 8. O-O Nf5 { DVD by Vidit (good but some holes in the analysis), Houska 'Opening Repertoire: Caro-Kann'. } 9. Qa4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 11. Rd1 Be7 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 O-O 14. g4?! Nh4 15. Nxh4 Bxh4 16. Qb3 Nxd4 17. Qxb6 Nxe2+ 18. Kf1 axb6 19. Kxe2 f6 20. exf6 Bxf6 $17 21. a3 Rac8 22. g5 Be5 (22... Bxb2 23. Bxb2 Rc2+ 24. Rd2 Rxf2+ 25. Kxf2 Rxd2+ 26. Ke3 Rxb2 $19) 23. Be3 { Up a pawn and White has some weaknesses - we can be patient. Single rook endings are more drawish than all other endgame types (except pure opposite-coloured bishops) } { [%csl Ge5,Ge3] } 23... Bf4?! (23... b5 { [%cal Gb6b5,Gc8c6] }) (23... Rc6 { Steadily improve the position - long-term advantages }) 24. Rac1 { I forgot about this
simple move however I am still better } 24... Bxe3 25. Rxc8?! (25. Kxe3 Rc5 { was my
intention } 26. b4 Rc6 { Kf7-e7-d6 } { [%cal Gb4b5,Gc6c5,Gg8f7,Gf7e7,Ge7d6] } 27. f4 Rfc8) 25... Rxc8 26. Kxe3 Rc2 27. Rb1 Kf7 28. a4 Kg6 29. f4 Kf5 30. h4 Rc4 31. Rf1 Re4+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


