1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 { Queen's Pawn Game 6 (Colle) Moves like 3...Bf5,
3...Bg4 and 3...g6 are all good, but allow White to transpose the game to the
Slav or Gruenfeld by 4...c4, openings which are outside our repertoire. With
the text move Black is playing the Queen's Gambit with colors reversed. The
Queen's Gambit is one of the two best ways to open for White, so even a tempo
down it should give Black at least equality. } 4. c3 { The "real" Colle system.
This is actually the Semi-Slav reversed! White now threatens to take and hold
the pawn. In a normal Semi-Slav our knight would already be developed to c6.
Here we protect the pawn by 4...Qc7, taking advantage of the fact that the
knight is not yet developed. This is an option not available to White in the
Semi-Slav! } (4. b3 cxd4 { Exchange now because White's c1 bishop cannot use two
diagonals. } 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 7. Be2 Bxf3 { Exchange before White plays
Nbd2 to thwart White's posting a knight on e5. } 8. Bxf3 g6 { Black targets the
d-pawn on the chance that White will bury his bishop with c3. } 9. O-O Bg7 10. c4 O-O { The pressure on d4, the extra center pawn and the problem of how to
develop the White knight compensate for the bishop pair. }) (4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Bg4 6. Nbd2 e6 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O Bg6 { The exchange of White's "good" bishop
ensures Black a pleasant game. }) (4. Nbd2 cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 { QGD Exchange with
colors reversed. The fact that White has blocked his queen's bishop makes this
a good choice for Black. Black will continue with ...Bf5 or ...Bg4, ...e6, ...
Bd6, ...0-0, ...Qc7, and aim at the minority attack b7-b5-b4. }) (4. dxc5 { Kaufman's main line. QGA reversed. Note that is a gambit pawn offering. 4 c4
e6 transposes to the QGD Symmetrical. } 4... e6 5. b4 (5. c4 Bxc5 6. Nc3 O-O 7. a3 (7. cxd5 exd5 { A pleasant QP game for Black because all the pieces are on the
board, which favors the side with better development and center control -
Black. }) 7... dxc4 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc4 { Boths sides have the same number of
useful moves on the board, but it is Black's turn. Therefore, Black must have
at least a microscopic edge, though a draw is likely. }) 5... a5 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+ { In a normal QGA, this would be illegal as the "e" pawn would
still be at home. This check is the attempt to justify accepting and defending
the gambit pawn. } 8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 Bd6) 4... Qc7 5. Bd3 g6 { The point of the Queen move: Black block the d3 bishop while avoiding
blocking the c8 bishop. } 6. Nbd2 Bg7 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Qe2 O-O 9. e4 { If White
omits this, Black can play ...e5 next or ...Re8, ...e5. } 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. cxd4 dxe4 { Gives Black good play against the IQP, since his bishop is already
pointing at it. }) 10... Nc5 11. e5 Nxd3 { Also good is ...Ng4 where Black's
bishop pair and White's bad bishop offset Black's shortage of space. } 12. exf6 Nxc1 13. Qxe7 Qxe7 14. fxe7 Re8 15. Raxc1 Rxe7 { We prefer Black's bishops to
White's better pawn structure. } 0-1


