{ Nakamura plays one of his 'special' blitz systems. }
1. d4 g6 (1... Nf6 2. c4 (2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Qd2 O-O 6. O-O-O c6 7. Bh6) 2... g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. g3) 2. c4 Bg7 3. g3 (3. e4 d6 4. Nc3 { Explorer - Other Player's
Games - Hikaru (username) }) 3... d6 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. O-O Qc8 { Clear
attacking plans can be quite hard to deal with in blitz chess. } 7. Re1 (7. Nc3 Bh3 8. e4 h5 (8... Bxg2 9. Kxg2) 9. d5 Ne5 10. Bxh3 Qxh3 11. Ng5 Qd7 12. f4 Nxc4 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15. fxe5+ Ke8 16. e6 Qd6 17. Qa4+) 7... Bh3 8. Bh1 { This idea is a lot less effective } (8. Nc3 h5 9. d5 Ne5 10. Bxh3 Qxh3 11. Ng5 Qd7 12. Qb3 { Engine say +1, but White has to find these very concrete and
unnatural moves to prove it (Black is doing okay). }) 8... h5 9. Nc3 h4 10. e4 (10. Nxh4 Rxh4 11. gxh4 Qg4+ { Main trick for Black. }) 10... hxg3 11. hxg3 { Black to play (P) - where are the weaknesses? } (11. fxg3 Bg4 12. Be3) 11... Bg4! { One of the main weaknesses for White } 12. Be3 { Black to play (P) - if
you're able to exchange the opponent's defending fianchettoed bishop, greatly
improves your attacking chances. } (12. Ne2 Rxh1+) 12... e5 (12... Bxd4! { Deflection example for CT-ART } 13. Bxd4 { Reversing the move order
(combinations) } 13... Rxh1+ (13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Rxh1+! { Checks and captures } 15. Kg2) 14. Kxh1 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Bxf3+ 16. Kh2 e5 17. Qd3 Qg4 18. Qf1 O-O-O 19. Qh3 Nf6 20. Qxg4+ Nxg4+ 21. Kg1 Rh8) 13. d5 Nd4 14. Bxd4 (14. Bg2) 14... exd4 15. Nb5 a6 16. Na3 (16. Nbxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Rxh1+) 16... Ne7 (16... Kf8) 17. Qd3 c5 18. dxc6 Nxc6 19. Bg2 (19. Nc2 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Ne5 21. Qd1 d3 22. Ne3 d2 23. Qxd2 (23. Rf1 Qh3) 23... Nxf3+) 19... Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Ne5 21. Qd1 d3 22. Qd2 (22. f4 Ng4) 22... Qc5 23. Rad1 Rc8 24. Re3 Bh6 25. f4 Ng4 26. Re1 Nxe3 27. Rxe3 g5 { Hikaru won by resignation } 0-1


