12... Bxd4! { Deflection! } (12... e5 { This was played in the game. }) (12... Rxh1+ { This also works, now try the 12...Bxd4 move order :) }) 13. Bxd4 Rxh1+! (13... Nxd4 { This
technically works too, but with 14.Qxd4 Rxh1 15.Kg2 White can try to struggle
on. } 14. Qxd4 Rxh1+! { Checks and captures } 15. Kg2) 14. Kxh1 Nxd4 { This works because 15.Nxd4 hangs the queen, and 15.Qxd4 (as we will see) will leave White's king too weak on the light squares. } 15. Qxd4 Bxf3+ 16. Kh2 e5 (16... Nf6 { This is also winning, now try 16...e5. }) (16... Qg4 { This move is also technically winning, but White can survive with 17.Qh8, covering the h-file. } 17. Qh8) 17. Qd3 Qg4 18. Qf1 O-O-O (18... Nf6 { This move order also wins, now try 18...0-0-0 }) 19. Qh3 Nf6 { Black is winning here due to the unstoppable attack down the
h-file. This is also why White can't trade the queens as hoped: } 20. Qxg4+ Nxg4+ 21. Kg1 Rh8 { Black mates next move with ...Rh1#. } 0-1


