[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/phY2uPn8/MaQgaXIH"]

{ Rb6 What can we take away from this game? 1) The opening is not just about
playing a general setup - it is also about setting as many problems for the
opponent as possible, limiting their options (especially as White). 2) The way
to exploit a lead in development is to open the position for our better-placed
pieces.  3) When we have a stable, long-term advantage, we don't have to be
as concerned with our opponent's counterplay, and this gives us the freedom to
improve our piece placement and execute our plans (usually in the form of a
pawn break, or some other transformation).  4) Pawn breaks are not always a
good idea - if they are ill-prepared, they may only create weaknesses in your
own position. 5) A direct confrontation tends to favour the side with
better-placed pieces.  6) If direct moves aren't working for you, look for a
way to improve your worst-placed piece.  7) It is generally a good idea to
fix your opponent's pawn weaknesses in place, so that they can't move. That
way, our pieces can then 'focus fire' on these weaknesses. Note that this can
be done with a piece (blockading an isolated or backward pawn) as well as a
pawn.  8) The way to take the initiative from the opponent is by executing
threats of our own, such as counter-threats. Note that favourable exchanges of
pieces (such as trading queens when our king is much less safe than his
counterpart) also counts as a threat.  9) It is often better to be down a
pawn, but with active pieces and threats, than with equal material but your
opponent in full control of the position (no counterplay for you).  10)
Strong positional play entails seeing small tactical 'tricks' that keep
control of the position. 11) When we have substantial long-term advantages
(such as a material advantage along with another positional advantage), we may
not need to radically change the position - using our advantages, such as by
queening a passed pawn, may prove sufficient.  12) If you have the time, you
will learn more from games by thinking about them yourself first and using the
engine only after your own analysis, to determine what you missed or failed to
appreciate in your analysis. }
1. c4 { The English Opening, which seemed to be a
slight sore point for Browne (a more tactical player) in his chess career. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 (2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 g6?! (3... e6 { is better. }) 4. Bxf6! exf6 5. Nc3 { and g3/Bg2 gave White an edge in a previous Karpov-Browne game, as Black's
d5-square is a permanent weakness, and Black has no good pawn break. }) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 { This move intends the 'Hedgehog' variation. } (3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 { is often used by Grunfeld players, as 5.d4 can potentially transpose to
Grunfeld play. } 5. d4 (5. e3!? { is the latest trend. }) 5... Nxc3 (5... e6 { transposes to the Semi-Tarrasch. }) 6. bxc3 g6 { and now 7.e4 Bg7 transposes to
a main line Grunfeld, but there are alternatives like 7.e3 and 7.Bf4 that you
may wish to explore. } 7. e3 (7. Bf4) (7. e4)) (3... Nc6 { is the other major
variation. }) 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 { White has many available plans -
Karpov opts for the most direct. } 7. d4 { Although White started with c4 and
not d4, you will usually White play the d4 central break at some point in the
game, to control the centre with pawns as well as pieces. } (7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 { is a Double Fianchetto setup that was favoured by the great technical player
Ulf Andersson. }) (7. Re1 { is more ambitious, playing for e4 and only then d4,
so that White can play cxd4 Nxd4 and avoid the exchange of light-squared
bishops. This has proven to be quite a dangerous version of the Hedgehog
structure for Black, so he usually avoids it with } 7... d5 { or starts with } (7... Ne4!? { to liquidate some pieces. })) 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4! (8. Nxd4 Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qc8 { is very solid for Black, who has no weaknesses and gets freer play with
every trade of minor pieces. }) 8... d6 (8... O-O { is the modern preference,
staying flexible and keeping ...d5 as an option in some cases. }) (8... Nc6 9. Qf4 { doesn't have the best reputation for Black, because usually the knight
belongs on d7 in the Hedgehog structure (to keep the b7-bishop's long diagonal
open). }) 9. Bg5 { The main line, creating some piece pressure while developing. } 9... a6 { Black starts with this prophylactic move, avoiding Nb5 as a means of
attacking the tender d6-pawn. With this move, Black also completes his
'Hedgehog' formation with the pawns on the sixth rank, keeping White at bay. } (9... O-O 10. Rfd1 Nbd7 11. Nb5! { forces Black to play ...d5 to save his pawn. } 11... d5 12. cxd5 { Black is not entirely ready for this opening of the position. } 12... Bxd5 (12... exd5 { We have reached an IQP position, where Black's pieces
(particularly the b7-bishop and d7-knight) are not well placed for action.
White can already take the initiative with } 13. Nh4! { , threatening Nf5 but
also intending Nc3 to gang up on the weak d5-pawn. }) 13. Nc3 Bc6 14. Qc4 { White has some initiative here because of his lead in development. Black has
to be a bit careful that the c6-square doesn't become a weakness after some
Nd4(e5)-c6 in an endgame. A classic example of that situation is
Botvinnik-Donner, Amsterdam 1963. }) 10. Bxf6 { The standard approach, luring
Black's bishop away so that the d6-pawn is vulnerable to attack. } (10. Rfd1 Nbd7 { allows Black to complete his minor piece placement, not giving White a
productive way to attack d6 and use his current lead in development. }) 10... Bxf6 11. Qf4 { The queen is most active on f4, eyeing the d6-pawn. Now Browne
falters. } 11... Bxf3 { Not the best approach - White's bishop will be better than
Black's in the arising play. } (11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 { is very good for White, as
Black has a hard time defending his d6-pawn after Rfd1. Also note the tactical
point } 12... e5? 13. Nxe5! dxe5 14. Qxe5+) (11... O-O { is the best move,
developing normally. Then } 12. Rfd1 Be7 13. Ne4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 Ra7 15. Nd4 $14 { gives White a small but persistent advantage, as the b8-knight is stuck
covering against Nc6, and White can steadily improve his position, eventually
going for a4-a5 or a kingside pawn storm when all his pieces are on the right
squares. This variation explains why most GMs nowadays favour 8...0-0. }) 12. Bxf3 { Now the play is similar to after 11...0-0. } (12. exf3 { is more precise,
since the pawn will be very annoying for Black on f4. } 12... Ra7 13. Rfd1 Rd7 14. Qe3 O-O 15. f4 { is a natural continuation for both sides, where Black struggles to
find a reliable source of counterplay. If he plays the thematic break } 15... b5 16. cxb5 axb5 { , White has the thematic pawn break (and sacrifice) } 17. f5! exf5 18. Rab1 { , leaving Black's b5 and d6-pawns ripe for plucking. Now we
understand the difference the pawn on f4 makes! }) 12... Ra7 13. Rfd1 Be5 { It would be easy to criticise this move based on the result, but Browne's real
mistake comes later. } (13... Rd7 14. Qd2 (14. Rd3 O-O 15. Rad1 Bg5 { keeps d6
safe. }) 14... O-O 15. Rac1 { was the alternative, when Black's game seems fully
playable after } 15... Qc7 { , as he has no bad pieces or serious weaknesses.
Furthermore, with two sets of minor pieces traded already, White's space
advantage is not a serious factor. }) 14. Qd2 { Keeping the piece pressure on d6. } 14... O-O 15. Rac1 b5?! { In retrospect, this pawn break, while thematic for this
variation, doesn't seem well timed here. } (15... Rd7 { and ...Qc7/...Rc8 should
still give Black a fine game. }) (15... Qc7 { and ... Rc8 seems less precise to
me, as the a7-rook will be stuck out of play for a while. }) 16. Qe3 { A good
move, targeting Black's undefended rook. Tactics flow from a good position! } (16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 (17. a3 Qb6 { also gives Black counterplay, with ...b4
in mind to again undermine White's centre. }) 17... Rxa2 { suits Black well, as
the b2-pawn is a bit exposed and if White defends it, ... d5 may follow. }) 16... Rd7 { The rook moves here to block the pin on Black's d6-pawn (to the
queen). } (16... Rc7 17. cxb5 axb5 { might be well met with } 18. Qb6 { , when
Black has a hard time defending his b5-pawn. If } 18... Rc5 { White has the trick } 19. Qxc5 dxc5 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Nxb5 Bxb2 22. Rxc5 { winning a pawn. Yes, there are
opposite-coloured bishops, but with the addition of rooks and knights, this
gives the stronger side excellent practical chances to win. }) 17. cxb5 { White is better developed, so the opening of the position is likely to play in
his favour. } (17. c5 { is interesting, but I think Karpov's move is stronger,
creating a clear weakness in Black's camp. }) 17... axb5 { b5-pawn is isolated - moving target, harder to win the pawn
One of the main ways to exploit a weakness - fix the weakness and only then attack it } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb1b5] } 18. Nxb5 (18. Qd3 { [%csl Gb5] } 18... b4 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gb4c3,Ge5b2] }) (18. b4! { Great
technique, fixing the opponent's weaknesses. } { [%csl Gb5,Gb2][%cal Gc3b5] } 18... Bxc3 { A natural decision, as other moves just lose the
b5-pawn, and it's not clear what Black's compensation would be. } { [%csl Gb5] } 19. Rxc3 { White looks to have a clear advantage, as his f3-bishop is far superior to the
b8-knight (which can only move to the ugly a6 square). Furthermore, Black
can't easily harmonise his major pieces, and the b5-pawn is vulnerable, as
noted before. } { When we attack their weaknesses, we often force concessions from the opponent to defend their weak pawns
- gave up their good bishop for our knight } { [%csl Gf3,Gb8][%cal Gf3a8] } 19... Qf6 { is a
logical alternative, but after } (19... Na6 20. a3 { [%csl Ga3,Gb4,Ga6][%cal Ga6b4] }) (19... d5 { After this move, Black loses a pawn. } { White can attack the weak pawn more easily } { [%cal Gc5b5] } 20. Qd3 { is weaker, as
after } (20. Qc5! { One key moment - b4 set up the whole win for Karpov, b5-pawn could be focused down } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gc5b5,Gd7b7,Ge2e4,Gd1d8] } 20... Qf6 (20... Rb7 21. e4 { is very strong, exploiting the pin against
Black's queen. If } 21... Nd7 { White should simply keep up the piece pressure with } 22. Qd4 { and Black is in trouble, as dxe4 Bxe4 would win Black's knight on d7. } (22. Qc6 Rb6 23. Qc7 { is weaker because of the tactical point } 23... Qxc7 24. Rxc7 Ne5! { and Black saves himself: } 25. Be2 dxe4 26. Rc5 Nd3 27. Bxd3 exd3 28. Rxd3 { and the endgame is holdable for Black. })) 21. Rdc1 d4?! { Black relies
on central counterplay, giving up on trying to save the b5-pawn. However, it
doesn't work out in the game, so this might have been Black's last chance to
try and hold the position. } (21... Rb7 { The natural move and probably best. } 22. e4 { I initially thought this move was just winning, but it's not so simple: } 22... Nd7 (22... dxe4 23. Bxe4 { forces the b7-rook away from its defensive role,
winning the b5-pawn. }) 23. Qc6 (23. Qd6 { can be met with } 23... d4!) 23... Ra7 { and exd5 is met with Ne5! } 24. Qxb5 Ne5 { and suddenly, Black has real
counterplay. } 25. Be2 (25. Bg2 Rxa2 26. Qf1 { gives Black a choice between ...
d4, which is probably what I'd do, and ...dxe4. }) 25... Rxa2 26. exd5 Ng4! { for instance shows how easily White can lose control. }) 22. Rd3 { Karpov keeps
Black tied down to his pawns. } 22... e5 23. Qxb5 { Now White is technically winning,
with an extra pawn and a bad Black knight on b8. The winning plan is to simply
queen the connected passed pawns and make good exchanges. } 23... Qe6 (23... Re8 { may be a better try, though ...e4 is still not a threat because of Bxe4! }) 24. Rc5 { A strong move, to meet ...e4 with Re5. } 24... Re7 { A bit passive, though it's
not easy to offer Black great advice by now. } (24... e4 25. Re5 Qxa2 26. Rxe4 { leaves the d4-pawn too weak. True, it is not threatened yet because of Qa1+,
but White can play Kg2/Qb6 and leave Black short of a great move or plan.
Perhaps the b-pawn will not win by itself, but White can play moves like
h4-h5-h6 to weaken Black's king, or even play e3 to open up the position at a
good moment. }) 25. Bd5 { The bishop is a beast on this square! } 25... Qd6 26. a4 { Even here, it is hard for Black to coordinate, as ... Nd7 runs into Rc6. } 26... Kh8 { Harbouring hopes of ...f5-f4 or ...e4, but it comes to naught. } (26... h5 { and ...h4-h3 is probably how I would try to swindle, even though it does
nothing. }) 27. Qc4 { White clears the way for the pawns to advance. I also like } (27. e3 { , trading off Black's most advanced pawn and bringing the other rook
into action. }) 27... Qd8 (27... Nd7 28. Rc6 Qb8 29. a5 { (stopping ...Nb6) is
too much for Black to handle. }) 28. a5 Nd7 29. Rc6 { Black's position is
completely hopeless - he has no defence to the steady advance of the queenside
passers. } 29... e4 { Desperation, but Black was already lost by this point. } 30. Rxd4 Ne5 31. Qc5 Rd7 { Black resigned without waiting for 32.Ra6/32.Rb6. White is
two pawns up for nothing and will win effortlessly. } (31... Nxc6 32. Bxc6 Qc7 33. Rd7! { is White's point, exploiting Black's weak back rank. })) 20... Qb6 21. Rc5 Rb7 { Black is ready to kick the rook away with ...Na6/...
Nd7. }) 20. Rdc1 { it is still not easy to deal with
Qb6xb5.20...d5 21.Qb6 would transpose to the game, for instance. } 20... Na6 { is well
met with } 21. a3 { , leaving the knight completely out of play. Next Qb6 or Rc6
will ask some tough questions of Black. }) 18... Bxb2 { looks very
playable for Black, as the a-pawn may prove more a weakness than a strength in
the middlegame. } 1-0


