{ HWK: How did fixing Black's weaknesses help White to win? Why was it important to fix the weakness? Why was the bishop so much better than the knight? }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qc7 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 a6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Bf4 d6 11. Qd2 h6 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 Bg4 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. f3 Be6 16. f4 { Despite the roughly symmetrical position, White has
long-term initiative. Soon, the game transposed into the ending that looked
fine for Black. } 16... Rd8 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 e4 19. Rfe1 Rxd5 20. Rxe4+! Kd8 21. Qe2 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1+ Qd7 23. Qxd7+ Kxd7 24. Re5 { Turns out that Black's
woes are only beginning. Their pieces are too passive. } 24... b6? { Black didn't
sense the danger and made a small, but very significant pawn weakness. } (24... Kd6 25. b4! { , it's still far from
equality for Black. } (25. Bxb7 Rb8 26. Bxa6 Rxb2 27. Bc4 Rxc2 28. Bxf7 c4 { , and the worst is over for Black })) 25. Bf1 a5 26. Bc4 Rf8 27. Kg2 Kd6 28. Kf3 Nd7 29. Re3 Nb8 30. Rd3+ Kc7 31. c3 Nc6 32. Re3 Kd6 33. a4 { An instructive
position! There are few pieces, a lot of space on the board, but still,
Black's position becomes more and more stifled. } 33... Ne7 34. h3 Nc6 { Much easier for Fischer to later get around and attack Black's pawns with teh bishop once they were fixed on the light squares } { [%csl Gb6,Ga5,Gc5][%cal Gf7f5,Gg7g6,Gh6h5] } 35. h4 h5 36. Rd3+ Kc7 37. Rd5 f5 38. Rd2 Rf6 39. Re2 Kd7 40. Re3 g6 41. Bb5 Rd6 { Here, the
game was adjourned. The conversion of the advantage is a masterpiece of
technique and home analysis. } 42. Ke2 Kd8 43. Rd3! { White evaluate the
position correctly and transpose into the minor piece endgame, where the
Bishop is stronger than the Knight. The Black get into zugzwang, and White
destroy the Black pawns with a Bishop sacrifice. } 43... Kc7 44. Rxd6 Kxd6 45. Kd3 Ne7 { Pawn ending is won for White, so Black need to avoid the exchange. } 46. Be8 Kd5 47. Bf7+ Kd6 48. Kc4 Kc6 49. Be8+ Kb7 50. Kb5 { Potential infiltration } { [%csl Gb6,Ga6,Gc6][%cal Gb5a6,Gb5c6] } 50... Nc8 51. Bc6+ Kc7 52. Bd5 Ne7 53. Bf7 Kb7 54. Bb3 Ka7 55. Bd1 Kb7 56. Bf3+ Kc7 57. Ka6 Ng8 58. Bd5 Ne7 (58... Nf6 { didn't help either due to } 59. Bf7 Ne4 60. Bxg6 Nxg3 61. Kb5 { etc. }) 59. Bc4 Kc6 60. Bf7 Kc7 61. Be8 Kd8 62. Bxg6! { The decisive Bishop sacrifice,
for which White get three pawns. The Knight, with its short jumps, turns out
to be completely useless against the pawns. } 62... Nxg6 63. Kxb6 Kd7 64. Kxc5 Ne7 65. b4 axb4 66. cxb4 Nc8 67. a5 Nd6 68. b5 Ne4+ 69. Kb6 Kc8 70. Kc6 Kb8 71. b6 { Black resigned. } 1-0


