1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. O-O O-O 9. Nh4 Nbd7 10. h3 Rc8 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. Qf3 g6 { Diagram [#] Black's
doubled f-pawns are restricting the mobility of White's forces. With his next
move Cheparinov aims to open the position for his Bs. } { In a lot of positions, the best way to exploit the doubled pawns is to exchange them.
- often they've left some weak squares behind when they have the doubled pawns
Doubled pawns as a 'hook' for activating your own pieces } 13. g4! fxg4 14. hxg4 { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gg1g2,Gf1h1,Gg4g5,Gc3e4] } 14... Be7 (14... h5 15. gxh5 Nxh5 { and White could have retained a clear advantage had he played } 16. Qg2!) (14... Qe7 { might be Black's best option. }) 15. Kg2 Nb6 16. Bb3 Qd7 17. a5 Na8 (17... Nbd5 { White has } 18. e4 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Qxg4+ 20. Qxg4 Nxg4 21. Rb1 $16 { and White has excellent compensation for the P because
of his massive centre, pair of Bs and the backward P on b7. }) 18. g5 Ne8 19. Ne4 Nac7 20. Rh1 Nd5 21. Bd2 Ng7 22. Rh3 { and White went on to convert his
overwhelming advantage. } 22... h5 23. gxh6 Ne6 24. Kh1 Kh7 25. Qg2 Rcd8 26. Rg1 Rg8 27. f4 f5 28. Nc3 g5 29. Bc2 Rdf8 30. Qg4 Nec7 31. fxg5 Rxg5 32. Qf3 Kh8 33. Rxg5 Bxg5 34. Qh5 Ne6 35. Nxd5 Qxd5+ 36. Qf3 Qxf3+ 37. Rxf3 f4 38. Bc3 Bf6 39. Bb3 Re8 40. Bxe6 Rxe6 41. Rxf4 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


