[ECO "D46"]
[Opening "Semi-Slav Defense: Chigorin Defense"]
[StudyName "Craze's Study"]
[ChapterName "Which File to Open?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/phY2uPn8/btVDWyUf"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "23:42:16"]

{ It's something you have to answer yourself using your understanding of the position, calculation of variations

Generally you want to open a file on the side where you're stronger - activates your pieces as much as possible }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 { a) You can play it without much preparation (convenient)
b) Improves a lot of pieces at once
c) Threats - e5 pawn fork (initiative)
Assessing a pawn break
a) How hard is it to get in? (if they have no counterplay, less relevant)
b) How much does it improve the pieces (how many pieces does it improve)
c) Does it take the initiative? (what threats do you have after this break) } { [%cal Gc1h6,Ge4e5] } 8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3h7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8] } *


