1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { Move 6 is often a good time to break with ...f6 } (3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 { Play f6 around move 7-8 } 5. c3 c5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ne2 (7. Ngf3 f6 (7... g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. Re1 O-O { Specific idea (don't see this in any other variations) } { [%cal Gf7f6,Gf6e5,Gc5d4,Gc3d4,Gg7d4] })) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 { If you don't get rid of the e5-pawn, White will play 0-0/f4/Nf3.
Knights on d2 and e2 - Nf3 and have both knights defend the d4-pawn } { [%cal Ge1g1,Gf2f4,Gd2f3] } 8... f6! { [%csl Ge6,Gc5,Gc3][%cal Ge2f4,Gc6d4,Gd4e6,Gf4e6] } (8... Qb6?! 9. Nf3 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gf3d4] })) (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 { Usually not playing ...f6 in these positions (unless you have to in the middlegame, e.g. to not get mated with a kingside attack) } 5. f4 c5 { Steinitz Variation - not to play an early ...f6 (middlegame) } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gb8c6,Ga7a6,Gb7b4] }) 3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 { [%csl Gf1,Gd3][%cal Gf7f6] } (5... Qb6 6. a3 { [%csl Gb6] } 6... f6 { [%cal Gf6e5] } 7. exf6 (7. Bd3 fxe5 8. dxe5 Qc7 { e5-pawn is a bit vulnerable, pawns side by side on c5 and d5 } { [%csl Ge5,Gd5,Gc5][%cal Gc8d7,Ge8c8] } 9. Bf4 c4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gf8c5,Gg8e7,Ge8g8] }) 7... Nxf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] }) 6. Be2 f6 { Williams recommended this in a book for Black } { [%cal Gf6e5,Gd8c7,Ge8c8] } *


