1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 { A solid approach against
the Berlin variation of the Ruy Lopez. White regains the pawn, maintaining a
symmetric structure but keeping the more comfortable position since Black has
to place his knight on the awkward d6-square. Most of the time, Black
equalizes with a few precise moves. } 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bf1 Nxe5 8. Rxe5 O-O 9. d4 (9. Nc3 Ne8 10. Nd5 Bd6 11. Re1 c6 12. Ne3 Bc7 13. Nf5 d5 14. Ne7+ Kh8 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 { White has gained the bishop pair, but Black is left with a very
solid position. } 16. d4 Nf6 17. Be3 Qd7 18. f3 Rce8 19. Qd2 Kg8 20. Bf2 Nh5 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Re1 Rxe1 23. Qxe1 g6 24. a4 Nf4 25. b4 a6 26. a5 { 1/2-1/2 (26)
Shirov,A (2676)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2711) Al Ain 2015 }) 9... Bf6 10. Re1 Re8 11. Nc3!? $146 { A novelty in this position which already occured once by a
transposition of moves. White sacrifices the d4-pawn in order to obtain some
initiative. } (11. c3 { is the normal move, after what Black gets time to solve
his development issues } 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Ne8 13. Bf4 d5 14. Bd3 g6 15. Nd2 Ng7 16. Nf3 Bf5 { 1/2-1/2 (30) Carlsen,M (2834)-Kramnik,V (2796) Doha 2015 }) 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 b6 (12... Bxd4 { has to be the most challenging. Black wasn't in
the mood to check his opponent's preparation and didn't accept the sacrifice. } 13. Bf4 (13. Nd5!? $146 c6 14. Bf4 cxd5 15. Bxd6 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Bf6 17. Qd1 Be7 18. Qxd5 Bxd6 19. Qxd6 Qf8 20. Qc7 $44) 13... Ne8 14. Nd5 c6 (14... d6 15. Bg5 f6 16. Bc4 fxg5 (16... Kh8 17. Qe4) 17. Nxc7+ Kh8 18. Nxa8 $13) 15. Ne7+ Kf8 16. Nxc8 Qf6 17. Bg3 (17. Qb4+!? c5 18. Qd2 Rxc8 19. Re1 $44) 17... Rxc8 18. Qb4+ d6 19. Qxb7 Rc7 20. Qb8 Bxb2 21. Bxd6+ Qxd6 22. Qxb2 Re7 { and Black was
able to equalize - } 23. Rb1 Qc5 24. Bd3 { 1/2-1/2 (24) Kravtsiv,M (2565)
-Kryvoruchko,Y (2692) Jerusalem 2015 }) (12... c6 { allows something like } 13. d5!?) 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Bxd6 cxd6 { Now White has a clear plan: play against this
weakened structure, limiting especially the b7-bishop. } 15. Qe3 { Re1 is coming,
I don't see many options for Black besides ...Qe7. } 15... Qe7 16. Qxe7 Bxe7 17. g3 Kf8 18. a4!? (18. Bg2!? { is a possible idea, Black would have to play } 18... Bc6 { , and then something like a4 would be similar to the game I guess. }) 18... Bc6 (18... a6 19. Bg2 Bxg2 (19... Bc6 20. Nd5 Bd8 (20... Bxd5 21. Bxd5 $16 { with an excellent endgame. }) 21. c3 $14 { keeping the better chances }) 20. Kxg2 { is very bad for Black, the threat is Nd5, totally dominating the passive
bishop: } 20... Rc8 21. Kf3 d5 { The only move to avoid suffocation. } 22. Ke3 Rc4 23. Kd3 Bf6 24. Ne2 $16) 19. a5 (19. Ba6!? Rb8 (19... d5 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. Bxb5 Bf6 22. c3 Ke7 23. a5 Rb8 24. Re1+ Kd6 25. a6 $14 { is comfortable for White,
though it's not easy to make progress. }) 20. d5 Bb7 21. Bxb7 Rxb7 22. Nd1 $14) 19... bxa5 20. d5 Bb7 21. Rxa5 a6 22. Ra3 Bf6 23. Na4!? Ke7 24. c4 (24. Nb6!? Rb8 (24... Bxb2 25. Re3+ Kd8 26. Nxa8 $18) 25. c3 Kd8 26. Bh3 Bc8 27. Nc4 Kc7 28. Ra2 Bb7 29. Bg2 $14) 24... Kd8 25. Re3 a5 26. Be2 Ba6 27. Kf1 Rb8 28. b3 { At the cost of weakening many dark squares, White has succeeded in leaving the
a6-bishop totally out of the game. The next part of the game still is very
complicated. } 28... g5?! { I don't get this idea, besides the fact that it
potentially creates serious weaknesses on the kingside. } (28... g6 $13 { With a move like this one I don't know exactly how White would improve his
position, even though he clearly has the best chances. Maybe taking his king
to the queenside and then somehow relocating the knight from a4 could be an
idea, but then ...a4 from Black has to be observed. }) 29. Ke1 Bd4 30. Rf3 Ke7 31. Bd1 h6 32. Kd2 Rb4 33. Kd3 Ba7 34. Rf5 { Highlighting one of the problems
with 28...g5?! } 34... f6 35. Nc3 Bc5 36. f4 Rb8 37. fxg5 fxg5 38. Kc2 Bg1?! (38... Rf8!? { was required, entering an awkard endgame, but I don't see clearly how
White can convert it into a full point. For example: } 39. Rxf8 Kxf8 40. Kd3 Ke7 41. Ne4 Bg1 42. h3 Bh2 43. Bh5 Bg1 (43... Bb7? 44. Kc3 $18 { Kb2-Ka3-Ka4 is
coming }) 44. g4! Bh2 45. Nc3 Kf6 46. Ne2 Be5! (46... Ke5 47. Nd4 Kf6 48. Nf5 Bf4 49. Be8 Bc8 50. Nxh6 Ke7 51. Bg6 $18) 47. Nd4 Bxd4 48. Kxd4 Bb7 49. Kc3 Ba6 50. Be8 Ke7 51. Bg6 Kd8 { running to b6, to avoid Kb2-Ka3-Ka4. }) 39. Bh5?! (39. Rf1! { would avoid the rook exchange - if Black takes on h2, then he
has problems to escape with his bishop - } 39... Bc5 { and now start all over with Bg4
or Bh5. } (39... Bxh2 40. Re1+ Kd8 41. Ne4 a4 42. Kc3 axb3 43. Bxb3 Kc7 44. Rh1 Re8 45. Kd4 Rxe4+ 46. Kxe4 Bxg3 47. Rxh6 $16 { with good winning chances. })) 39... Bxh2? (39... Rf8 40. Rxf8 Kxf8 41. h3 { would transpose to 38...Kf8 and
was definitely a better chance than the game continuation, which involved
enormous risks and is actually simply lost for Black. }) 40. Rf7+ Kd8 41. Bg4! Rb7 (41... Bxg3 42. Ne4 Be5 43. Rxd7+ Ke8 44. Nxd6+ $18 { and everything
collapses. }) 42. c5?! (42. Ne4! a4 (42... Rc7 43. Nxd6 a4 44. Nb5! Bxb5? (44... axb3+ 45. Kb2 Rxc4 46. Rxd7+ Kc8 47. Nd6+ Kb8 48. Nxc4 $18) 45. d6 $18) 43. c5! axb3+ 44. Kb2 $18 dxc5 45. d6 { with mate to follow. }) 42... Bxg3 43. Ne4 dxc5 (43... Rc7!? 44. Nxg3 Rxc5+ 45. Kb2 Bb5 $16 { with chances to survive. }) 44. Nxg3 d6 45. Rf8+ Ke7 46. Ra8 Rb6? (46... Bd3+! 47. Kc3 (47. Kxd3? Rxb3+ 48. Ke4 Rxg3 { and Black has hopes to escape }) 47... Bg6 { threatening to
'run' with ...Kf6-Ke5 } 48. Rxa5 Kf6 49. Ra1 $16) 47. Kc3 $18 { Now White has a
deadly attack. } 47... Bb7 48. Nf5+ Kf6 49. Rf8+ Ke5 50. Ne3 Ke4 51. Nc4 Ra6 { A
classy finish - Ponomariov allows a very pretty checkmate in the center of the
board! } 52. Bf3# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } 1-0


