{ My System by Nimzowitsch - concepts are fairly simple (this is when you exploit the open file, how to exploit it) - version by New In Chess

Simple Chess by Michael Stean (breaks down the types of advantages)

How to assess the position:

1. Who has control of the game? (clearly one side, they are almost certainly better)
2. Long-term advantages (material, better minor pieces, better pawn structure)
3. Who has the pawn weaknesses, whose pawns are easier to attack
4. Who has the more harmonious position? - whose pieces work together better to achieve a common goal?

Dynamic positions

- Who has the threats?
- Who can attack the king more easily?
- Who has more options? }
 *


