[Event "Beating The Berlin!: Beating The Berlin! Introduction"]
[Date "2021.05.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation"]
[StudyName "Beating The Berlin!"]
[ChapterName "Beating The Berlin! Introduction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/PivSzZCh/u9VPMPof"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2021.05.31"]
[UTCTime "11:57:31"]

{ What's up guys!

In this Lichess Study, I'm going to show you how to beat the Berlin!

The Berlin is a variation of the Ruy Lopez, arising after the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish Opening. } 3... Nf6 { Black doesn't just develop his knight actively, but also pressures the e4-pawn. This explains our next move. } 4. d3! { With this move, we defend our e4-pawn from attack, while renewing the threat of Bxc6 and Nxe5 to win a pawn. } 4... Bc5 { The usual move, developing the bishop actively and also stopping White from winning a pawn. } (4... d6 { is also possible, but leaves Black in an inferior version of a normal Spanish after } 5. O-O { and the standard Lopez moves. } { [%cal Gf1e1,Gc2c3,Gb1d2,Gh2h3,Gb5a4] }) 5. Bxc6! { This is my recommendation. The idea is not to win a pawn, but rather , to double Black's pawns and thereby make Black's pawn structure a lot less flexible. } 5... dxc6 6. Nbd2! { With this move, we prepare Nc4 to pressure the vulnerable pawn on e5, and can meet Black's kingside castling (...0-0) with a kingside pawn storm and a very strong kingside attack. Check out the next game, Wei Yi-Navara, to find out more! } (6. Nxe5? { would be a mistake because of the } 6... Qd4 { fork, when White is unable to defend both f2 and e5 at once. } { [%cal Gd4f2,Gd4e5] }) *


[Event "Tata Steel-A 78th"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee"]
