[Event "A guide to Catalan: Main ideas"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Štěpán Soukup"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E04"]
[Opening "Catalan Opening: Open Defense"]
[StudyName "A guide to Catalan"]
[ChapterName "Main ideas"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0Ue8aUb0/HwADeVel"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "20:50:00"]

{ Savielly Tartakower created an opening idea at the Barcelona tournament of 1929 as a tribute to the region of Catalonia. Later, the Catalan became defined as a specific opening structure.
Catalan is usually played for people that like rapid development, you don't worry to have given up a pawn when u have a crushing position }
1. d4 d5 { [%cal Gg2g3,Gg1f3,Gf1g2,Gc2c4] } (1... c5 { you can't play catalan against the benoni }) (1... g6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 { Panno variation of the KID }) (1... e6 2. c4 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 { catalan }) (1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 { [%cal Gf8b4,Gb7b6,Gg1f3] } 3. g3 { avoiding most of the lines (bogo indian, queens indian, ragozin setup, vienna) } (3. Nf3 { allows bogo indian and queens indian } 3... d5 4. g3) 3... d5 (3... c5 { avoiding the catalan, again } 4. d5 (4. Nf3 { transposing into Reti/English } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 d5 6. Bg2) 4... exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 { fiancetto benoni, ton of separate theory }) (3... Bb4+ { sort of bogo indian fashion } 4. Bd2 { good for black that don't want to learn how to beat the catalan } { [%cal Gd8e7,Gb4e7] } 4... Be7 5. Bg2 d5 { white bishop is missplaced } { [%csl Gd2] }) 4. Nf3) 2. c4 e6 (2... c6 3. Nf3 { importatnt to avoid the Winaver gambit } 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. a4 Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 { another way to meet the slav }) 3. Nf3 (3. g3 dxc4 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 { Not that I recommend you to play this, but white is usually very easy to regain to pawn back and hes trading a d7 pawn for c2 pawn, which should favor him } { [%csl Gc2,Gd7,Rd4,Re2,Re6] }) 3... Nf6 4. g3 { The ambitious open lines carry a looot of risks for black
if white knows what hes doing and plays forcefully it can really crush your opponent
if black plays solidly, in a more classic fashion, it can lead to more passive and defensive position } 4... dxc4 (4... Be7 { Leads to positional lines which turn out to be pretty passive for black }) 5. Bg2 { This is the open catalan. Let's pinpoint a few things.
Black is up a pawn, but his pawns are doubled and in theory are shown to be really weak.
White has a powerful catalan bishop. } { [%csl Gc4,Gc7][%cal Gg2a8] } (5. Qa4+ { we'll talk about this move at the very end of this study }) *


[Event "A guide to Catalan: 4... dxc4 - 5... b5 - 7... Nd5"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Štěpán Soukup"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E04"]
[Opening "Catalan Opening: Open Defense"]
[StudyName "A guide to Catalan"]
[ChapterName "4... dxc4 - 5... b5 - 7... Nd5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0Ue8aUb0/Ft7TyjIY"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "20:50:00"]

{ So if you are looking for just the best moves for white, follow the main line till move 8, I firstly discussed just this line, but now I've added and went through more options in the opening phase }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 { kinda busted for black, there's a huge danger of getting super-destroyed real fast, black will be forced to play moves that aren't furthering up his development and that can be met with a crushing attack } 5. Bg2 b5 { big danger on diagonal } { [%csl Gc6,Ge5,Gd7,Gf7][%cal Gg2a8,Gf3e5] } 6. a4 { not so easy to defened } (6. Ne5 { Less common move } 6... Nd5 7. a4 c6 8. O-O Bb7 9. e4 Nf6 10. Nc3 a6 11. d5 Be7 { safest option } (11... cxd5 12. exd5 exd5 (12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. axb5 Bc5 15. Be3 Bxe3 16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. fxe3+ Kg8 18. e4 { it's all over }) 13. Ng4 { black is collapsing } 13... Ne4 14. Re1) 12. dxe6 (12. Nxf7 Kxf7 13. dxe6+ Kxe6 14. Qf3) 12... fxe6 13. Qe2 { theoretical move }) 6... c6 (6... b4 { tactical mistake, white can take the pawn back } 7. Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4] }) (6... a6 { black cant take back } 7. Ne5 { an improvement } (7. axb5 { [%cal Ga1a8] }) 7... Ra7 8. axb5 { [%cal Ga1a7] }) (6... Bd7 7. Ne5) (6... Bb7) 7. Ne5 (7. axb5 { another option, which I don't recommend, but here are some lines: } 7... cxb5 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. Nc3 { two options for black } { [%cal Gf7f6,Gf8b4] } 9... Bb4 (9... f6 10. Ng4 Bb7 11. e4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bd6 13. Rb1) 10. O-O Bxc3 11. e4 Bxb2 12. Bxb2 Ne7 13. d5 (13. Nxf7)) (7. O-O { another option, but it allows black to play Bb7 } 7... Bb7 8. b3 { not as strong of a gambit as in the main line } (8. Ne5 { gives black three options } 8... a6 { we again have the option of playing b3 } { [%cal Ga6b5,Gb2b3] } (8... Qc8 { most interesting, white has to go for } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 9. b3 cxb3 { full pawn gambit } 10. Qxb3 b4 11. a5 c5 12. Qa4+ Nbd7 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Bb2 { white should have enough for the pawn, but its hard to play }) (8... Nd5 9. e4 Nf6 10. Nc3 a6 11. d5 { reached by the same position by transposition } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gc6d5] }) 9. Nc3 (9. b3 cxb3 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Nd3 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb7c6,Gb7a6,Gb7c8,Gc8e6] } 11... Qb6 12. Qxb3 Be7 13. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c2,Gc2c5,Ga1c1] }) 9... Nd5 10. e4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nd7 { two options and both are very tricky } { [%cal Ge5d7,Gf2f4] } 12. Nxd7 (12. f4 Be7 13. Ng4 (13. Qg4) 13... O-O 14. e5 Nb6 15. f5 exf5 16. Ne3 g6 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. Rxf5 { very hard to defend for black again } { [%cal Gg2e4,Ge4h7] } 18... Kh8 19. Be4 Nd5 20. Rh5 f5 21. exf6 Nxf6 22. Rxh7+ Nxh7 23. Qh5) 12... Qxd7 13. Be3 a5 14. Qh5 b4 15. d5 { [%csl Ge3,Gg2,Gh5,Gd1,Ge1] } 15... exd5 16. exd5 { only one move that is equal } 16... cxd5 (16... Bd6 17. Bd4 O-O { its equal, but I wouldn't want to play it as black } 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+) 17. Bd4 Be7 18. Bh3 { [%cal Gf1e1] }) 8... cxb3 9. Qxb3 b4 10. Ne5 Be7 11. Bb2 Qc7 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc6c4,Gd8c8] } (11... Qc8)) 7... Nd5 { forced to move the same piece twice, which he would like to avoid } (7... Bb4+ { I will be making a part on this move. }) (7... Bb7) 8. O-O Bb7 9. e4 { Nd5 blocking the diagonal gave us a tempo now } 9... Nf6 10. b3 { b3 key strategical move } (10. d5 { decent move } 10... Be7 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Nc3 { with tempo } 12... a6 13. b3 { needs to open up } 13... Nfd7) 10... cxb3 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Qxb3 { with tempo } 12... a6 13. d5 { There are three lines that we will go through } { [%cal Gd8b6,Ge6d5,Gf8d6] } 13... Bd6 { Giri - Morozevich } (13... Qb6 { two Russian grandmasters, instructive game } { [%cal Gb6e6] } 14. Nc4 Qd4 { Again, when attacking, don't slow down unless you have to } (14... Qc7 15. Na5 e5 16. Be3 Bd6 17. Rc1 Qe7 18. f3 { a lil weird move, kinda not standard, because u're opening the diagonal } { [%cal Rg1a7] } (18. Nd2 { more natural }) 18... Qd7 19. Bc5 { taking away c7 and achieving to infiltrate } (19. Bh3 Qxh3 20. Nxb7 Qd7 21. Nxd6+ Qxd6 22. Rc8+) 19... Bxc5+ (19... Bc7) 20. Rxc5 Bc8 (20... Qd8 { the punishment of f3 which was not found } 21. Nxb7 Qb6 { [%cal Gb6g1,Bf2f3] }) 21. Qc3 O-O 22. Rc7 Qe8 23. Nd2 Nbd7 24. Nc6 Kh8 25. Nb3 Ng8 26. Rc1 f6 27. Na7 Nb6 28. Qc6) 15. Nba3 Bxa3 16. Nxa3 Qxa1 17. Bb2 Qxf1+ 18. Kxf1 { When we exchange a piece we want to achieve something in return, such as destroying the pawn shield protecting our opponents king } 18... exd5 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. exd5 O-O (20... Nd7 21. Qe3+ { [%cal Ga3c2,Gc2d4,Gd4f5] }) 21. Nc4 bxc4 22. Qxb7) (13... exd5 { main line } 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Qe3 { very difficult for black } (15. Bxd5 Qxd5 { bad for white }) 15... Qe7 (15... Be7 16. Rd1 { losing for black } { [%cal Gd1d8] }) 16. Ba3 { with tempo } { [%cal Ga3f8] } 16... Qe6 17. Re1) 14. Nxf7 Kxf7 15. dxe6+ Ke8 16. e5 { blacks king is in trouble } 16... Bxg2 17. exf6 (17. Kxg2 { dont slow down too early, BAD MOVE }) 17... Qxf6 (17... Bxf1 18. fxg7 (18. e7 Qc8 19. fxg7) 18... Rg8 19. e7) 18. Kxg2 { forcing black to take even more material } 18... Qxa1 19. Nc3 { [%csl Ga4,Gd5][%cal Gc1b2,Gc3e4] } (19. Bb2 { worse move, allows Qa4, allows black counterplay } 19... Qa4) 19... Be5 20. Nd5 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 20... Qd4 (20... Qa4) 21. Ba3 Qe4+ 22. f3 Qa4 23. Rc1!! { brilliant move } *


