1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 b5 6. a4 c6 7. Ne5 Bb4+ { This move hasn't been played that much and I think I could see it happening on lower ratings } 8. Nc3 { The main move has to be Nc3 } (8. Bd2 { the problem of Bd2 could be that unlike in 4.Bb4+ line, black cannot afford going Be7 now. he has to take, which means the line isn't similar and unlike in that line, Bxd2+ isn't a bad move. } 8... Bxd2+) 8... Nd5 { covering the long diagonal and hanging c6 pawn and here white has few options: O-O, Bd2 and axb2 (Qc2 seems to be too bad), we are gonne look at castling, because i personally think it gives the best fighting chances for white. } { [%cal Gg2a8] } (8... O-O { black can't castle here, loses tactically. } 9. Nxc6 Nxc6 10. Bxc6 Bd7 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. O-O) 9. O-O { [%cal Gf7f6,Gd5c3,Gb4c3,Ge8g8] } 9... Bxc3 (9... f6 { seems to solve problems for black, but white comes with a great attack here } 10. e4! fxe5 { taking the king leads into an inferior position after } (10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 fxe5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxe5 Rf8 14. cxb4) (10... Ne7 11. Nf3 { leaves white in a position with a great centre and black has made a consession with the f6 move } (11. Qh5+ { or a crazy line } 11... g6 12. Nxg6 Nxg6)) 11. exd5 cxd5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qxe5 { where white is objectively better }) (9... Nxc3 { also loses tactically } 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Ra3 b4 12. Rxc3 bxc3 13. Ba3 { black will never castle and white can munch up all those pawns on c file, } 13... f6 { just forces white to play } 14. Nxc4 { and enjoy a position where black will never castle and white will have all the time in the world to win }) (9... O-O { castling allows white to take on b5 twice } 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Nxb5 { and lose yet another pawn after } 11... Bb7 (11... a6 { [%cal Ga1a8] }) 12. Nxc4 { now white is a healthy pawn up with a open c-file and great chances to win the game } { [%cal Gf1c1,Rc1d2,Be2e4] }) 10. bxc3 Nxc3 { if black doesnt take, then he's just worse } 11. Qc2 { [%cal Gb5b4,Gc3d5] } 11... Nd5 { allows white to play the classical punch with e4 } (11... b4 { loses a pawn or the entire c-file after } 12. Bb2 Nd5 (12... O-O 13. Bxc3 bxc3 14. Qxc3) 13. Nxc4) 12. e4 { [%cal Ge4d5,Rg2e4,Bc2e4] } 12... Nb4 (12... Nb6 13. d5 O-O 14. Rd1 $14) 13. Qc3 { black has to defend his knight } 13... a5 { and now white has the classical move } 14. d5 cxd5 (14... O-O 15. dxc6 N8xc6 16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. axb5 { white takes the pawn back with a better structure, but black could get a dangerous pawn } 17... Nd4 18. Qxc4) 15. axb5 f6 16. exd5!! Nxd5 { and in this position, the rare, but typical consession of the lightsquared bishop comes to place } (16... fxe5 17. dxe6 { taking the knight wont work tacially, because black isn't castled yet } 17... O-O 18. Qxc4 { [%cal Gc4g8] }) 17. Bxd5 Qxd5 18. Nxc4 { black cannot aford to waste a move castling, because he would be losing tactically } { [%cal Rc4b6] } 18... Bb7 { [%csl Rg2] } 19. f3 { [%cal Gc4b6] } 19... O-O (19... Nd7 { but defending the for would be met with } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gc4b6] } 20. Ba3 { stopping black from ever castling } { [%cal Ra3f8] }) 20. Nb6 Qxb5 21. Nxa8 Bxa8 { both white and black managed to castle, white gave up two pawns, but won the exchange and will win a pawn back, black had to give up the exchange, because he would lose the castling privileges and lose to a strong attack later } 22. Rxa5 *


