1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 { This part of the study shows that keeping on the c4 pawn is very dangerous, because black will eventually have to invets more time and he's also exposing the long diagonal and inviting white to activate his pieces with tempo } 5. Bg2 a6 { nice a6-b5 structure } 6. O-O { we aren't concerned about the pawn, we wanna develop, develop and attack when the time is right } 6... b5 { black loses time to defend the pawn and exposes the long diag } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 7. Ne5 { [%cal Gg2a8] } (7. a4 { is a theme move, but not in this line, as black has the very strong Bb7 } { [%cal Gb2b3] }) 7... Nd5 (7... c6 { seems like a very good move at first } 8. b3 (8. Nxc6 { Looks like white has to plaay this move but then black has } 8... Qb6 9. Ne5 (9. Nxb8 Rxb8 { pretty bad for white }) 9... Bb7 { Black gets a nice counterpart to the white g2 bishop, would be decent for black }) 8... cxb3 9. Nxc6 Qb6 10. Na5 Ra7 (10... Qxa5 11. Bxa8 { loses rook }) 11. Nxb3 { good for white, white is up a tempie and stuff }) 8. a4 Bb7 (8... bxa4 9. Qxa4+ Bd7 10. Qxc4 { [%csl Gc6,Ga6][%cal Gg2a8] }) 9. axb5 (9. b3 { is the other line, but is a little worse than the one I've shown in the main variation, because black has c3 } 9... cxb3 (9... c3) 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Qxb3 { blacks development and the fact that that white has many easy targets makes it easy for white to play } { [%csl Gb5,Gc7] }) 9... axb5 10. Rxa8 Bxa8 { Looks like we just exchanged and lost a tempo, and we got nothing, but its gonna get clear soon } 11. e4 Nf6 (11... Nb6 12. Qh5 { crushing } 12... g6 13. Nxg6 fxg6 14. Qe5 Rg8 15. Qxe6+) 12. Nc3 c6 { it is clear that the bishop on a8 is missplaced
This is now a key strategic moment of Catalan
white fight with the initiative and good placed pieces, but black is trying to hold onto the pawn up } (12... b4 13. Qa4+ { too powerful }) 13. d5 { a great breakthrough } (13. b3 cxb3 14. Qxb3 { nothing for white }) 13... cxd5 { black has hard time avoiding this move } (13... Be7 { black could try } 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Qe2 O-O 16. Bh3 { the king is not so happy } { [%csl Ge6] } 16... Qc8 17. Rd1 { takes the open file and planining to increase pressure with Nf3 Ng5 and e5 } { [%cal Ge5f3,Gf3g5] }) (13... Bd6 { black could also try } 14. Bf4 cxd5 { black could try this, but its losing tactically } 15. Nxb5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 O-O { black looks fine after castling but } 17. Bd6 { [%cal Gd6f8] } 17... Re8 { [%cal Rb5c7] } 18. e5 { shows that the bishop on a8 is misserable } { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gb5c7,Re5f6] }) 14. exd5 { black has a choice } 14... Bxd5 (14... exd5 { Black might be up two pawns but white is just crushing, great pieces, Re1 Bg5 comming, everything in white's favour and black only has a decent knight on f6 and atleast the bishop on a8 supports the centre } 15. Ng4 { taking off the only real deffender of blacks position } { [%cal Gf1e1,Gc3d5,Gg4f6] } 15... Nxg4 (15... Ne4 { black can try } 16. Bf4 Nxc3 (16... Bd6 { would be really bad for black } { [%cal Gd1d4,Gg2e4] } 17. Qd4 { [%cal Gd4g7] } (17. Bxe4 { also a nice tactic } 17... Bxf4 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Nxd5 Bd6 20. Re1+ { leading into no castling }) 17... O-O 18. Bh6 gxh6 (18... f6 19. Nxd5 gxh6 20. Bxe4) 19. Nxh6# { nice mate }) 17. bxc3 { black has to lose time exchanging the knight }) (15... Nbd7 { black is colapsing } 16. Re1+ (16. Nxf6+) 16... Be7 17. Bxd5 { [%cal Gd8d5] }) 16. Qxg4 { would be lovely }) 15. Bxd5 { white has to respond with a somewhat atypical move, but it is because blacks queenside is already ruptured and there's nothing much to do with white's great bishop } 15... exd5 { forced } (15... Nxd5 16. Qh5 { black has two moves } 16... g6 { typical move } (16... Qf6 { white has a nice attack } 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Re1 Be7 19. Bg5 Qxg5 (19... Qf5 20. Ng6 Qxg6 21. Rxe7+ Kf8 22. Qe2 f6 23. Rc7 { [%cal Ge2e7,Ge7d8] }) 20. Qxf7+ Kd8 21. Qxd5+ Kc7 22. Qxb5) 17. Nxg6 fxg6 18. Qe5 Nf6 { only way of keeping the rook } (18... Rg8 { still loses the rook } 19. Qxe6+ Qe7 20. Qxg8) 19. Qxe6+ Qe7 20. Qc8+ Kf7 21. Qxb8 { still loses a piece } 21... b4 22. Nb5 { black will have a hard time defending }) 16. Ng4 { again we try to takeaway the main defender } 16... Be7 (16... Ne4 { black could try this again, but it's not really an option } 17. Nxd5 { but we just take on d5 } 17... f5 18. Nh6 gxh6 (18... Qd7 19. Re1 gxh6 20. Nf6+ { [%cal Gf6d7,Gf6e8] }) 19. Qh5+ Kd7 20. Qxf5+) 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Re1+ Kf8 (18... Be7 19. Nxd5 { deadly } { [%cal Gd5e7,Ge1e7] }) 19. Nxd5 { playing the rest of the game with basically an extra rook } 19... Nc6 20. Be3 h5 21. Bc5+ Kg8 22. Be7 { completely crushing black coordination } 22... Qc8 (22... Nxe7 23. Nxf6+ { [%cal Gd1d8] }) (22... Bxe7 23. Nxe7+ Kh7 24. Qxh5#) 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Nxf6+ (24. Re8+ { also possible } 24... Qxe8 25. Nxf6+) 24... Kg7 25. Nxh5+ Kh6 26. Qd6+ Kxh5 27. Re4 Kg5 28. h4+ Kh5 29. Qf6 Rg8 30. Qxf7+ { GM Pavel Eljanov vs GM Igor Novikov } *


