1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. O-O Nc6 7. e3 { we overprotect the pawn in order to play Nbd2 and regain c4 } { [%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4] } 7... Bd7 { a better way of trying to keep the pawn for black seems to be Bb7, because it protects the Knight on c6 and that allows black to play b5 } (7... Rb8 { seemingly a good way but there's a brilliant move of Nfd2! } 8. Nfd2 { [%cal Gg2c6,Gd2c4] } 8... b5 (8... e5 { people also tried } 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. dxe5 Ng4 11. Nxc4 Be6 12. Nbd2 { but black doesn't have enough in this postiion }) (8... Na5 { Also doesn't work, thanks to this combination: } 9. Qa4+ { [%cal Ga4e8] } 9... c6 { [%cal Gd8a5] } 10. b4 cxb3 11. axb3 b6 12. b4 Nb7 13. Bxc6+ { white is gaining much more in return }) 9. Bxc6+) 8. Qe2 b5 (8... Bd6 { Black has also tried this move, not keeping the pawn } 9. Qxc4 O-O { but the idea for black has to be e5, and white can easily prepare for it with } { [%cal Ge6e5] } 10. Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d8] } 10... e5 { playing it now wouldn't work after } (10... Rb8 { so instead they could play Rb8 and in that case white just prepares b3 and fianchettoing the bishop, getting a good hold of the centre } 11. b3 e5 12. Bb2 exd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 { very harmonious for white } { [%cal Gb1d2,Ga1c1] }) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 { because the b7 pawn is hanging } 13. Bxb7) 9. b3!! $18 { turns out best way to play for white is to remove the pawn from c4 with b3, opening the c-file } (9. Ne5 { a 'good looking' move of Ne5 doesn't really work because after } 9... Nxe5 10. Bxa8 Qxa8 11. dxe5 Ne4 { white is really weak on white sqares so black has a great compensation for the exchange sac } { [%csl Gd3,Gf3,Gg2][%cal Gd7c6] }) (9. Nc3 { similar try to Ne5 and after } { [%csl Ge4] } 9... Be7 { finally Ne5 } 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 { black just goes } 11... Nd5 { and gives back the pawn } 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Bg2 Qc7 { and there's no problems for black, equal material and black is going to finish his development }) 9... cxb3 10. axb3 { black could play basically any other bishop developing idea, but the ideas keep the same } 10... Be7 (10... Bb4 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Rc1 Nd5 { in this line, black has a big controll over c3, and playing Nc3 would allow black to exchange a little too much, but white has a different idea of } { [%csl Gc3] } 13. Ne1 { with the idea of winning a tempie against the bishop on b4, beucase black can't afford losing the bishop and leaving the black squares weak } { [%csl Ga5,Gc5,Ge5][%cal Ge1d3] } 13... Be7 { and now we can repeat the idea of } 14. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 14... Ncb4 15. Ne4 { and in this position it's not very clear how black wants to free himself } 15... a5 16. Nc5 c6 { but now we can kick one knight from d5 } 17. e4 Nf6 { and attack the remaining knight on b4 } 18. Bc3 { and if be take on b4 then the knight from e1 is read to hop onto his spot. And all this keeping the superiority in the centre } { [%cal Ge1d3,Gd3b4] }) 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Rc1 { at this point, black isn't forced to play Nb4, he could also go Nd5, but that gives white another idea } 12... Nb4 (12... Nd5 13. Nc3 { with the idea Ne4 Nc5! } { [%cal Gc3e4,Ge4c5] }) 13. Ne5 { [%cal Gg2a8] } 13... Rc8 { in this position black has many weaknesses that are all held by the b4 knight, white hasn't developed just one piece, being the knight on b1, so his ideal plan is to activate his knight trying to exchange him for the b4 knight } { [%csl Gb4] } (13... Rb8 14. Nd2 { Tomashevsky's opponent didn't play as Loek van Wely, playing Rc8 and that allowed him to show that he doesn't even have to rush Na3 Nc2 to beat his opponent, even though it should be considered the strongest way } 14... Rb6 { because black cannot play c5 yet } 15. Ndf3 Bc8 { we see that if black doesnt play for c5 then he no idea to roll in this position and he's basically just trying to rearange his pieces and hoping to exchange. Now Tomashevsky shows the reason of Ndf3 and goes } 16. Ne1 { finally going Nd3 and exchange blacks powerful knight on b4 and his idea of taking the longer way is to have a knight ready to jump on c5 } { [%cal Ge1d3,Be5d3] } 16... Nd7 { black want's to exchange pieces and is all cramped } 17. N5d3 { but white doesnt want to, he just wants to get rid of the knight on b4 } 17... Nxd3 18. Nxd3 { keeping c5 forever under controll } 18... Bd6 19. e4 Bb7 20. Nc5 Bc8 { seems like black has no plan, but he's also a 2600 GM, trying to survive } 21. e5 Be7 { in this position black is all cramped white can just make small improvements in the position and slowly win } 22. h4 { gaining space on the QS and following with Qe3 Bc3 to Ba5 } { [%cal Ge2e3,Gb2c3,Gc3a5] }) 14. Na3 { if black would way white could just play Nc2 and black's position would colapse, so hes forced to play c5 } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Ga3c2] } 14... c5 15. dxc5 Rxc5 16. Rxc5 Bxc5 { looks like black has some sort of relief, but white just goes onto his plan } { [%cal Ga3c2] } 17. Nc2 Nxc2 18. Qxc2 Qb6 { defending both a6 and c5 and seems to be hanging on and in reality, if black had a little more time, he would probably manage to finish developement and consolidate, white needs to do something } { [%cal Gb6a6,Gb6c5,Bd7e8,Bf8d8] } 19. g4!! $36 { but ivanchuk found even more aggresive way } (19. Nd3 { a standard way of playing } 19... Be7 20. Bd4 { taking over the queenside } 20... Qd6 21. Bc5 Qc7 22. Rxa6 { taking on a6, having more active pieces } 22... Bxc5 23. Nxc5 { [%cal Gb3b4] }) 19... Rd8 { bringing the rook into the game and defending d7 } 20. g5 Nd5 { now that the knight of gone from f6 black has no defense over the kingside } 21. Be4 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Ge4h7] } (21. Nxf7 { white has a better attack in this crazy engine line, but it wasnt played, nor in the video } 21... Kxf7 22. Qxh7 Rg8 23. Rd1 { preparing first e4 and after Bxf2 Kh1 with ideas of Rf1 and Be5 } { [%csl Rf2,Gd7,Gh1][%cal Ge3e4,Bd1f1,Bb2e5] }) 21... f5 (21... g6 { would be really bad because of the black bishop and the long diag would be really weak } { [%cal Gb2h8,Ge5g4] }) 22. Bxd5 { and now ivanchuk transformed the position } 22... exd5 23. Nxd7 Rxd7 24. Qxf5 Rd8 { white is just better here, white has very strong bishop on b2 and black has seriously exposed king and would be winning (unlike in the game) after } { [%cal Gb2h8] } 25. Rc1 (25. h4 d4 26. Rd1 a5 27. h5 dxe3 28. Rxd8+ Qxd8 29. Qxc5 exf2+ 30. Kg2 f1=Q+ 31. Kxf1 Qd1+ 32. Kg2 Qd2+ 33. Kf3 Qxb2 34. Qxb5 Kf8 35. Qc4 Ke7 36. Kg4 Qe5 { Ivanchuk, Vassily - Van Wely, Loek, 1/2-1/2, Tata Steel-A 74th, 2012, https://lichess.org/cOzuyD0B }) 25... Bf8 26. h4 { its very hard for black to survive against the idea of h5 g6 or h5 h6 and move like } { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gh4h5,Gg5g6,Bh5h6] } 26... Qg6 { would allow white to win a pawn } 27. Qxg6 hxg6 28. Rc6 *


