1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. Qa4 { has to be played, because black would just play Rb8 b5 } 6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Nd5 8. Bxb4 Nxb4 9. O-O { and now white's move gotta be really precise, gotta know all the theory and key questions to strategically take pawn back } (9. a3 { doesn't really work because black has a series of exchanges } 9... b5 10. Qxb5 Nc2+ 11. Kd2 Bd7 12. Kxc2 Nxd4+ 13. Nxd4 Bxb5 14. Nxb5 Rb8 15. Bc6+ Kf8 16. Rd1 Qf6 { where its three pieces against a Queen but white is unable to hold on onto the meterial } { [%csl Gf2] }) 9... Rb8 { [%csl Gb5] } (9... Bd7 10. Ne5 Nxe5 { doesn't work because } (10... a5 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Nc3 { white remains with a very stong bishop on b2 and is ready to play a3 and kick the knight away }) 11. Qxb4 { and white can now grab the pawn }) (9... a6 { doesn't work on the count of } 10. Ne5 b5 11. Nxc6 bxa4 12. Nxd8 { [%cal Gg2a8] }) 10. Nc3 (10. Na3 { has been played on the top level }) (10. Ne5 { not good } 10... Qxd4 11. Nxc6 Nxc6 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxc6+ Bd7 { no serious damage }) 10... a6 { black is ready to play a6 } 11. Ne5 { [%cal Ga4e8] } 11... O-O 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 { and now we give up our nice bishop on b2 to destroy blacks position completely } 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qxc4 { [%csl Gc6,Gc7,Gc8,Ga6,Ge6,Gb2] } 14... Qd6 (14... Rxb2 { a straightforward move, but basically leads to a much worse position for black } 15. Rab1 Rxb1 (15... Rb6 16. Qc5 { stopping Qd6 and keeping the black locked
white can just get his pieces better and exchange later on, or manouver his rook forcing black to exchange } { [%cal Bb1b3,Bf1b1,Gf2f3,Gg1f2,Gf1d1] }) 16. Rxb1 Qd6 { black would like to play e5 to open his lightsqared bishop so white stop it with } { [%csl Gc8][%cal Ge6e5] } 17. f4 Rd8 18. Rb8 { white penetrates } 18... Kf8 19. Ne4 Qd5 { white is happy to exchange } 20. Qxd5 cxd5 21. Nc5 Ke7 22. Kf2 f6 23. Ra8 h6 24. e3 Re8 25. a4 Bd7 26. Ra7 Rc8 27. Ke2 g5 28. Kd3 gxf4 29. gxf4 h5 30. h4 a5 31. Rxa5 Rg8 32. Ra7 Kd6 33. Ra6+ Ke7 34. f5 { breaking through } 34... Bc8 (34... exf5 { doesnt work } 35. Nxd7 Kxd7 36. Rxf6) 35. Rc6 { basically after this move black is completley colapsing } 35... e5 36. a5 { a better move } (36. Ne6 Bd7 37. Rxc7 e4+ 38. Ke2 { basically, black is completely colapsing } 38... Kd6 39. Ra7 Bxe6 { and the knight is always untouchable, because white has } (39... Rg2+ 40. Kf1 Rh2 41. Ra6+ { and white quite quickly wrapped up the game with attackign all the weaknesses } 41... Ke7 42. Nf4 Bxf5 43. Nxd5+ Ke8 44. Ra8+ Kd7 45. Nxf6+ Kd6 46. Ra5 Ke6 47. Nxh5 { and evenetually white converted without a difficulty }) 40. Ra6+ Kd7 41. Rxe6) 36... Bxf5+ (36... Bd7) 37. Kc3 exd4+ 38. exd4 Rg3+ 39. Kb4 Rg4 40. a6 Rxd4+ 41. Kb5 Rg4 42. a7 Rg8 43. Ra6 Ra8 44. Kc6 Bc8 45. Ra2 { white white is just winning }) 15. b3 { but turns out b3 is a very strong and not as popular move for white and if black lets white play Ne4 its ggs } { [%cal Gc3e4] } (15. Ne4 { Ne4 doesnt seem to bring anything for white either } 15... Qd5 16. Qxd5 { taking on d5 doesnt work because black has exd5 } 16... exd5 17. Nc5 Rxb2 18. e3 { the point being Bf5 stopping all of whites ideas } 18... Bf5 19. Nxa6 Ra8 { and now after capturing the pawn black will have a very active rook on a2 that gives a lot of counterplay }) (15. e3 { after e3 Rxb2 is finally getting good and this line seems to not bring anything for white } 15... Rxb2 16. Rab1 Rxb1 17. Rxb1 { so after exchanging rooks black is doing fine with e5 } 17... e5) 15... Rb4 { so after Rb4 the play is very concrete } (15... e5 { doesnt really bring anything for white because after } 16. Rfd1 exd4 17. Qxd4 { we exchange queens and the white king is completely safe }) 16. Ne4 Rxc4 (16... Qxd4 { another idea for black } 17. Qxd4 Rxd4 18. f3 { question could be why not e5 and attack the knight } 18... e5 (18... Rfd8 19. Rfc1 { very similar to Nxd6 line } 19... e5 20. Kf2 Bf5 { but we won't allow the exchange } 21. Nc5 { with an attack against } 21... a5) (18... f5 { this move was tried in a grandmaster game, but its kinda a sad move, since now another pawn is on the white squares, blocking bishop } 19. Nc5 e5 20. Kf2 Rf6 21. Rfd1 Rh6 { and here white actually got nervous and deffended the pawn on h2 with king, although he didnt have to, as black has nothing after } 22. h4 { and its basically the same as the other lines now }) 19. Kf2 Bf5 { but we won't allow the exchange } 20. Nc5 { attacking a pawn } 20... a5 { and here white has the option of exchanging rooks } 21. Rfd1 Rfd8 22. Rxd4 Rxd4 { and then white can quite nicely activate all his pieces in to the game } 23. e4 Bc8 24. Ke3 { white is again going to play Rc1, play Nd3 and capture all the pawns and it's not possible to hold on for black in the long run } { [%csl Ga5,Gc6,Ge5][%cal Ga1c1,Gc5d3] }) 17. Nxd6 Rxd4 18. Nc4 { white has no worries about his kingside, because he exchanged the threads and black is left with a d-file which doesnt really matter, because he has no entry on d2... what matters is the weaknesses on queenside } { [%cal Gf1c1] } 18... Rfd8 19. Rfc1 g6 20. f4 { stopping e5 } 20... Bd7 21. Kf2 Be8 22. Rc2 Kg7 23. Rac1 h6 24. Ne5 a5 { trying to exchange everything, but white doesn't allow that } 25. Rc4 g5 26. Ke3 gxf4+ 27. gxf4 R4d5 28. h4 { taking bit more space } 28... f6 { weakening the 7th rank } 29. Nxc6 Bxc6 30. Rxc6 { and after } 30... e5 { and the strong move } 31. f5 { black is already lost, milion weaknesses and no counterplay } { [%csl Gf6,Gc7,Ga5,Gh6] } *


