1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 { here white has to make a confession to regain the pawn } 7. Qc2 { yes, white gets the pawn back indeed, but here the consession is that the queen has been brought out so early, it takes 2 moves to got to c4, but also allows an expansion on queenside } (7. Nbd2 b5 { there's no way to use the exposed long diagonal } 8. Ne5 Nd5) (7. Ne5 Nc6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Nxc6 Qe8 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Qa4 e5 { here in general black manages to drain up o nthe fact that the white king is exposed }) 7... a6 { there are two moves, we'll discus Qxc4 here } 8. Qxc4 b5 { the question is, can white make use of the weaknesses on the c-file and very often in catalan games, where the pawn stctures are symetrical d and c pawns on both sides have been exchanged we see this pawn formation with the b pawn losing control over the c-file, which is a crucial element of whites play } 9. Qc2 Bb7 { solving one key problem in the catalan, but there are weakened squares on the c-file } { [%csl Gc5,Gc6,Gc7] } 10. Bd2 { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gd2a5,Ga5d8] } (10. Bg5) (10. Bf4) 10... Ra7 11. Rc1 Be4 12. Qb3 (12. Qd1 { used to be the case, but after } 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Qxd4 { theres no way to use the skewer } 14. Be3 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 c5) 12... Nc6 13. e3 Qa8 { black is putting a lot of pressure on the a8 h1 diagonala, but the knight is missplaced and it will have to move again } { [%cal Ga8g2] } 14. Qd1 Nb8 { [%cal Gc7c5] } 15. Ba5 Bd6 16. a3 { making sure nothing bad happens of to the bishop } (16. Nc3 Bb7 { its clear that the bishop is missplaced and could be threatened alot with Nc6 } { [%csl Ga5] }) (16. Nbd2 Bd5 { theres still the issue of Bishop on a5, again with the thread of Nc6 and b5 would win a full piece }) 16... Nbd7 { preparing c5 and e5 } 17. Nbd2 Bd5 18. Qf1 { making sure that e5 can be captured enough times } 18... c5 (18... e5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Rc2 { leaving nice position for white } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gc2c7,Ga1c1] }) 19. dxc5 Bxc5 { and now we see how important it was to play Rfc1 and put the queen back, because the rooks are connected and can be just doubled up on the c-file } 20. Rc2 Qb7 21. Rac1 Bb6 22. Bxb6 Qxb6 23. Nd4 { removing the strong bishop on d5 and getting ready to invade blacks position } 23... Ne5 { keeping an eye on the c4 outpost and defending c6 } 24. Bxd5 Nxd5 25. N4f3 { to exchange the knight on e5 } 25... Nxf3+ 26. Nxf3 { the smoke is slowly clearing and lot of pieces have been exchanged, but white is left with a strong hold of c-file and a c6 entry point } 26... Rd8 27. Qd3 { a great positional move, heading to an optimal square of e4 } 27... Ne7 (27... Nf6 28. Rc6 Qb8 (28... Rxd3 29. Rxb6 { the rook on b6 can't be kicked out and is keeping the queenside under fire, black will soon be completely out of squares } { [%cal Gg1f1,Gf1e2,Gc1c2,Gf3d4] }) 29. Qc2 { a great improvement for white }) 28. Qe4 Rad7 29. Kg2 { dodging the bullet } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gf3e5,Ge4f3,Gf3f7,Gc2c7] } 29... f6 { black felt that it was needed to weaken his kingside playing f6 } 30. h4 { a typical move, once f6 has been played we use h pawn as a dagger to produce further weakneses } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gh4h5,Gh7h6] } 30... e5 31. h5 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf3h4] } 31... Qb7 { here Aronian missed the chance of playing perfectly, with exchanging the queens } 32. Qg4 (32. Qxb7 Rxb7 { and now that theres no hold over the d-file, white can reroute his knight to e4 } 33. Nd2 { whole queenside under pressure } { [%csl Gf6,Ga6,Ge6,Gd7,Gb7][%cal Gd2e4,Ge4c5,Gh5h6,Rc2c7,Bc2c5] } 33... b4 { the only way to try to fight on } 34. Ne4 { very difficult struggle ahead }) 32... Kf7 (32... h6 { should be somewhat fine for black } { [%cal Gg8h8] }) 33. Rc5 Rc8 { black is crumbled under the pressure } 34. Rxc8 Nxc8 35. Qf5 { very unpleasant for black } 35... g6 36. Qg4 Ne7 37. hxg6+ hxg6 38. Rh1 f5 (38... Kg7 39. Qh3 { with decisive attack }) 39. Rh7+ Ke6 40. Qg5 { just a matter of moves until white pieces manage to completely flash out the black king } 40... Qe4 41. Qh6 f4 42. Qf8 Nc6 43. Qc8 Ne7 44. Qe8 Kd6 45. Qf8 Qd5 46. e4 Qe6 47. Ng5 { Qf6 is unstopable and white is winning
GM Levon Aronian vs GM Sergey Karjakin 1-0
Aronian managed to keep the pressure up from the moment where he got to double the rooks and eventually step by step he increased his advantage until black colapsed } *


