1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 { blacks plan is to play Ne7 b6 Be7 and eventually strike with c5 and equalize in the centre and not worry about lower space, there are two moves white can play... one is Nc3 and the other Qc2 } { [%cal Gb8d7,Bc6c5,Bb7b6,Rc8b7,Gb1c3,Gd1c2] } 7. Qc2 { keeping an eye on the c4 pawn and preparing e4 asap } 7... Nbd7 (7... b6 8. Nbd2 Bb7 9. e4 Na6 10. a3 dxc4 11. Nxc4 (11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxc4 c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 Nd7 15. Bb2 Rc8 16. Qe2 Ba6 17. Rfc1)) 8. Nbd2 b6 { and now already white manages to push } 9. e4 Bb7 { black carried out his plan with Bb7 and is now ready to play c5, so now comes an important move for white } (9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 { now white has much more control over the centre and stands better } { [%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5] }) 10. e5 { grabbing more space and gives black a problemed piece for the rest of the game } 10... Ne8 { [%csl Gf8,Ge8,Ga8] } 11. cxd5 { we gotta capture right away, because if we playde for example Re1 black would play Nc7 and if we ever took, he'd be always ready to capture back with the knight } 11... cxd5 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Qa4 { making it dificult for the bishop to get into the game } { [%csl Gb7] } 13... a5 14. Bf1 Nb8 { to get rid atleast of the one bad piece, but better was Nc7 to atleast try to activate the knight a little } { [%cal Gb8a6] } 15. a3 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb8a6] } 15... Ba6 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 17. Nf1 Nec7 { the knights are problemed with the coordination and they are blocking each other } { [%csl Gc7,Ga6] } 18. h4 { grabbing more space } { [%csl Gg5] } 18... Qe8 { because of the e5 pawn, its only good to keep the queens on, because there always can be a crushing attack and the kingside is harder to defend because of the pawn } { [%csl Be5] } 19. Qd1 Qd7 { connecting the rooks } 20. Bg5 { black can never take on g5, because of hx and the h file will be deadly } 20... f6 { weakening his king up } (20... Bxg5 21. hxg5) (20... h6 { also bad, allows } 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Rc1 { with the idea of tripling up on c file, or also Kg2 g4 Ng3 g5 and attack blacks king } { [%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5,Gg1g2,Gf1g3] }) 21. exf6 gxf6 { really weak squares around blacks king } { [%csl Gh5,Gh6,Gg4,Gf4,Gg8] } 22. Bh6 Rf7 { and now just natural development } 23. Rc1 Bd6 { black has a stronghold on c7 so he cant be overrun on the c file just yet, but there's no constructive plan } { [%csl Gc7] } 24. Qc2 { pinning the knight also the idea of Qc6 is very! strong } 24... Nb8 { with black all cramped white has all the time in the world to improve his position so GM Georg Meier came with a nice manouvre } { [%cal Gb8c6] } 25. Ne3 Kh8 26. Ng2 Rg8 27. Nf4 Re7 28. Nh5 Rg6 29. Bf8 { and blacks position is overloaded } 29... Rf7 30. Bxd6 { and now the stronghold is no more. } 30... Qxd6 31. Re3 { with the idea of tripling up } { [%cal Ge3c3] } 31... Re7 32. Rc3 Ne8 33. Rc8 { penetrating } 33... Rg8 34. Kg2 { giving him a move, because its really hard to find one } 34... e5 { opening up more squares to white's pieces } 35. Qf5 Qd7 { happily exchanging } 36. Qxd7 Nxd7 37. R1c6 { allowing the penetration of the other rook } { [%csl Gf6,Ge5,Gb6] } 37... Rf8 { black just has no moves } 38. b4 axb4 39. axb4 Kg8 40. b5 Ref7 41. Rd8 Re7 42. Kf1 Ref7 43. Nh2 { also landing on the squares weakened by f6 } { [%cal Gh2g4,Gg4h6] } 43... exd4 44. Ng4 Re7 45. Nh6+ Kh8 46. Nf5 Re5 47. Nxd4 { black resigned
GM Georg Meier - GM Ehsan Ghaem-Maghami
1 - 0 } 47... Rxh5 48. Rxd7 { and black just has no way of getting back into the game, white just promotes the pawn and wins, there's no way for black to get out, notice that the knight that was troubled thanks to e5 remained troubled for the rest of the game } { [%csl Ge8] } *


