[ECO "E11"]
[Opening "Bogo-Indian Defense: Retreat Variation"]
[StudyName "A guide to Catalan"]
[ChapterName "4... Bb4+"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0Ue8aUb0/dzkRuRHM"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "20:50:00"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 { best move, if black would like to trade on d2 then white just has developed more } (5. Nc3 { not so good } 5... O-O 6. Bg2 { black can take the pawn and actually hold onto it } 6... dxc4) (5. Nbd2 dxc4 { black again can take on c4 }) 5... Be7 { the idea of Bb4 is to provoke Bd2 and then go back to e7 } 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Qc2 c6 { and we get to the closed catalan, but here the bishop would be on c1
here usually white would play Nd2 and attack the centre with Nd2 and e4, white cannot play Nc3 as he wouldn't be able to hold onto the pawn and wasting move like b3 to protect c4 then the black bishop would rather be on b2 to fianchetto } { [%cal Ge2e4,Rb1d2,Bb2b3] } 8. h4 $146 { BANG! Dubov recently came up with a great novelty, the reason why h4 is so great is because it manages to exploit blacks position with a direct attack and that's exactly what players wanted to avoid when they choose the setup when they hold onto the pawn on d5 } (8. O-O Nbd7 { with the classic closed catalan and white has not much to work with, black has a stable position where u can't generate a lot of threads } { [%cal Gb7b6,Gc6c5,Gc8b7,Gb7a6] }) 8... Nbd7 (8... b6 { other typical way of approach } 9. Nc3 Ba6 10. Ng5 Bxc4 (10... Nbd7 { giving white initiative } 11. e4 dxe4 12. Ncxe4 h6 { you can always ignore because the hfile cannot open for white, because black } 13. O-O-O { castling queenside and white has made a good use for the bishop on d2 and here white is just better }) 11. e4 { white has a very strong iniciative } 11... Na6 12. a3 { and black cannot take on e4 } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ga6b4,Gb4d3,Ge4e5,Gc2h7] } 12... dxe4 13. Ncxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 { no way black can survive } { [%csl Gc4,Gh7][%cal Ge4c6] }) 9. Nc3 { giving up the pawn on c4 } 9... dxc4 { and doesn't take the centre with } 10. Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d8] } (10. e4 { because black would have } 10... e5 11. dxe5 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4e5,Gd7e5,Ge5d3] }) 10... b5 { and in these type of positions white is usually castled and what is going to happen now would never be possible } 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 (12... Nd7 { doesnt work } 13. Nxb5 { [%cal Gg2a8] }) 13. Ne4 { [%cal Gh1h8,Ge4g5] } 13... f5 { black felt he has to take some space back and kick the knight eternaly weakening his king } (13... Qc7 14. Ng5 g6 15. Nxh7 Kxh7 16. h5 Kg7 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Be4 { with a great attack } (18. Rh6 Rf5 19. g4 Bg5 { only move })) 14. exf6 gxf6 { it will become increasingly difficult for black to hold on } { [%csl Gg8,Rd5][%cal Gf6g5,Rd5f6] } 15. b3 cxb3 16. axb3 { taking away the c4 pawn that was taking a lot of space and white can play Nc5 and giving up the black bishop would be another huge concecssion } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge4c5,Bc1c6,Bd1c1] } 16... Qb6 17. O-O a5 { the only way for black to get out is a4 } { [%cal Ga5a4] } 18. Rc1 { here dubov tried to play positionally and played Rc1, but there were a lot of ideas, but here black had time to play a4 and give the pawn back on c6, but instead he played Bd7 } (18. Bh6 Rd8 19. g4) 18... Bd7 { atleast trying to hang on onto the extra pawn } (18... a4 19. bxa4 Rxa4 20. Qxc6) 19. Bh6 Rfc8 (19... Rf7 { the rook feels oddly placed on f7, but he would defend alot }) 20. Rfd1 { putting the last piece into the game and having more than enough compensation, here a4 was played } 20... a4 { whiteš took on a4, but there was an instructive moment white could play the extremly strong move b4 which is very desirable, until u realise that black cannot take the pawn and white can jump on c5 } (20... e5 { bolstring the long diag so Qb2 would not attack on f6 } { [%cal Gb2h8,Gc2b2] } 21. Qd3 Be6 22. Qf3 { but slowly white is able to switch focus to the kingside with ideas of Kh2 Bh3, get rid of the white bishop and suddenly all the squares would be weaker around the black king and getting more and more difficult to defend and here we can already see the difference with the rook on c8 and not f7 } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gg1h2,Gg2h3,Gd1d5,Ge4f6] }) (20... Kh8 { if black were to make a waiting move like Kg8 then we could start attacking with g4 } 21. g4) 21. b4 { and blacks defense will not be able to hold } (21. bxa4 { even though he didnt play the star move, its still very hard for black to defend } 21... Rxa4 22. Qb2 { [%cal Gb2f6] } 22... Rb4 23. Qa1 Qd8 { [%cal Gc8a8] } 24. Rc2 { making room for queen on c1 supporting Nc5 } 24... Qe8 25. Nc5 Qg6 26. Qc1 Bxc5 27. Rxc5 Kf7 28. h5 Qxh5 29. e4 { and the final colapse } 29... Rc4 30. Rxc4 bxc4 { but here Dubov missteped, he couldhave just picked up the piece } 31. exd5 (31. Be3 { the move Dubov played }) 31... cxd5 32. Rd4 { he would start the final attack } 32... c3 33. Rh4 Qe2 34. Qa3 c2 35. Bf3 { and the pieces would come from all sides } { [%csl Ra3,Rc1,Rh6][%cal Gf3h5,Ga3e7] }) 21... Nxb4 (21... Bxb4 22. Rxd5 cxd5 23. Nxf6+ Kf7 24. Qxh7+ { with a forced mating attack } 24... Kxf6 25. Qg7+ Kf5 26. Qg5#) 22. Qb2 { [%cal Gb2f6,Gb4d5] } 22... Nd5 23. Rxd5 cxd5 24. Nxf6+ Bxf6 25. Qxf6 Rxc1+ 26. Kh2 { no defense } { [%cal Gf6g7] } *


[Event "A guide to Catalan: Caruana line 3. g3 - 4. Bg2; dxc4 line"]
[Date "2021.01.21"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Štěpán Soukup"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E03"]
[Opening "Catalan Opening: Open Defense"]
[StudyName "A guide to Catalan"]
[ChapterName "Caruana line 3. g3 - 4. Bg2; dxc4 line"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/0Ue8aUb0/7hNFfHFd"]
[UTCDate "2021.01.21"]
[UTCTime "20:50:00"]

{ this line on the olympiad caught everyones attention because some of the moves looked odd at first }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 { with better chances of playing catalan } 3... d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 { this position is similar to Qxc4 b5 line, but now that there's no knight on f3 and there's a bishop on g2 } 7. Be3 $146 { fighting against c5 } 7... Bd6 { saying that black can not only play in the centre with c5, but also e5, it's rare, but it could happen } (7... b5 8. Qc1 Rb8 9. Nd2 { its clearly very hard for black to play c5 } { [%cal Gd2b3,Rb3c5] }) 8. Qc2 O-O (8... Nd5 { looks like a tempo gaining move on the bishop } { [%cal Rd5e3] } 9. Bd2 c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Nc3 { the black knight is awkward on d5, black doesn't want to take and help white's developement } 11... Nb4 12. Qb1 { these knights are missplaced } { [%csl Gb4,Gc5][%cal Gg1f3,Ge1g1,Gf1d1,Gf3g5] }) 9. Nh3 $146 e5 10. O-O h6 { preparing Ng4 } (10... Ng4 11. Bg5) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nc3 Qe7 13. Rad1 Re8 14. Nf4 { [%csl Gd5] } 14... c6 15. Bd4 { centralizing the bishop avoiding with Ng4, black is in a though spot with developing a normal move like Bd7 } 15... g5 (15... Bd7 { would be met with Ne4 } 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Rad8 18. Bb6 { [%cal Gb6d8] } 18... Rc8 { we see that the pawn structure on blacks queenside is not optimal and now because of that he cannot fight for the open file } 19. Rd2) 16. Nd3 { Anand felt that his position was worse so he lashed out g5 permanently weakening his king if he plays a logical move like } 16... Nxd3 { and Bf5 shoudlhave been played but he started with Nd3 } (16... Bf5 { white would go } 17. e4 Bh7 18. Qe2 { remove the queen from bishops diagonal } { [%cal Gh7c2] } 18... Rad8 { and after some exchanges } 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qe3 { at first sight it seems very equal, but white's king is very safe, and the black is wekened } { [%csl Gh7,Gg8,Ge4][%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5,Gf1e1] }) 17. Rxd3 Be5 18. Qd2 { removing the queen from the soon-to-be-bishops diagonal and also taking control over the d file } 18... Bf5 19. e4 Bg6 { f4 f5 might come with a tempo now that the bishop is on g6 } { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] } 20. f4 { black shouldhave taken on d4, but instead he took, opening up the g file, which doesn¨'t look that dangerous right away, but will become clear very soon that this was the decisive mistake } 20... gxf4 (20... Bxd4+ 21. Rxd4 { and play } 21... Rad8 22. e5 { and try to fight back here, but after } 22... Qc5 23. Rd1 { white will remain better with his control over the d file }) 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 22. gxf4 Qc5+ 23. Kh1 { black absolutely has to take on e4 and if it works its great, but if not then all that taking on f4 was bad } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gf4f5,Gd2h6,Gc3e4] } 23... Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Rxe4 { white obviously cannot take } 25. Rg3 { [%cal Gg3g8,Gg2e4] } (25. Bxe4 Bxe4+ { [%cal Re4h1,Re4d3] }) 25... Rd4 { anand was hoping for Qf2, but white has Qe3 } (25... Kh7 26. Rxg6 { [%cal Gg2e4] }) 26. Qe3 { which is also looking at the h6 pawn and here Anand actually resigned the game, because he has issues everywhere, he needs to do something about f5, but if he goes 26. Kh8 or 26. Kh7 } { [%cal Ge3h6,Ge3c5] } (26. Qf2 { where black still has } 26... Kh8 { and after } 27. f5 Bh7) 26... Kh8 (26... Kh7 { then after } 27. f5 Bh5 28. Rh3 { there's no defense } { [%cal Ge3h6] }) 27. f5 { with Qh6 is a mating attack } { [%cal Ge3h6] } *


