pieces are still uncoordinated (and white's are). }) 34. c4! { Open up the lines! } { [%cal Gc6c4,Ge5d6,Gd6d8,Gd6f8] } 34... dxc4 { [%csl Gc8,Gb8][%cal Gd1d8,Ge1d1,Gd8c8,Gc8b8] } 35. Bf5 { [%cal Gf5c8,Gd8c8,Ge1d1,Gd1d8] } 35... Rff7 36. Rd1+ Rfd7 (36... Nd7 37. Bxd7 { [%cal Gf7d7,Gf1f8] } 37... Rcxd7 { [%cal Ge5b8,Gc6c8] } 38. Qb8+ { [%cal Gd8e7,Gd1e1,Ge1e7] } 38... Qc8 39. Rxd7+ { [%cal Gf1f7] } 39... Rxd7 40. Rf8+ { [%csl Gc8,Gd8][%cal Gf8c8] }) 37. Bxd7 Rxd7 38. Qb8+ Ke7 39. Rde1+ { 1-0 Black resigns. -Blacks 17...Kf8
was the source of the real problems, simply 17...0-0 was better (keeping the
h8 rook in play). -Black had some nice (but easily avoidable) defensive ideas
early on with 10...Qb6 to trade off the bishops with 11...Bb5 and the 13..Nb4
threat made with 12...Nc6. It's important to be aware of and avoid these like
Fischer did to keep attacking potential. -Move 33. b4 was nice, showing how
good the position was (white could switch between attacking and picking up a
pawn). -White's move 34 showed good judgement. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge7f7] } 39... Kf7 40. Qe8# { [%cal Gf1f8] } 1-0


