1. e4 c5 2. b3!? { Andreikin is a very creative player and constantly goes for
less known variations, something even more expected when he's facing one of
the best opening specialists in the circuit today, Maxime Vachier-Lagrave. } 2... g6! { A very good recommendation against the b3 variation. } 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e5 { The most logical response. } (4. Bxf6 exf6 { White would prefer to have the pawn
on e3 in a position like this, because of the control of the dark squares } 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Bc4 O-O $15 { 0-1 (20) Senders,M (2319)-Reinderman,D (2571)
Netherlands 2016; following with ...Nc6 and ...f5 next, Black should be happy
here. }) (4. Qf3 Bg7 (4... d6!? 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. Bxf6 exf6 $13) 5. e5 Ng8 6. e6 { threatening mate } 6... Nf6 7. exf7+ Kxf7 8. g4 h6 9. Nc3 d5 10. h3 $13 { ½-½ (58)
Short,N (2677)-Jones,G (2653) Bunratty 2012, with a very weird position. }) (4. Nc3 Bg7 { threatening ...Nxe4 } 5. e5 Nh5 6. Ne4 Nc6 7. Nxc5 Nxe5 (7... d6! $17) 8. d4 Nc6 9. Qd2 d6 $15 { 1/2-1/2 (63) Bregadze,L (2483)-Chandra,A (2495)
Saint Louis 2015. Black is doing fine anyway. }) 4... Nd5 5. Nc3 (5. e6 f6 { is pretty safe for Black, as the world champion himself played in 2015: } 6. exd7+ Qxd7 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Bb5 Nc7 9. Bxc6 Qxc6 10. Qf3 Bd7 11. O-O-O e5 12. Qxc6 Bxc6 $17 { 0-1 (37) Aravindh,C (2486)-Carlsen,M (2834) Doha 2015 The game was
very complex and White even achieved an advantage, but the opening experiment
clearly failed. }) (5. Bc4 Nb6 6. e6 f6 7. exd7+ Qxd7 8. Bd3 Bg7 9. Nc3 e5 10. Nge2 O-O 11. a4 a5 12. O-O Nc6 $15 { 0-1 (58) McShane,L (2696)-Mchedlishvili,M
(2631) Warsaw 2013 }) 5... Nxc3 6. Bxc3 Bg7 7. h4 d5 $146 (7... O-O 8. h5 d5 { also very logical } 9. exd6 { would be similar to the game, White having played
h5 instead of 9.dxe7, as Andreikin did } (9. f4?! Nc6 10. Nf3 Bg4 11. h6 Bh8 12. Rh4 Qd7 $17 { 0-1 (77) Gelashvili,T (2563)-Yilmaz,M (2630) Minsk 2017 })) 8. exd6 { A necessary move. } 8... O-O! { White doesn't have any development; this
looks very logical. } 9. dxe7 (9. h5 { would transpose to the 7...O-O analysis. }) 9... Re8 10. Qf3 (10. Bc4?! Rxe7+ 11. Ne2 Nc6 $44 { looks bad for White;
castling kingside has to be bad with the h4-pawn already there. }) 10... Qxe7+ (10... Rxe7+!? { was another way to play it } 11. Ne2 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Nc6 13. O-O-O Bf5 14. Kb2 Nb4 15. h5!? { with the rook on e7, Black has to be watching for h6 } 15... Bxc2 16. hxg6 Bxg6 17. Nf4 { and I don't know anymore who's attacking } 17... Nd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. Bc4 $13 { with an unclear position. }) 11. Ne2 Nc6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. O-O-O Qe5 14. Qc3 (14. c3 { it doesn't look healthy to weaken the queenside
like this, but it was a possible move, White also has attacking possibilities,
if he is able to control Black's initiative } 14... a5! { good and logical } 15. Ng3 h5! { like the 14.c3 move, this is necessary, making the h1-rook and the
g3-knight passive. It is worth losing a tempo for that, and there is an
important ...Bg4 threat } (15... a4?! 16. Bc4 { a multi-purpose move, helping
the defence and attacking f7 } 16... Qe7 17. h5 $16 { white is getting there fast! }) 16. Bc4 Qc7! 17. Rde1 Bg4 $36 { keeping the initiative. }) (14. Kb1 Bf5 (14... a5?! 15. Qe3! { exchanging queens, taking advantage of the hanging rook on e8 }) 15. Qc3 Nd4 16. Nxd4 cxd4 17. Qf3 h5! 18. Bc4 d3! $36) 14... Nd4! 15. Nxd4 cxd4 16. Qf3 (16. Qb4!?) 16... d3 { Black has to keep the initiative
somehow. } 17. c3 h5! 18. Bxd3 (18. Qxd3?! Bf5 19. Qg3 Qxg3 20. fxg3 Bg4! $17 { and the rook is trapped. }) (18. Qe3!? { now Black has the option to
choose between a draw and a weird endgame } 18... Qa5 (18... Bf5 { Black may try to
play this endgame, with the weak f1-bishop } 19. Qxe5+ Rxe5 20. Rg1! { following with f3 and g4 } 20... Rd8 21. f3 Kf6 22. g4 Be6 23. Rg2 { White will play
Rf2 and try to develop with Bg2 at some point } 23... Rd6 $44) 19. Qxe8 Qxa2 20. Qe5+ Kg8 21. Bxd3 Qa3+ { and White can't escape the perpetual check } 22. Kb1 Qxb3+ 23. Ka1 Qa3+ 24. Kb1 Qb3+ 25. Ka1) 18... Bg4 19. Qxb7 Rab8 20. Qa6 (20. Qxa7?! Ra8! { getting a2 back. }) 20... Bxd1 21. Rxd1 { White has three pawns
for the exchange, but the position remains quite open, which is scary when
your opponent has an additional rook for your bishop. In the next moves, we
have dozens of options on every single move, since the position is completely
open. Surprisingly both players go on to choose the computer's 1st suggestion
almost always, just showing how strong they are. } 21... Qf4 22. Qxa7 Ra8 23. Qc5 (23. g3!? Qd6 24. Qd4+ Qxd4 25. cxd4 Rxa2 26. Bc4 { with balanced chances in
the endgame. }) 23... Rxa2 24. Bb1 (24. Qd4+!? { similar to 23.g3. }) 24... Raa8 25. g3 Qf3 26. Qd4+ Kg8 27. Qf4 Qb7 (27... Qxf4 28. gxf4 { a very original
endgame! I would be scared with either colour. }) 28. b4? { The first real
mistake. } (28. Kb2! Qa7 29. Qc4 Qa3+ 30. Kc2 $13) 28... Qa6!? (28... Ra1! $17 29. Qd4 Qa8 { and Black has a scary attack. }) 29. Qf3 Qa3+ 30. Kc2 Rac8 31. g4? (31. Qd5! { was a nice way to deal with the pawn loss } 31... Qxb4 32. Ba2 Re7 33. f4 $36 { trying to follow with f5. }) 31... Rc4! 32. Qd5 Rxb4 33. Qa2 (33. cxb4 Rc8+ 34. Qc5 Rxc5+ 35. bxc5 Qxc5+ $19 { and Black wins easily after taking
on g4. }) 33... Qxa2+ 34. Bxa2 Rxg4 $19 { There is still play, but MVL concluded
the game with confidence from now on. } 35. Bd5 Rxh4 36. c4 Rf4 37. d4 Rxf2+ { Now suddenly Black is a pawn up! on the other hand, White's pawns are marching. } 38. Kc3 h4 39. c5 Re3+ 40. Kc4 Rc2+ 41. Kb5 h3 42. c6 h2 43. Kb6 Rg3 44. Be4 Rc4 45. Rd2 Rh3 46. Bh1 Rc1 47. Bg2 h1=Q 48. Bxh1 Rhxh1 49. d5 Rc3 50. Rb2 Rd1 51. Rb5 Kf8 52. Kc7 Ke7 { With the pawns controlled, White has to resign. } 0-1


