1. e4 (1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 { See the other
files for the Slav/Semi-Slav Black coverage. }) 1... c5 { Sicilian! If you
watched 'The Godfather' you will smile even more about this offer we can't
refuse ;) } 2. Nf3 (2. c3 d5 { This pawn break works well when
White can't play Nc3, or if he played some 2.d3 or 2.f4 sideline. } 3. exd5 { If 3.e5 Black gets a good French/Caro-Kann (see the Scandinavian file for
details). } 3... Qxd5 4. d4 { White puts a pawn in the centre, but we don't want to
trade on d4 too early, because after cxd4 White gets Nc3 with a tempo on the
queen. } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 e6 { This solid development is the simplest way to a good
game. In a more advanced file I suggest 5...Bg4 as a more dynamic alternative. } 6. Be2 Be7 { In principle, developing our kingside first is a safe way to
counter opening surprises. } 7. O-O O-O { Black's position is robust, and he
will play moves like ...cxd4, ...Nc6, ...Qd6 and ...Rd8 (...b6/...Bb7) to
pressure White's d4-pawn and equalise. }) 2... Nc6 { This is the most common
move order, but if you want to avoid variations like 3.Bb5, you can also start
with 2...g6. } 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 { Black's basic setup is ...Bg7/...Nf6/...
0-0. We will see the advantages of delaying the normal ...d6 a bit later. } 5. Nc3 { White should probably play the Maroczy Bind, 5.c4, to grab more space,
but we can still develop in the same way. } 5... Bg7 { Now White must deal with the
pressure down the long diagonal. By the way, this setup also works well
against Anti-Sicilians with 2.Nc3. } 6. Be3 (6. Nxc6 bxc6 { White often trades
on c6 at junior level, but it works well for Black, as we have more central
control and can get pressure down the half open b-file in the middlegame. }) 6... Nf6 { Black wants to play ...d5 against inaccurate moves by White, but not
before castling first ;) } 7. f3 { The most common move at club/junior level,
playing it like a 'normal' Dragon, but here there is an important difference -
Black has not played ...d6 yet! } (7. Bc4 O-O { We can also start with 7...Qa5,
but this move is more flexible and in my view gives White more chance to go
astray. } 8. f3 { The most common move, but not the most prudent. You see, the
e3-bishop is left undefended, as is the b2-pawn. We can exploit that
tactically - how? } (8. Bb3 { White should play this instead, to avoid the
tricks. } 8... d6 9. f3 Bd7 { We don't just develop the bishop but prepare queenside
play as well. } 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 { Black will advance the queenside
pawns for fine counterplay. }) 8... Qb6 9. Bb3 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Nxd4) 7... O-O 8. Qd2 { If White plays 8.Bc4, then ...d5 is not
possible anymore, but then we transpose to the 7.Bc4 line. } (8. g4 { also runs
into } 8... Qb6 { as we saw before. }) 8... d5 { Well done! Now Black uses his 'central
majority' to take control of the game. } 9. exd5 { White should probably castle
queenside instead, though Black would still be a tempo up on a normal Dragon! } 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 { With every exchange, Black's pieces are moving to more
active positions! This is because White takes first for each exchange. } 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 { Black is already comfortably better, with his more active bishops,
the central majority and ...Rd8 with a tempo later.  Total Variations: 7 } 0-1


