{ Introduction to the Queen's Indian Defence (QID) }
1. d4 { Usually the move 1.
d4 is connected with the full occupation of the centre via. 2.c4, 3.Nc3 and 4.
e4. The disadvantage of grabbing so much space is that White will take longer
to develop his kingside compared to 1.e4. } 1... Nf6 2. c4 (2. Nc3 d5 { leaves White
unable to challenge the d5-pawn with either c4 or e4. }) (2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4 b6 4. e3 Bb7 { and
generally speaking Black will follow with ...Be7, ...0-0 and either ...c5 or ..
.d5 (or both). }) 2... e6 3. Nf3 { White wants to avoid the pin with 3.Nc3 Bb4,
and therefore develops his kingside, keeping several options open. } (3. Nc3 Bb4 { , the Nimzo-Indian Defence, is the main idea of 2...e6 - Black makes it as
difficult as possible for White to play his desired e4 push. So the QID is not
a standalone defence to 1.d4 - you also have to learn the Nimzo (not to
mention White's non-2.c4 tries). }) (3. g3 { avoids the Queen's Indian as after
3...b6 4.Bg2 White's bishop would reach the long diagonal first. But we can
switch to a Queen's Gambit Declined with } 3... d5 4. Bg2 { and Black has several
decent systems, the simplest of which is } 4... Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 { , not so
much with the idea of keeping the c4-pawn, but using the time White spends
regaining the pawn to activate our light-squared bishop, e.g. } 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 (8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6) 8... b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 { and like in the QID, we
successfully challenged White's 'Catalan' bishop on g2. This variation is
outside the scope of this game and you might like to investigate it more
deeply, although it's unlikely you will see the Catalan in sub-2000 play. }) 3... b6 { This is the starting position of the Queen's Indian Defence. Sure,
it's not as trendy as the QGD transposition 3...d5, but it's a good opening
with a clear plan of controlling the central light squares (so that after 4.
Nc3 Bb7, White has difficulty achieving the e4 break). The author of 'My
System', Aron Nimzowitsch, was the pioneer of this opening. } (3... Bb4+ { , the Bogo-Indian, is playable but less flexible than the Nimzo-Indian as
White can play } 4. Bd2 { when Black will lose a little time dealing with the
threat to the b4-bishop. }) (3... d5) 4. g3 (4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 { is a Colle style
of development that should be taken seriously, as waiting too long to place a
pawn in the centre could lead to Black getting run over with an e4 or d5 break
at various stages. The easy way to avoid that event is } 5... d5 6. O-O Bd6 { which
you might recognise as the makings of a Colle-Zukertort setup for Black. After
the natural development } 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 { there's absolutely nothing
wrong with Black's position, and he can choose between central play with ...c5
or kingside attacking chances with ...Ne4. The position is quite strategic in
nature after } 9. Nc3 a6 { (avoiding 9...Qe7 10.Nb5) so you could get away with
only knowing the line to here when you first play the opening, but later on
you'll definitely benefit from a close study of these positions. }) (4. Nc3 { isn't a common move order at a high level because of } 4... Bb4 { when Black
transposes to a Nimzo-Indian, having avoided White's most critical tries. } (4... Bb7 { is also fine, when } 5. a3 { transposes to 4.a3. Most other moves
generally allow Black to equalise with ...Be7, ...0-0 and ...d5 - like a
Tartakower Queen's Gambit Declined, but where we play ...d5 last rather than
first! })) (4. a3 { , the Petrosian Variation, is White's main alternative to 4.
g3 and recently became popular at a high level. To the uninitiated it will
seem like a waste of time, but the point is to prepare Nc3 (fighting for the
e4-square) without allowing ...Bb4 pins, as we saw in the previous variation. } 4... Bb7 5. Nc3 { White has a positional threat to push d5 followed by e4 to take
over the centre, so we should fight for these light squares. } 5... d5 6. cxd5 { White has various moves, but this exchange is the most natural. } (6. Bg5 { is the start of a slightly peculiar sequence of moves, aimed at keeping the
b7-bishop behind Black's pawn chain, but it comes at a price. } 6... Be7 7. Qa4+ c6 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 { Black's bishop on b7 is a bit passive, but White
giving up the bishop pair advantage is no less important. The middlegame after } 10. g3 O-O 11. Bg2 { is quite strategic in nature, but it's unlikely you will
face this below the international level, so a player new to the QID could
probably skip this variation without trepidation. }) 6... Nxd5 { In general, we
want to recapture with the knight, so our bishop on b7 has an open diagonal.
Also, White will need a preparatory move to get in his desired e4 break. } 7. e3 g6 { This is the recent preference, fianchettoing the other bishop, although
there's nothing objectively wrong with developing the bishop to e7. } 8. Bb5+ { A little trick to prompt Black into closing the long diagonal of his bishop
with ...c6. If your opponent plays 8.Bd3 directly, you get an easier version
of the main line. } 8... c6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O { This position is still not
overly explored, but Black seems to be totally fine with a plan of ...Nd7, ...
Qe7 and getting in the c5 break. White has a lot of options on move 7 and 8,
but Black's general plan is pretty similar against each of them, and these a3
lines are rare in amateur games. }) 4... Bb7 { The most natural move and what I
will analyse, as it's easier to understand what's going on here. } (4... Ba6 { is the other main line, leading to more direct play in general. If you later
broaden your QID repertoire with this move, you should definitely study
Karjakin's Black games. }) 5. Bg2 Be7 { The most natural move, developing simply. } (5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 a5 { has also been played by good players, but it won't
make sense without first understanding the classical 5...Be7 variation. Let's
leave it for another time. }) (5... c5 { would be a positionally desirable move,
trying to trade our flank pawn for a central pawn. The problem is the pawn
sacrifice } 6. d5! { (as a rule of thumb, ...c5 is dubious if White can reply
with d5, shutting in our QID bishop) } 6... exd5 7. cxd5! Bxd5 8. Nc3 Bc6 9. e4! { and while it would take a detailed analysis to prove conclusively, take my
word for it that White's initiative and development far outweighs the
sacrificed material. For instance, } 9... Nxe4 { (otherwise e4-e5 will hurt) } 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Qe2 Qe7 12. O-O { leaves Black unable to get his king to safety, while
White plays Bf4/Rfe1/Qb5 for a killer attack. }) 6. O-O (6. Nc3 { gives us the
chance to introduce an important rule of thumb - when White plays Nc3, they
are threatening to get in the e4 break (with a preparatory d5 or Qc2). So we
should fight for the e4 square tooth and nail with } 6... Ne4 { with the idea that
our bishop will replace the knight in blockading the central light squares. } (6... O-O 7. Qc2 { is not terrible, but I would rather avoid it. }) 7. Bd2 (7. Nxe4 Bxe4 { just helps Black activate his bishop. }) 7... Bf6 { It may seem
tempting to grab the bishop pair with ...Nxd2, but it's better to wait until
we're provoked with Qc2. } 8. O-O O-O { We've transposed to the main line (6.0-0
0-0 7.Nc3 Ne4 8.Bd2 Bf6). }) 6... O-O { The vast majority of your opponents will
go 7.Nc3, but occasionally people try to move order Black. } 7. Nc3 { The most
natural move, although you'll know how to meet it already if you went through
the earlier variations. } (7. d5 { is the Polugaevsky Gambit, and one of the few
lines of the QID where it's important to remember the exact moves for Black. } 7... exd5 (7... Na6 { is a shortcut if you really want to decline the gambit, but
I'd prefer not to give White a free hand in the centre. }) 8. Nh4 c6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nf5 { At this point you might like to remember Black's next move as
it's a retreat, although you'll probably find it reassuring to know the
computer considers Black to have no less than four decent moves here! } 10... Nc7! { White was going to kick away our knight with e4 anyway, so we retreat
voluntarily to fight back in the centre with ...d5. } 11. e4 d5 12. Nc3 Bf6 13. exd5 cxd5 { By this point Black is relatively safe. If you get this far in a
game, keep in mind that you can sometimes give back the extra pawn on d5 later
to neutralise White's initiative. }) (7. Re1 { is the sort of move you'll only
really see from a titled player, but I've included it to show you might meet a
'waiting move' in general. } 7... Na6 { This is a good counter waiting move, and by
this point White usually blinks first with Developing this way is a decent
'counter waiting move'. } (7... d5 8. cxd5 exd5 { is generally considered
inaccurate against 4.g3 as it shuts in our light-squared bishop, but it's fine
if White played some not very useful move (like 7.Re1). }) 8. Nc3 { is the only
move that really makes sense, but that lets us play our thematic } 8... Ne4 { with
somewhat similar play to 7.Nc3. }) 7... Ne4 { This is a really important move to
remember, blockading White's desired d5 and e4 pushes. Since the position is
very quiet, Black can afford to move the same piece twice. } (7... d5 { is
traditionally considered dubious because of } 8. Ne5 { when Black comes under
pressure on the long diagonal. The computers actually don't think it's so bad
after } 8... Nbd7 { , but it's a lot easier to just avoid this. }) 8. Bd2 { This is the
dominant move at a high level. At club level I actually think you'll get
White's two other options more often, as most players are reluctant to give up
their bishop pair if they don't know it's book. } (8. Nxe4 Bxe4 { gives Black
quite simple play. If White plays quietly you can opt for a flexible setup
such as ...d6 and ...Nd7, and then it depends on what White does but you have
a lot of options, from ...c5 and ...e5 in the centre to ...f5 or ...a5 on the
flanks. Sometimes you can also hit in the centre with } 9. Ne1 Bxg2 10. Nxg2 d5 { , exploiting White's own loss of time with his knight moves. At the GM level
this is an established drawing line starting with } 11. Qa4 { , but at lower
levels there's still a lot that can happen, and pretty much any normal move is
fine for Black, with } 11... dxc4 12. Qxc4 c5 { being the most common (albeit also the
most drawish). }) (8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 { at least develops White's queen
compared to 8.Nxe4. Black can choose from several decent plans here and it's
hard to single out one as being the best, but I like } 9... f5 { as a somewhat more
combative choice. It allows allows Black to play } (9... Be4 { is sometimes a
good move to blockade the e4 break, though I have a few reservations in this
exact position. }) 10. b3 Bf6 11. Bb2 d6 { challenging White's queen and bishop
battery on the long diagonal. White would love to play d5 and shut out the
b7-bishop, but it's hard to do, e.g. } 12. Rad1 Qe8 { (guarding e6 against any
Ng5xe6 tricks) } 13. Ne1 Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nc6 { and the trade of two sets of minor
pieces makes it very hard for White to use his small space advantage in this
Dutch-like structure. White can try to play for the e4 break, but Black will
be fast with ...e5 himself. }) 8... Bf6 { With this move Black activates his
other bishop and places the d4-pawn under piece pressure. Again, we're fine
with moving the same piece twice, because we don't have a comfortable square
for the b8-knight. If you check the 8...d6 variation below, you'll also
appreciate that with the bishop on f6, White can't play d5 without accepting
doubled c-pawns. } (8... d6 { and ...Nd7 might seem more natural, and it's
playable too. After } 9. d5 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 e5 { We reach a King's Indian
structure we'll see in the main line (in that case, with the bishop on f6
instead of e7). While Black's bishop on b7 is currently out of play, it's not
the end of the world as White gave up the bishop pair and the light-squared
bishop can reroute via. c8. }) (8... d5 { is a more direct move and actually the
computer's first choice. I'd recommend going through Korobov's games if you
want to play this way, he's scored 4/5 against elite opposition after } 9. cxd5 exd5 { . }) 9. Rc1 { This is the most common move, preparing the d5 break once
again. Because the position is still quite unforcing, White has a lot of moves
and you don't have to memorise everything, but it's important to understand
roughly what's going on in the typical middlegame positions. } (9. Be1 { avoids .
..Nxd2 and is the latest craze at the time of writing. A common sense response
is switching to the 'occupy e4' plan with } 9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 { (White lost a tempo
with this capture) } 10... Be4 { when Black's position is fully playable after ...d5
or ...d6. I really wouldn't worry about this unless you're playing in
Grandmaster tournaments. }) (9. Ne5 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 c5 { used to be
considered a drawish line, but Black's won quite a few high-level games
lately! The endgame arising from } 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Qd6 Qb6 14. Rfd1 Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Be7 16. Rd2 d6 17. Nd3 { is definitely unbalanced enough for the stronger
player to win. }) (9. Qc2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 { looks like a strange loss of time, but
tempi won't be that important in the arising position. It will be a typical
battle between White's space and Black's bishop pair. } 10... d6 11. e4 (11. d5 e5 { is a pretty healthy version of the KID structure for Black, who will continue
with } 12. Ne1 Nd7 13. Nd3 a5 { followed by ...g6, ...Bg7, ...Bc8 and eventually
the thematic ...f5 break for a pretty comfortable position. White's main
problem is that without the dark-squared bishop he finds it very difficult to
engineer any kind of play on the queenside (where he has more space). }) 11... Nd7 12. Rad1 g6 { White's position looks better than it is - Black has a very
flexible Hippo-style formation and can chip away with ...c5 or ...e5 later
depending on the next several moves. It's even possible to play quietly with ..
.Bg7, ...Qe7, ...a6 and place the rooks on the side of the board you want to
play on. }) 9... Nxd2 (9... d6 { looks more flexible, but after } 10. d5 Nxd2 { White obtains the extra option of } 11. Nxd2 { which I'd rather avoid. }) 10. Qxd2 { Obviously Nxd2 drops the d-pawn. } 10... d6 { Thanks to the 9.Rc1 finesse, White has
the extra move Rac1 in compared to the position after 9.Qc2 Nxd2 10.Qxd2 d6.
The ideas remain similar for both sides, but let's consider a few
possibilities. } 11. d5 (11. e4 Nd7 12. Rfe1 g6 { it's not that easy to
find a more useful move than Rcd1 anyway, since even if White gets in the e5
break, it tends to just make the pawn vulnerable to attack. }) 11... e5 { As noted in the 9.Qc2 line, we have a closed pawn structure from the King's
Indian Defence, with a few important differences - White has conceded his
dark-squared bishop for a knight, but Black will lose quite a bit of time
rerouting his bishops to support an eventual ...f5 break. Fortunately the
position is not very time sensitive, as it will be extremely hard for White to
get in the c5 break after ...a5 and ...Nd7. } 12. e4 (12. h4 { This move looks
weird, but the idea is to be ready to play h5 after Black plays ...g6, trying
to create some play himself on the kingside. This takes a while to transpire
in practice, though. } 12... Nd7 13. Bh3 a5 { could transpose to 12.e4 if White plays
14.e4 here. But if White waits too long, Black will get in ...f5 without too
much trouble, e.g. } 14. Qc2 Nc5 15. b3 g6 16. a3 Bg7 17. b4 Nd7 { and although
White got in b4, he struggles to make further progress. }) 12... Nd7 (12... a5 13. h4 Bc8 { has never been played, but it could be interesting to hold up
White's Bh3 for a move. }) 13. h4 (13. b4 a5 14. a3 g6 { is a stalemate on the
queenside as we saw in some previous notes. }) 13... a5 14. Bh3 Nc5 { At this
point we'll follow a recent game between the elite GMs Wesley So and Richard
Rapport. Although White won the game, it's clear that Black dominated for the
first 30 moves. } 15. Kg2 Bc8 16. Rh1 { White is positioning himself to meet ...
g6 with h5, but it doesn't work that well in the game. } 16... Bxh3+ 17. Rxh3 Qd7 18. Nh2 (18. Ne1 { can be met in similar fashion to the game with } 18... h5 19. Nd3 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 g6 21. Rhh1 Bg7 { and the bishop will find a great home on h6, like in
the game - if Qe3 we renew the idea with ...Kh7. After that Black will be
ready to begin his kingside play with the thematic ...f5 break. }) 18... h5 19. f3 { White's moves from here were certainly not the best, although they
demonstrate the difficulty White has finding a good pawn break. In general f4
by White just transforms the dark-squared bishop into a monster after ...exf4. } 19... g6 20. g4 Kh7 21. Rh1 Rg8 { Black has prepared himself for the opening of the
kingside with gxh5. In the meantime it's hard to see what White's rooks are
doing on the closed h-file. } 22. Qd1 Bg7 23. Nf1 Bh6 24. Kf2 { A tactical
oversight. } (24. g5 Bg7 25. Ng3 Rgf8 { followed by ...f6 is still pleasant for
Black, but White's position is also playable. }) 24... Bc1 { A lovely move - the
bishop can't be taken because of the Nd3 fork. } 25. Ng3 (25. b3 { doesn't lose
a pawn, but Black's attack will be very potent after } 25... Bb2 26. Nb5 f5 { and
White can't avoid the opening of the kingside, where Black is stronger. }) 25... Bxb2 { Having won a pawn, Black was in control in 1-0 (48) So,W (2808)-Rapport,
R (2702) Wijk aan Zee 2017 and lost only because of mistakes in a winning
position.  Anyway, the consistent theme you probably noticed is Black's
differing ways of keeping the e4-square covered, although we shouldn't get too
fixated on this as the hypermodern Queen's Indian is open to various
interpretations. I deliberately started briefly and gradually went into more
detail as we went through the variations, to show some typical middlegame
positions as well as how you can broaden your own knowledge with research and
naturally your experiences in this opening.   I wish you success in your games
with this opening! Max  Total Variations: 24 } 0-1


