1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 { In general, I will be recommending a
'light-squared' approach within the Nimzo, where we control the key e4-square
with either ...d5 or ...b6/...Bb7, depending on White's choice. } 4. Qc2 { I had initially made 4.e3 my main line, but when I checked on Lichess, it's
the Classical Variation, 4.Qc2, that is most popular at the club level!
Perhaps it's because in this line, White can avoid doubled pawns and obtain
the bishop pair advantage with a3 and Qxc3, albeit at the cost of some time. } (4. e4? Nxe4) (4. Qb3 { is a pretty harmless sideline; the
d4-pawn is vulnerable and we can exploit that with } 4... c5! 5. dxc5 Nc6 { , when
White has to content with ...Nd4 and ...Ne4. } 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 { still doesn't
save the pawn after } 6... h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6) 6... Ne4 { White now has to give up
the bishop pair to avoid the trebling of his queenside pawns. } 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2 f5! { Black could also recapture on c5 immediately, but I prefer to stop
Nde4, activating White's passive knight. } 9. e3 (9. g3 { is probably better,
but the same plans as in the next note still work. }) 9... Bxc5 { Black has a
fantastic score in practice, based on castling kingside and reaching a
turbocharged Hedgehog with ...b6/...Bb7. In general we will attack on
whichever side White castles. }) (4. Bf4 { is a questionable hybrid of the
Queen's Gambit and London setups, which tends to backfire when Black can play
a quick ...c5 or ...e5 break: } 4... d6!? 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Nf3 Qe7 { and ...e5 is
one way to exploit the bishop's slightly vulnerable placement. }) (4. Bd2 { is pretty harmless, but can't really be punished either, so we should
transpose to our Rubinstein line with } 4... O-O 5. e3 b6! (5... d5 6. a3!? Be7 { is surely harmless, but we've been move ordered into a weird QGD position that
isn't similar to any other part of our Nimzo repertoire. }) 6. Nf3 Bb7 7. Bd3 d5 { We cover this position under the 4.e3 0-0 5.Nf3 d5 6.Bd2 move order. }) (4. g3 { is the Romanishin Variation, considered harmless until very recently, when So
and Caruana revitalised it with some interesting gambit ideas. } 4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5! { The most principled, punishing White for playing Nc3 too early in the
Catalan. } (5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 $13 { and ...e5 is a viable low-theory
alternative, if one wishes to postpone the study of this rare line. }) 6. Nf3 (6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 { isn't a pawn we'll be able to hang on to, but White
will lose time in development regaining the c4-pawn: } 8. Qa4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 { and Black has no problems with his strong grip on the light squares. }) 6... dxc4 7. O-O Nc6! { This is an important move, pressuring d4 so White
can't regain the lost pawn with Ne5xc4. Now White has various options, but the
most critical is } 8. Qa4! { , playing to regain the pawn with a3 and later
Qxc4. The disadvantage is that the queen is exposed on a4 to ...Nd5-b6: } 8... Nd5! 9. Qc2 Be7! { Prophylaxis, so we can meet e4 with ...Ndb4-d3, exploiting the
potential outpost. } 10. Rd1 Bd7!? { A useful developing move that also
prepares the ...b5 break, hanging on to the extra pawn. White has a few tries
here, but despite Caruana's recent win against So in a rapid game, Black's
position looks objectively very healthy, as he can easily hang on to his extra
pawn with ...Nb6, which incidentally is why you will see Black meet } 11. e4 { with } 11... Ncb4! $132 { , rather than the more obvious ...Ndb4. }) (4. Bg5 { is the
Leningrad Variation (so named after Boris Spassky), which you don't see much
anymore, because after } 4... c5 5. d5 d6 6. e3 exd5 7. cxd5 Nbd7 { White has a worse
version of a normal Benoni structure, with Black's bishop on b4 in one go
instead of g7. If you already know some things about the Nimzo, you may wonder
why we didn't flick in ...h6 to chase their bishop. The reason becomes clear
in the following variation: } 8. Bd3 Qa5 9. Ne2 Nxd5 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 { With ...h6/Bh4 inserted, this position would favour White, but the undefended
bishop on g5 gives Black a trick you'd do well to remember: } 11... c4! { and Black
equalises, since } 12. Bxc4?? N5b6! { wins a piece. }) (4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 { is the Samisch Variation, which you don't see very often as Black can obtain
the more comfortable game by quite simple and well-known means, connected with
play against the weak c4-pawn: } 5... c5! { Naturally, we should fix the enemy
weakness before we attack it, so it cannot move away. } 6. e3 Nc6 (6... b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. e4 Ne8 { is the same thing, but with f3 and ...
Bb7 inserted. It's also possible, but one good line is enough. }) 7. Bd3 O-O { Castling is a waiting move to some extent, because our setup varies depending
on where White moves his knight. } 8. Ne2 (8. e4 { is well met by } 8... d5!) (8. Nf3!? { isn't a move you will see that often, as now White can't
attack Black's king with e4 and f4/f5. On the other hand, he can defend his
c4-pawn with Nd2 if we try to attack it. The simplest reply is } 8... d6 9. e4 e5 { , reaching a Hubner Variation with an extra tempo for Black, as White played
a3 earlier (in the Hubner, Black plays ...Bxc3 without being provoked by a3). }) 8... b6 9. e4 { White threatens an unpleasant Bg5 pin, so we should prevent it. } 9... Ne8! { Once you know this move, the rest comes fairly naturally - attack the
c4-pawn with pieces, and stop White's kingside attack. } 10. O-O Ba6 11. f4 f5! { Now it is hard for White to progress his kingside attack. The position is
still about equal, but it feels easier to play Black, since his plan is more
obvious - hold the kingside/centre and grab the c4-pawn with ...Na5. The one
situation we should avoid is } 12. e5?! Na5?! (12... d6! $17) 13. d5 Bxc4? (13... d6! $15) 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. d6! $16 { , when the e8-knight, and
subsequently the f8-rook, is unable to enter the battle on the queenside, but
a quick ...d6! would have given Black the advantage. }) (4. f3 { is the Kmoch
Variation, with the idea of e4. It's a favourite of Mamedyarov and often leads
to quite sharp play, though you'll see it more at GM level than anywhere else. } 4... c5 { This move basically forces an improved version of the Samisch Benoni for
Black. The most solid continuation is } (4... d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Ne7! { , which has been the recent recommendation
of repertoire resources. However, it requires a fair bit of memorisation for a
line you won't face much at amateur level. } 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Qc7 12. Bb5 Nec6 13. Ne2 Na5 14. Qb4 e5 15. O-O Na6 16. Bxa6 bxa6) 5. d5 O-O 6. e4 d6! { Continuing normal development. The general plan is ...a6/...b5/...Nbd7-e5/...
Re8 in some order. } (6... b5!? { forces greater precision from boh sides - my
recommendation is more forgiving if you forget the theory. }) 7. Ne2 b5!? { This is one point where I want to play more forcefully, as I'm not entirely
convinced by Black's position if White gets enough time to consolidate his
centre. A key point behind Black's play is that } 8. Nf4 exd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 { runs into } 10... Qb6! { when taking on a8 fails to ...Bb7, but } 11. Bf4 Be6 12. Qxd6 Qa5! $44 { also gives Black a full share of the play in a
complicated position, thanks to his serious lead in development. }) (4. Nf3 { is a flexible move which can transpose to several other variations. I'll be
recommending a transposition to the Queen's Indian with } 4... b6 { , since this also
fits with my other recommendations. } 5. e3!? { This move orders us into a
different variation of the Rubinstein, with ...b6 instead of ...0-0.
Fortunately, it's a harmless line where White's early Nf3 greatly limits his
options. Alternatives: } (5. Qc2 Bb7 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 O-O { transposes to my
4.Qc2 recommendation, but here White is reduced to setups with Nf3. }) (5. Bg5 { is the old main line, but now considered quite harmless because of } 5... h6 6. Bh4 g5! (6... Bb7 7. Nd2!? { is not that scary, with } 7... e5!? $13 { being a particularly creative reply, but I would nonetheless prefer to avoid
it. }) 7. Bg3 Ne4 { - as with 5.e3, we can try to benefit from the delayed ...
Bb7. } 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. e3 (9. Nd2 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 d6 { is fairly
similar to 9.e3 - if } 12. e4 Nd7 13. Be2 Qe7 { White may have more central
space, but it seems difficult to exploit. }) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. Bd3 Nxg3 { The simplest, playing as in a system opening. } (11... f5!? { was my old
preference, but it requires a bit more memorisation. }) 12. hxg3 g4! 13. Nh4 Nc6 14. Be4 Qe7 15. a4 a5 { White's knight on h4 is quite offside, and
while the position should be objectively equal, I'd rather be Black. We will
castle queenside, where our king is untouchable. }) 5... Bb7 (5... Ne4 6. Qc2 Bb7 7. Bd3 f5 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 O-O { , since Rubinstein exponents usually prefers to avoid this position.
Black generally goes for ...d6 and ...e5 as his middlegame plan, though
passive play by White may permit ...Rf6-h6(g6) attacking ideas. The main line
runs } 10. Nd2 Qh4 (10... Nxd2 11. Bxd2 Qh4 12. f3 { just transposes. }) 11. f3 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 d6!? 13. Be1 Qg5 14. e4 fxe4 15. Bxe4 Qe3+ 16. Bf2 Bxe4 17. fxe4 Qg5 18. Qa4 Qe7 { (then ...Qd7!), and White can't claim a real edge from
his space advantage, as too many pieces were traded and Black will get in ...
