with } 14. Rac1 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Rc5! { followed by } 16. Bd3 Qc7! 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. exf6?! Qf4! $15 { being a key trick to keep Black's game afloat. }) 12. bxc3 Nbd7 { is a typical hanging pawns structure, where Black has no
problems, but as always there are various subtleties you should master at some
point in your career as a Nimzo player. }) (11. Re1 Nbd7 12. Rc1 { can also
arise via. 11.Rc1 Nbd7 12.Re1. After } 12... Rc8 13. Bd3 (13. Qb3 Bxc3 14. Rxc3 h6 15. Bh4 Bd5 { trades off White's bishop pair, completely equalising the position in
turn. }) 13... h6 14. Bh4 Be7 15. Bb1 Re8 16. Qd3 Nf8 { , as played in
numerous correspondence and GM games, Black has a rock solid position against
all White's attacking attempts, and with } 17. Ne5 Nd5 { , or 17...Nh5, can
initiate the minor piece exchanges that tend to favour the side facing the IQP. }) 11... Nc6!? { This is the one case where I like the more active knight
development, though } (11... Nbd7 { is also playable, if you want to play the
same setup every time. After } 12. Qe2 Bxc3 13. Rxc3 { Black should only know
the finesse } 13... Qb8! { , threatening ...Ne4, for rough equality. }) 12. Re1 (12. a3 { can be met by either the exchange or the retreat. I propose } 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 (13. Rxc3 Rc8) 13... Rc8 14. Bd3 h6 15. Bh4 Ne7! 16. Bxf6 gxf6 { , as it's instructive to observe that Black's king is perfectly safe in
this structure, and may even generate attacking chances down the half-open
g-file and long diagonal if White is incautious. }) 12... h6 13. Bh4 Rc8 14. Bd3 Be7 { We have seen this retreat before, but it's important to understand why
it's important - we want to trade their bishop with ...Nh5! } 15. Bb1 Nh5! { Black is fine, though one tactical point must be noted: } 16. Qd3 (16. Qc2 g6 17. Rxe6 Nf4! $17) 16... g6 17. Rxe6? Nf4! $19) 4... O-O { The most
flexible reply, particularly if White doesn't play the consistent 5.a3. } 5. a3 (5. Bg5 { is quite harmless - we already know the answer from our Leningrad
analysis. } 5... c5 6. dxc5 Na6! 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 { Black has no problems in this structure, as White lacks the development
to consolidate his position. Our basic setup is ...b6/...Bb7/...a5, also in
the case of } 11. b4 Na4) (5. e4 { leads to quite sharp play. } 5... d5! (5... d6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 e5 8. Bd3 c5 { avoids the theoretical discussion, but at
the price of giving White a tiny bishop pair edge. }) 6. e5 Ne4 7. Bd3 (7. a3 { is too ambitious after } 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 c5 9. Bd3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Qa5+! 11. Kf1 Nc6 12. Ne2 f6! $44 { gives Black a strong attack on White's king for the
pawn. }) 7... c5 8. Ne2 (8. Nf3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 { transposes. }) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nd7 { This is better than ...Nc6, first because the knight won't be traded off,
and second to have ...Ndc5 available to support our e4-knight. } 10. Bf4 Qh4 (10... Ndc5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 b6 14. cxd5 exd5 { is the
solid alternative, though White objectively has more chances of an advantage
here than after 10...Qh4, due to his strong knight and e5-pawn, which is not
so easy to challenge. }) 11. g3 Qh5 12. O-O g5! 13. cxd5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 exd5 { The position remains incredibly sharp, but engine analysis shows that Black is
doing fine. }) (5. Nf3 { is thematically met by } 5... c5 6. dxc5 Na6! { , just like
we saw after 5.Bg5. White has various options, but the main line runs } 7. g3 (7. c6 bxc6 8. g3 d5 { gives Black very healthy play in the centre. }) 7... Nxc5 8. Bg2 Nce4 { The most critical, to double White's queenside pawns. } (8... b6 9. O-O Bb7 { is a less theoretically intensive alternative. }) 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. e4 d6 12. e5! { White must play dynamically, or his doubled c-pawns
will become a sore point. } 12... dxe5 13. Nxe5 Qc7 14. Qe2! { White does possess
some piece pressure, but Black can neutralise it with accurate play: } 14... Bd6! 15. Bf4 Ne8! { and now White has to find } 16. c5 Qxc5 17. c4 { , with good
compensation for the pawn, but not more than that after } 17... Rb8! { ,
preparing both ...f6 and ...b6/...Bb7(a6). }) 5... Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6!? (6... d5 { is the dominant line at the elite level, but I find the old main line to be
no worse, and it's also the preference in correspondence. }) 7. Bg5 { The most
critical, as we don't have a dark-squared bishop to break the pin. However,
once our knight gets to d7 the pin won't be an issue anyway. } (7. Nf3 Bb7 8. e3 (8. g3 { is harmless for various reasons, but I like } 8... a5!? { with the idea of
clamping White's queenside: } 9. Bg2 (9. b3 d6 10. Bg2 c5!? $132 { is an
interesting alternative to the usual ...Nbd7 and occupying e4 with a piece. }) 9... a4 10. Bg5 d6 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. O-O Nd7 { If anything it's easier to
play Black here, as White lacks a good pawn break. }) 8... d6 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 f5 12. b4 { White has played normal moves, but his position
could even prove slightly dangerous after } 12... Rf6! { followed by ...Rh6/...Rg6,
as } 13. d5 c5! 14. dxc6 Bxc6 $13 { reopens the long diagonal for our bishop. }) 7... Bb7 8. e3 { The main line, although the quiet nature of the position gives
White a few alternatives. } (8. Nf3 d6 9. Nd2 { is a bit slow, and if White
moves the same piece more than once, opening the centre tends to work well: } 9... Nbd7 10. f3 h6 11. Bh4 c5! 12. e4 Rc8 { Black will rip open the centre with ..
.d5!, and if } 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 { is a fairly safe
endgame for Black, thanks to his lead in development. }) (8. f3 { was the old
main line, but it's not seen that often because of the following long
variation: } 8... h6 9. Bh4 d5! { The thematic counter to f3, not permitting the e4
break at all. } 10. e3 (10. cxd5 exd5! { is the correct reply when we have } 11. e3 Re8! { to stop the Bd3/Ne2 setup. }) 10... Nbd7 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 { This endgame is equal, as White is too far behind in development to use
the bishop pair advantage (which only 'kicks in' after all the pieces are out). } 13. Bh4 (13. Bxc7 Nd5 14. Bf4 { is hardly inspiring for White, while }) (13. Be7 Rfe8 14. Bh4 Nd5 15. Bf2 { might allow ...c5 to be met with Bb5!, but } 15... e5! { now gains in strength with the rook on e8. After } 16. e4 exd4 17. O-O-O Nf4 18. Bxd4 Rad8 { Black has no real problems after the subsequent ...Ne6. }) 13... Nd5 14. Bf2 c5 15. e4 Ne7 16. Ne2 (16. Bb5 Bc6 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. Ne2 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Rac8 { is rather drawish, with ...f6/...Rfd8/...Kf7/....
e5 to follow. }) 16... f5! 17. exf5 Nxf5 18. dxc5 Nxc5 $132 { Black has nice
activity, and while the position is nearly exclusively drawn in correspondence,
in practical play there are some chances for the stronger player to win. }) 8... d6 9. Ne2 (9. Nf3 Nbd7 10. Nd2 c5 { gives Black good play in the centre,
especially if we recapture on c5 with the b-pawn. }) (9. f3 Nbd7 10. Bd3 c5 { is similar - White doesn't develop in time to use his bishop pair advantage. }) 9... Nbd7 { White wants to bring his knight to c3 and then develop the
f1-bishop and castle kingside, stopping ...Ne4 ideas, but the question now is
where the queen should move first. } 10. Qc2 (10. Qd3 Ba6! 11. Nc3 d5 $132 { is a nice way to exploit the queen's exposed position on d3. }) 10... c5 $132 { We will eventually place the rook on c8, opposite the enemy queen, but we can
throw in a few other developing moves first: } 11. Rd1 Qe7!? 12. Nc3 cxd4 13. Rxd4 h6 14. Bh4 Ne5 { There is some more theory from here, but objectively the
position is equal, with White still struggling to develop his kingside, while
the c4-pawn may come under pressure in the near future. If one is concerned
about the pin, ...Ng6 will resolve that problem. } 0-1


