1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 (2. Bc4 Bc5 3. c3 Nc6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5) 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 Qe7?! { Diagram
# Jude Acers notes: "Players of the White pieces will swiftly win
gamesthroughout their careers against anything but direct center counterplay
by Black [by d5]. All piece moves are bad." The Queen is exposed to attacks
along the e-file, along the h4-d8 diagonal, and sometimes by Nc3-d5 etc. } (6... dxc3? { which seems essentially a
counting mistake: Black is down a piece after } 7. exf6 Qxf6 8. Qe2+ Ne7 9. Nxc3 c6 10. O-O d5 11. Bg5 Qg6 12. Bd3 Qh5 13. h3 Be6 14. Bf4 h6 15. Na4 Bb4 16. a3 Ba5 17. Nc5 g5 18. Nxe6 gxf4 19. Nxf4 { 1-0 George,N-Jorgensen,M/Menorca 1996 }) 7. O-O!? { This may be the most forcing continuation, but better may be } (7. cxd4! Bb4+ 8. Nc3! (8. Kf1!? $16) 8... d6 (8... Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 f5 11. O-O d6 12. exd6 cxd6 13. Re1 $18) 10. bxc3 Ba5 11. O-O h6 (11... O-O 12. Ng5! g6 13. Ne4 Kg7 14. Bg5 Qa3 15. Bf6+ Kg8 16. Qd2 $18) 12. Bd2 d6 13. Rfe1 O-O 14. Bxh6! gxh6 15. Qg6+ Kh8 16. Qxh6+ Kg8 17. Re4 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Be6 19. Rh4 f6 20. Bxe6+ Qxe6 21. Qg6# { 1-0 Primavera,C-Ruiz,S/
Chapadmalal 2003 }) (8... d5?! 9. O-O! dxc4 10. exf6 gxf6 (10... Qxf6 11. d5 Bxc3 12. dxc6 Ba5 13. cxb7 Bxb7 14. Qa4+ $18)) (8... Na5 9. O-O! $40) (8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 d5 10. Bd3 Ne4 11. Qb3 $16) 9. O-O! dxe5 10. dxe5! Ng4 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ne4 (11... Ng4? 12. Bb5) (11... Nd7 12. Bg5 Qa3 (12... Qc5? 13. Bxf7+!! Kxf7 14. e6+ Kxe6 15. Qb3+ Qd5 16. Rfe1+ Nde5 17. Rxe5+ Nxe5 18. Nd4+ Kd6 19. Be7+ $18) 13. e6 fxe6 14. Bxe6 $40) 12. Bd5 Nc5 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Ba3 $18) 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Nxb4 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nh6 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Kh1 $18 Rg8 19. Rg1 Kd7 20. Rad1+ Ke6 21. f4 Rad8 22. Rxg8 Rxd1+ 23. Kg2 Rd4 24. Nc2 Rxf4 25. Rh8 Rg4+ 26. Kf3 Rg7 27. Re8+ Kd7 28. Ra8 b6 29. Rxa7 Rg5 30. Kf4 Rg2 31. Kf3 { .. 1-0 Krys,J-Reichel,T/Frymburk
2000 }) 7... Ng8? (7... Nxe5 { is necessary, when Black survives by
giving up his queen for bishop and Rook after } 8. Re1 (8. Nxe5!? Qxe5 9. Re1 Ne4 $13) 8... Nxc4 (8... Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 $18) 9. Rxe7+ Bxe7 10. Qe2 d5 11. cxd4 $14 { with at least some advantage to White. }) (7... Ng4? 8. cxd4 Bb4 9. h3 Nh6 10. a3 Ba5 11. b4 Bb6 12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. Nc3 $18 { and the threats of
d5-d6 or Nd5-f6+ are deadly and unstoppable. }) 8. cxd4 (8. Bg5!?) 8... Bb6 (8... Bb4 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 Bb6 { is even worse. }) 9. d5! (9. Re1 Qd8 10. d5 Na5 11. Bg5 f6?? (11... Ne7 12. d6 $18) 12. exf6+ Kf7 13. fxg7 Nf6 14. gxh8=Q Qxh8 15. Bd3 d6 16. b4 Bg4 17. bxa5 Bxa5 18. Nbd2 Rg8 19. Qe2 Nxd5 20. Qe4 { 1-0
Neugebauer,J-Goetz,K/Weilburg 1996 }) 9... Qc5 (9... Na5 10. d6 { with the
plan of boxing Black in is effective } (10. Bd3 { with the plan of embarrassing
the Knight at a5 is also good, e.g.: } 10... Qc5 11. Nc3 Ne7 12. Be3 Qb4 13. Bd2 $18) 10... Qf8 (10... Qd8? 11. Bg5) 11. Bd5 $18) (9... Nd8 10. Nc3 Qb4 11. Qe2 $18) 10. Na3 Nd4 (10... Na5 11. Be3 Qb4 12. Bd2! Qxb2 (12... Qc5 13. b4 $18) (12... Qe7 13. Bd3 { and White will win the Knight at a5 }) 13. Qa4 $18 Nxc4? 14. Nxc4 $18 { and Black's Queen is trapped }) (10... Nce7 11. Be3 $18) 11. Be3 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Qf8 (12... Qe7 13. d6! cxd6 14. Bg5! f6 (14... Qf8 15. Nb5!) (14... Qxg5 15. Qxf7+ Kd8 16. Qf8+ Kc7 17. Nb5+ Kb8 18. Qxd6+ Bc7 19. Qxc7#) 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Rae1 $18) 13. Bxb6! axb6 { Diagram # } 14. Nb5 Kd8 { White's super central pawns completely dominate the board and Black's
forces sit in confusion upon the first rank. White has too many winning moves
to count! } (14... Qc5 15. d6 $18) 15. Rac1 d6 16. exd6 cxd6 17. Qe3 Ra6 18. Nc7 Qe7 19. Ne6+!! fxe6 20. Bxa6 Bd7 (20... bxa6 21. Qxb6+ Ke8 22. Rxc8+ Kf7 23. Rc7 $18) 21. Bb5!? Ke8 (21... Bxb5 22. Qxb6+ Ke8 23. Qxb5+ $18) 22. dxe6 Nf6 (22... Bc6) 23. Rc8+ { Black was dead in the opening and the rest of White's
attack practically played itself -- though it's impressive that Morphy could
conduct it so well in a blindfold simul! Those looking to be precise in the
opening, however, should probably prefer 7.cxd4 to Morphy's 7.O-O. } 1-0


