1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 d6 5. O-O Nf6 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb6 8. h3 h6?! (8... Nxe4 { which is also the line
modern theory recommends. }) 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 Re8 11. d5 Bxe3 12. dxc6 Bb6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Qb3?! (14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Nxe5 { with a clear advantage for White. }) 14... Re7 { [#] } 15. Bxf7+ { Morphy strives for tactical complications. Modern engines,
however, think that this violent approach is premature. But when judging this
game one should not forget that it is a blindfold game from 1849. } 15... Rxf7 16. Nxe5 Qe8 17. cxb7 Bxb7 18. Rae1 Ba6 19. Ng6 { [#] The critical position.
White's rook on e1 attacks Black's queen and White threatens to play 20.Re7.
How should Black defend against these threats? } 19... Qd8? { Black misses a hidden
tactical ressource which modern engines find immediately. } (19... Bxf2+! 20. Kxf2 Rb8! { The point of Black's 19th move. Now White can take
Black's queen with check, but after } 21. Rxe8+ Nxe8+ { Black has a countercheck
after which he regains the queen with interest. After } 22. Qxf7+ Kxf7 { Black
attacks the white knight on g6 and the rook on f1. Black is clearly better.
But in the game Black missed this tactical shot and lost immediately. }) 20. Re7 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


