{ Paul Morphy (11 and 12 years old) soon defeated the five players then
reigning supreme in the New Orleans Chess Club: Eugene Rousseau, Ernest Morphy,
A. P. Ford, Charles Le Carpentier and James (later judge) McConnell. }
1. e4 { Lawson: Paul Morphy. p.22. Out of the 30 games played with McConnell about
that time, Paul lost but one. } 1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. Bc4 Bg7 5. d3 h6 6. O-O Nf6 { c2/d3/e4 structure is fine -
not when we sacked a pawn } { [%csl Gd3,Ge4][%cal Gd2d4,Ge4e5,Gb1c3] } 7. c3 { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5] } 7... b5 (7... O-O { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd7d5] }) 8. Bxb5 c6 9. Bc4 d5 10. exd5 cxd5 11. Qe2+ Be6 12. Bb3 O-O 13. d4 Ne4 14. Bc2 f5 15. Nbd2 Nc6 16. c4 Bxd4+ 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 { One should not push the f-pawn without a good reason
(weakening) } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gb6g1,Gh4e1] } 18. Qd3 Qb6 19. Kh1 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 { Black to play (P) - what's the
most clinical win? (P) } 20... Nf2+ { [%cal Gf1f2,Gb6f2] } 21. Kg1 { [%cal Gb6g1] } 21... Nh3+ 22. Kh1 { Smothered mate } 22... Nf2+ { 0-1 White resigns. } (22... Qg1+!! 23. Rxg1 Nf2# { Morphy games -
good set of puzzles for checkmating patterns 'Berserk' - get half the time on
the clock, but you get one more point if you win Lichess tourneys - rewarded
for winning fast, and for berserking (if you win) }) 0-1


