1. e4 { Born in France (1810) but settled in New Orleans around 1842, Rousseau
was the leading player of the Chess Club in New Orleans. In Paris he is said
to have lost by a very small balance only in over 100 games with Kieseritzky.
In 1845 he lost a match for the U.S. Championship against Stanley. Lawson:
Paul Morphy. p.22. During 1848-1849, out of over fifty games with Paul, he
have won five at most. Of all these games the records of but two survived. } 1... e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ng5 h6 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qxg4 Qf6 8. Bc4+ Ke7 9. Nc3 c6 10. e5 Qxe5+ 11. Kd1 Kd8 12. Re1 { How to defend is also
important - Black is up a piece, we would love to trade queens } { [%cal Ge1e5] } 12... Qc5 (12... Nf6! { [%cal Ge1e5,Gf6g4] } 13. Qf3 Qd4 { [%cal Gd4c4] }) (12... Qg7 { [%cal Gg7g4] }) 13. Bxg8 { [%csl Gd8,Gd1,Gg4,Gg8,Ge1,Gc3] } 13... d5 { How do we deal with the attack
on White's queen? (P) White to play } (13... d6 { [%csl Gd6,Gd5][%cal Gd7d6,Gg8e6] } 14. Re8+ Kxe8 15. Qxc8+ Ke7 { [%cal Gd6d5,Gc3d5,Gc6d5,Gd6c5] } 16. Qxb7+ Nd7 17. Qxa8 { [%csl Gd1] } 17... Qg1+ 18. Ke2 Qxg2+ 19. Ke1 { [%csl Ge1] } 19... Qh1+ 20. Ke2 Rxg8 { Black queen adn rook vs. long king } { [%cal Gg8g2] }) 14. Re8+!! (14. Be6 Bxe6 { [%csl Ge6,Ge8][%cal Ge8a8] } 15. Rxe6 { [%csl Gg4,Gd2][%cal Gd2d3,Gf4b8] } (15. Qxe6 Nd7 16. Qe8+ Kc7 17. Qxa8 Bg7 { [%csl Ga8] } 18. Re8 Qg1+ { [%cal Gd1e2,Gg1g2] })) 14... Kxe8 15. Qxc8+ Ke7 16. Nxd5+! Kd6 (16... cxd5 17. Qxc5+) 17. Qc7# { Swindle } 1-0


