[Event "USA-01 Congress Grand Tournament"]
[Site "New York,NY"]
[Date "2018.06.22"]
[Round "4.1"]
[White "Morphy, Paul"]
[Black "Paulsen, Louis"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "ChessBase"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Paulsen-Basman Defense"]
[StudyName "Craze's Study"]
[ChapterName "Morphy, Paul - Paulsen, Louis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/r2kuauyW/5qYNU65z"]

{ Paul Morphy - greatest chess player of the mid-19th century (Romantic,
combinative style) - how to develop the pieces quickly and actively }
1. e4 { Daniel Fiske: The First American Chess Congress New York 1857, p. 240. Louis
Paulsen, born 1833 in Nassengrund, Lippe/Detmold (GER), went to U.S. in 1854
with his elder brother Wilfried and became a tobacco-broker. When the civil
war startet he returned to Europe and came just in time to play in September
1861 the Chess Association Tournament in Bristol. In London 1862 he become
second behind Anderssen. } 1... c5 2. d4 (2. Nf3 { [%cal Gd2d4] }) 2... cxd4 3. Nf3 e6 4. Nxd4 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gg8f6] } 4... Bc5?! { Basman-Sale
Variation - White to play (P) } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Gd8b6,Gb6f2] } 5. Nb3 { Morpy was the
first player to find this plan in connection with 7. Bf4 using the weak point
at d6. } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gb3c5] } (5. Nc3 Qb6 $13) 5... Bb6 6. Nc3 Ne7 { Weak
squares - find those squares that can't be covered with a pawn } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gb6g1] } 7. Bf4 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Gf4d6] } 7... O-O (7... d5 { Looks interesting } 8. exd5 exd5 { Isolated Queen's Pawn (IQP) } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5d4] }) 8. Bd6! { b7/d7-pawns can be called 'traitors' - kill his own bishop
(on c8) } { [%csl Gc8,Gb7,Gd7][%cal Gc8b7,Gc8d7] } 8... f5 9. e5 { Opening is not just about developing the
pieces, controlling the centre and castling - making this harder for the
opponent } { [%csl Ge5,Gd6] } 9... a6 { Blacks position is not easy: A weak square on d6, a
backward weak pawn on d7 and a not easy to develop Bishop on c8. The good
thing is, that White has no concrete threats. Turning a better position
(positional advantage) into a win } { [%csl Gd6] } (9... Bc7 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc7d6,Gd1d6] } 10. Be2 Bxd6 { [%cal Ge5d6] } 11. Qxd6 { [%csl Gd6] }) 10. Be2 { White plays the
'football game' - get all his pieces into the action (no one is left behind) } 10... Nbc6 11. O-O Rf7 { 'Look at all checks and captures' (tactical
puzzle) No big tactics (such as this one) - how can we improve our position?
Improve the placement of our pieces? } { [%csl Gd6] } 12. Kh1 { Often see moves like Kh1 in these positions (when the opponent has this
'sniper' on the a7-g1 diagonal) } { [%csl Gf4,Ge5,Gd6][%cal Gf2f4] } 12... f4 { Preventing White to play f2-f4 it opens the square f5 for Ne7 or Rf7, but
weakens the square e4. White to play (P) Simple Decisions (not a game winning
or game saving move) - 3 questions that can help to make a good decision 1.
Where are the weaknesses? 2. What is the opponent's idea? 3. Which is the
worst-placed piece? (pieces can be like links in a chain, a chain is only as
strong as its weakest link) } { [%csl Gd7,Gd6,Ge5][%cal Ge7f5,Gf7f5] } (12... g5 { To prepare activities on the King's
wing. } 13. Na4 Bc7 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. Qd6 Nd5 16. Qxc7 Nxc7 17. Bh5 Rg7 18. Nb6 $14) (12... Ba7 { To free the b-pawn with a possible Bc8-b7. } 13. f4 g5 14. fxg5 Ng6 15. Qd2 Ncxe5 16. Rad1 $14) 13. Ne4 { Outpost squares (squares that can't be covered by an opposing
pawn) - Knights are best at occupying these squares Knight on the 6th rank is
often called an 'octopus' } { [%cal Ge4d6,Gd6c8,Gd6f7,Gd6b7,Gd6f5,Gd6c4] } (13. Bd3 { Is freeing the way for the Queen Qd1-h5 } 13... Bc7 14. Nd2 Nxe5 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Qxe5 Bxd6 18. Qxd6 $14) (13. Nd2 { after To protect e5 } { [%cal Gd2c4,Gc4d6,Gc4b6,Gd2e4] } 13... Ng6 14. Nf3) 13... Nf5 { It looks more logical to attack White's weak Pawn. King safety - pawns around
the king. Want the opponent to move their pawns around the king to create
weaknesses that we can attack } (13... Ng6 14. Bh5 (14. c4 Ngxe5) 14... Rf5 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. c4 Nxe5 { Seems okay for Black } 17. g4 fxg3 18. Nxg3 Nxc4 19. Nxf5 gxf5 20. Rc1 Nxd6 21. Qxd6 Ba7 22. Rc3 b5 { And Black is happy. }) (13... Bc7 14. Bxc7 Qxc7 15. Qd6 (15. Nd6 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gd6c8,Gd6f7] }) 15... Qxd6 16. exd6 Nf5 { Is there an advantage for White? }) 14. Bh5 g6 (14... Nxd6! 15. Nxd6 Rf8 { The pawn e5 remains a target. } 16. Qe2 Qg5 17. Rad1 (17. Rfe1 Qh4) 17... Nxe5) 15. Bg4 { Creating gaps in
Black's position If you are in a worse/bad position, your best chance is to
try to create threats - try to counterattack and take the initiative from the
opponent } { [%csl Gg4,Gf3,Ge4,Gf6][%cal Ge2f3,Gg7g6,Gh5f7] } (15. Bf3! Nxd6 16. Nxd6 Rf8 (16... Nxe5 17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Qe2 $14) 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Nd2 Qg5 19. N2c4 Bc7 20. Re1 $16) 15... Ng7? { Not easy to understand } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7e8,Gg7e6,Gg7f5,Gg7h5] } (15... Nxd6 16. exd6 (16. Nxd6 Rf8 { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gd8g5,Gb6c7,Gb7b5] } 17. Qe2 Qg5 18. Rfe1 Nxe5? 19. Qxe5 Qxg4 20. f3 $14) 16... Ba7 17. Bf3 b6 18. Nd4 Bb7) 16. Qf3 { Black enters self-destruct mode We don't always need
a winning plan - sometimes the opponent will collapse, make more mistakes } { [%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2e5,Gg7e8,Ge8d6] } (16. Qe2) 16... h5? { Black lost access to the position } 17. Bh3 { Is
there a follow-up to the 1-move attack? } { [%cal Gh7h5] } 17... Qh4? { King + Queen vs. King mate - use both the king and queen to mate, using the
lone queen will not be enough } { [%csl Gh4,Gf6,Gg8][%cal Gg2g3] } (17... g5 { White to play (P) } { [%cal Gg5g4] } 18. Nf6+ { Ideally we want to meet the opponent's threat with a
threat of our own - keep control of the game } { [%cal Gf6h5,Gg8h8] } (18. g4) 18... Rxf6 19. exf6 Qxf6 { [%cal Gg5g4] } 20. g4 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf4g3,Gf3f6] }) 18. Nf6+ $18 Kh8 { Studying Morphy's games - looking for
the flashy way to win } { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gb3d2,Gd2e4,Gd2c4,Ga1e1] } 19. Qe4 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Ge4h7,Ge4g6] } (19. Qd3 Qg5 20. Nd2) (19. Nd2! Bd4 (19... Bd8 20. Qd3 Qg5 21. Nde4 $18) 20. Nc4 Nxe5 (20... b5 21. Na5) 21. Bxe5 Bxe5 22. Nxd7 $18) 19... Qg5 20. g3 { Open up the side of the board where you are stronger } { [%csl Gh8][%cal Gg2g3,Gg3f4] } 20... f3? { Loosing the pawn } (20... fxg3 21. fxg3 { If
your rooks lack a good open file, pawn exchange can often solve that problem
(pawn break) } { [%csl Gf4,Gf2][%cal Gf1f8,Gg2g3] } 21... Bd8 22. Ne8! $16 { f.e. } 22... Rxf1+ 23. Rxf1 Nf5 24. Bc5 b6 25. Nd6 Kg7 26. Bb4 Nxd6 27. Bxd6 Bb7 28. Bg2 Be7 29. Bxe7 Qxe7 30. Rf6 $16) 21. Nd2! $18 { Black has overlooked this pawn winning move } { [%csl Gg5,Gd2] } 21... Bd8 (21... Qxd2 22. Qxg6 $18 { Winning } { [%cal Gg6h7] } 22... Rxf6 23. exf6 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg6g7] }) 22. Nxf3 Qh6 23. Rg1 { Preparing Qe4-f4 Qxf4 gxf4 } { [%cal Gd8f6,Ge5f6,Gf7f6] } 23... Bxf6 (23... Nf5 24. Bxf5 gxf5 25. Qf4 Qxf4 26. gxf4 Bxf6 27. exf6 Rxf6 28. Rg5 { Winning }) 24. exf6 { Black has no real
dark-squared protection (bishop or pawns covering this colour complexes) } { [%csl Gd7,Ge6,Gg6,Gh5,Gb7,Ga6,Gc8] } 24... Ne8 (24... Rxf6 { Doesn't help } 25. Bf4 Qh7 26. Rad1 (26. Ng5 Qg8 { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gg3g4,Gg4h5] })) 25. Bf4 { [%cal Gh6h7,Gf3g5] } 25... Nxf6 { There is nothing better
White to play (P) Tactic - where several pieces are hanging, more likely to be
some trick (looking for the forcing moves) } 26. Qxc6! { Desperado } { [%cal Gf4h6,Gf6e4] } (26. Ng5 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gf3g5,Gf6e4,Gg5f7] } 26... Qxg5! { [%cal Gf4g5] } 27. Bxg5 Nxe4) (26. Ne5 { [%cal Ge5f7] } 26... Nxe5 27. Qxe5 { [%csl Gf4,Gh3] } 27... Qg7 { [%csl Gc8] } 28. Qe2 { [%cal Gf4e5,Ge5h8] }) 26... Qxf4 { Counter-Desperado } { [%cal Gg3f4,Gb7c6] } (26... bxc6 27. Bxh6 Ng8 { Move one piece
to defend the 2nd attacked piece } { [%cal Gg8h6,Gf7f3] } 28. Bf4) 27. Qxc8+! { [%cal Gc8h8,Gf4f3] } 27... Rxc8 28. gxf4 $18 Rxc2 29. Rac1 Rxf2 30. Rc8+ Ng8? { Collapsing } (30... Kh7 31. Ng5+) (30... Kg7 31. Ne5) 31. Ne5 Rg7 32. Nxg6+ Kh7 33. Nf8+ Kh6 34. Nxd7 Rxd7 35. Rcxg8 Rxf4 (35... Rdd2 36. Rh8#) 36. Bxe6 Re7 37. R8g6+ Kh7 38. Bg8+ Kh8 39. Rh6+ Rh7 40. Rxh7# { Time 5½ hours } 1-0


