{ [%evp 16,61,-8,-45,22,11,40,17,96,85,81,66,268,258,251,249,245,198,263,0,238,
77,387,385,377,360,812,811,865,862,818,695,744,606,1633,1661,1440,1633,1558,
1556,1453,1453,1232,1171,1556,1555,1350,1350] C51: Evans Gambit: Declined and
Accepted without 5...Ba5 Source: Tartakower & du Mont, 500 Master Games of
Chess, pp. 31-32. All comments are Tartakower's unless otherwise noted. The
following game demonstrates, more clearly than could mere words, the attacking
value of the open file. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 { In the hands of
Morphy this move, played in many games against strong amateurs, produced
dazzling results. His opponent here was a master of the first rank. 4.... } 4... Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O d6 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. d5 { Although this move, for the
time being, closes the Italian Diagonal, it has a disorganising effect on
Black's game. 9.... } 9... Ne5 (9... Na5 { , a frequent continuation being } 10. Bb2 Ne7 (10... Nxc4 11. Qa4+ { followed by Qxc4 }) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nc3 Ng6 { , and
there are breakers ahead for either side. }) 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Bb2 Qe7 { Guarding the e pawn with a counter-threat, eventually, of 12.Qh4. } (11... f6 12. Bxe5 (12. Kh1 Ne7 13. f4 { , with better chances. }) 12... fxe5 13. Qh5+ Kf8 14. Qxe5 Qf6 { , etc., is unsound. }) 12. Bb5+ (12. Qh5 Bd4) 12... Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Qg4+ { By the simplest
means White not only recovers his pawn, but wins one as well without giving up
his attack. 14.... } 14... f5 (14... Ke8 15. Qxg7 Qf6 16. Bxe5 { and wins. }) (14... Kd6 { (here or on the next move), then } 15. Nd2 { settles Black's fate. }) 15. Qxf5+ Ke8 16. Bxe5 (16. Qxe5 Qxe5 17. Bxe5 Kf7 { etc. }) 16... Nh6 (16... Nf6 { was
called for. }) 17. Qf4 Kd7 { Hoping to connect the rooks by this artificial
castling. } 18. Nd2 (18. Nc3 { , as Black wins a piece by } 18... Rae8) 18... Rae8 19. Nc4 $18 { Combining defence (of the bishop) with attack (20.d6 cxd6 21.Rad1,
etc.). 19.... } 19... Bc5 (19... Kc8 20. Rab1 { vivifies the attack. }) 20. Rad1 (20. Bxc7 Rhf8 (20... Qxe4 { because of } 21. Ne5+ Rxe5 22. Bxe5 { etc. }) 21. Qe5 (21. Qg3 Qxe4 22. Qxg7+ Nf7 { and the tables are turned }) 21... Ng4 22. Qxe7+ Rxe7 23. Bg3 Rxe4 { etc.-but he prefers not to relax his grip. }) 20... Bd6 21. Bxd6 cxd6 22. Rb1 { Here and on the following move White effects a lightning change
of target for his heavy artillery. 22.... } 22... b6 23. Rfc1 Qf6 24. Qe3 Ng4 (24... Rb8 25. e5) 25. Nxb6+ { A brilliant sacrifice, which is to be complemented by
an even more generous offer. 25.... } 25... axb6 26. Rc7+ Kd8 (26... Kxc7 27. Qxb6+ Kd7 28. Qa7+ { , followed by 29.Rb8#. }) 27. Qxb6 Qxf2+ 28. Qxf2 Nxf2 29. Ra7 { Recovering his piece, thanks to the threat 30.Rb8#, and maintaining two extra
pawns with a dominating position. 29.... } 29... Nh3+ 30. gxh3 Kc8 $18 31. Kf2 { and wins. } (31. Ra8+ { wins a rook. }) 1-0


