1. d4 e6 (1... d5 2. Nf3 c6 { is a good option against Thapa. Meet any bishop
moves with ...Qb6 just to get him thinking. }) 2. e4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nh6 6. Bd3 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gh6f5,Gd3f5,Ge6f5] } 6... f6 { After this game I dismissed this as dubious, preferring
instead the main move 6...cd4 7.cd4 Nf5, but interestingly Watson labels 6...
f6 'dynamic and effective' in his book! } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc1f4,Gg7g5,Gg5g4] } (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 f6 { will be my
preference for next time. }) 7. O-O! { I am surprised that this, the main move,
goes unmentioned by Watson. } 7... Nf7 8. Re1 fxe5?! { I don't like this move as
White's strong novelty seems to give him a slight but pleasant advantage. } (8... cxd4 9. cxd4 fxe5 10. dxe5 Bd7 { was the other possibility I was
considering, which should equalise: } { [%cal Ge8g8,Gf8e7] } 11. a3 Be7 12. b4 O-O 13. Nbd2 a5 14. b5 Na7 15. a4 Nc8 16. Qc2 h6 17. Ba3 Nb6 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. Qc7 Qd8 20. Rec1 Qxc7 21. Rxc7 Rab8 22. Nb3 Rfc8 23. Rac1 Rxc7 24. Rxc7 Bc8 25. Bg6 Nh8 26. Bd3 Nxa4 27. Nxa5 Nb6 28. h3 Na8 29. Rc2 Kf8 30. Nd4 Bd7 31. f4 Nf7 32. Kf2 Ke7 33. Ke3 Nd8 34. g4 Rc8 35. Rxc8 Bxc8 36. f5 Nb6 37. fxe6 Bxe6 38. Nxe6 Nxe6 39. Nxb7 Nd7 40. Bf5 Nxe5 41. Bxe6 Kxe6 42. Kd4 Nf3+ 43. Kc5 d4 44. Kc4 Ke5 45. Nc5 g6 46. Nb3 Ke4 47. Kc5 d3 48. b6 Ne5 49. Nd2+ Ke3 50. Kd6 Kxd2 51. b7 Ke2 52. b8=Q d2 53. Qb5+ Nd3 54. Qb1 d1=Q 55. Qxd1+ Kxd1 56. Ke7 Nf4 57. Kf6 g5 58. Kg7 Nxh3 59. Kxh6 Ke2 60. Kg6 Kf3 61. Kf5 Kg3 62. Ke4 Kxg4 63. Ke3 Kg3 { 0-1 Fioravanti,
E (2049)-Bastarelli,G (2104)/Porto Sant Elpidio 2005/EXT 2007 }) 9. Nxe5! Ncxe5 (9... Nfxe5 10. dxe5 { left my kingside
too weak, although Black has a playable position after } 10... g6 11. f4 Bg7 { . }) 10. dxe5 { [%csl Gf7,Gf8] } 10... c4 (10... Be7 11. c4 d4 12. Bf4 $14) (10... g6!? { somehow seemed too
risky during the game, but I am at a loss to explain why. } 11. c4 d4 12. Nd2 Bg7 13. f4 $14) 11. Bc2 Bc5 { Played to try and avoid the punch of White's f4
advance. Fortunately, I succeeded in this objective. } 12. Be3 (12. b4 cxb3 13. axb3 Bd7 $132) 12... Bxe3 13. Rxe3 $14 { White has quite a pleasant plus here. } 13... Qb6 (13... Bd7!? 14. Nd2 Qc7 15. Nf3 O-O-O) 14. b4 cxb3 15. axb3 Bd7 16. Qh5 (16. Nd2! Rc8 17. Nf3 { would have retained the edge. }) 16... g6 17. Qh4 Qd8! { Now I think that Black is okay. } 18. Qb4 b6 19. Nd2 Qe7 20. Qg4 (20. Qxe7+ Kxe7) 20... Qg5?! 21. Qe2 O-O 22. Nf3 Qf4 23. Rd1 (23. Nd4 { Rybka }) 23... Ng5 24. Nxg5?! Qxg5 25. Rg3 Qf4 { The exchange of White's great knight
for my passive knight relieves most of the pressure on Black's position - I
think the current position is equal. } 26. h3 (26. Rd4 Qc1+ 27. Rd1 Qf4) 26... Bb5! { Exploiting the overloaded queen to activate the bishop with tempo. } 27. Qe1 (27. Qe3 Qxe3 28. Rxe3 Rac8) 27... Kh8 28. Rd4 Qh6 29. Rdg4 Be8 30. Rg5 Rc8 31. Qe3 Rc7 32. f4 Qg7 33. Qf3 Qe7 34. Qg4 Qf7? { A bad move, but it
wins the game! Both players were in time-trouble at this point; he had 2
minutes to my 12. } { [%cal Gg3f3,Gg4h4,Gf7f4] } (34... Qc5+ 35. Kh2 Qf2 { would have given Black a clear
advantage. }) 35. Qh4?? (35. Rf3 { retained the balance. My opponent was now
claiming a win for White, and refused to concede that it is completely equal!
LOL }) 35... Qxf4 $19 36. Qh6 Qc1+ 37. Kh2 Rf1 { This is the resource my
overlooked, although other moves also win. Now White played a few more moves
before giving up: } 38. Rf3 Rxf3 39. gxf3 Qxc2+ 40. Rg2 (40. Kg3 Rg7) 40... Qf5 41. Qe3 Rf7 42. Kg3 Kg7 { White resigned. } 0-1


