1. e4 e6 { I played the Scandinavian in our previous encounter, but had
prepared the French for this game. } 2. d4 d5 { My strategy of playing the board,
not the girl was successful. In Ryde-Eastwood, I became very careless and
nearly paid for it. } 3. e5 c5 (3... b6 { is a playable surprise weapon for next
game. }) 4. c3 Nc6 (4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 { as recommended by McDonald is another
line in my repertoire. }) 5. Nf3 (5. Be3 Nh6 { occured in my previous Advance
French, and is good for Black. }) 5... Nh6 { I have played this a few times, and
still this line surprises my opponents. } 6. Bd3 { I had already faced this
against Thapa, and had an improvement ready. } 6... f6 7. Qe2?! { A new move; I
don't really trust this since the queen could be misplaced on e2, and castling
is stronger. } 7... Nf7 8. Bf4? { A suprising oversight by Emma; 8.0-0 was already
essential to retain equality. } 8... g5 $17 { White's centre is falling apart, and
already she cannot avoid material loss. } 9. Be3 fxe5? { Again I was careless,
although fortunately my position is still pretty good. } (9... g4 10. Nfd2 cxd4 11. cxd4 fxe5 { leaves Black a pawn up for nothing. } 12. Qxg4 exd4 13. Bxd4 e5 { [%csl Gd4] }) 10. Nxe5! Ncxe5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Bb5+ Nc6! (12... Bd7?! 13. Bd4! $14 { favours White. }) 13. Qh5+ Kd7 { At this stage Rybka prefers White and I prefer Black. Let's just say it's
unclear, for argument's sake. } 14. Bxg5 (14. Nd2 a6 15. Bxg5 Be7 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Bd3 Kc7 $15 { is better for Black. After ...e5, Black's king is in fact
safer. }) 14... Qe8 { The doubled pawns do not hassle Black because he achieves
a b-file for his rook and his c8-bishop becomes active on a6. } 15. Qh4 (15. Qxe8+ Kxe8 16. O-O Rg8 { does seem about equal, to be honest. } (16... Bd6!?)) 15... Bg7 (15... Qg6 { , my original intention, was probably better. }) 16. Nd2 $13 { Now the position is not so clear. } 16... a6! { The best move, stopping the
annoying pin. } 17. Bxc6+?! { This is tempting, but the Black king actually
turns out to be very well placed on c6. } 17... Kxc6 { Completing a very nice king
walk! Interestingly, I dubbed this 'the sexy king walk' after the game,
although I didn't tell anyone... } 18. Nb3?! { The knight is just misplaced
here. } (18. O-O-O $13 { is complicated - if Black gets his a8-rook in the game,
he will be better, but for now White has a lead in development. }) 18... b6 19. O-O-O (19. a4 a5 { is Rybka's preference, but the inclusion of a4 and a5
favours Black because ...Ba6 is now a strong possibility. }) 19... Qg6 { Now
Black is better as White does not have any targets to attack. } 20. g3?! { This merely weakens White's position. } 20... Rf8 (20... e5 { would have secured a
clear advantage. }) 21. Be3 Bd7! { Correctly completing development. Now I
didn't even see Emma's idea of Nc5, but fortunately Black retains the
advantage nonetheless. } 22. Nxc5? { Right idea, wrong execution. } (22. Bxc5! bxc5 23. Qe7 Rab8 24. Na5+ Kb6 25. Nc4+ Kc7 26. Qd6+ Kc8 27. f4 { would have
led to an extremely unclear position. She has only a pawn for the piece, but
Nb6 will regain some of the material and the queen is a large irritant. }) 22... bxc5 23. Qe7 (23. Qa4+ { was the alternative: } 23... Kd6 24. Bxc5+ Kxc5 25. Qxd7 { and here she probably saw that } 25... Rf7 { followed by Rf2 wins for Black. }) 23... d4! { A nice idea, intercepting the bishop and winning. } 24. cxd4 Rf5?! { A nice idea, but I overlooked a clean kill: } (24... Rf7 25. Qxc5+ Kb7 26. Qb4+ Bb5 { is decisive. }) 25. dxc5 Rd5 26. Rxd5 (26. Qh4 Rb8 { is also much better
for Black although White can continue fighting. }) 26... exd5 27. Rd1 Qf6 $19 { Now the rest is a matter of technique. Emma continued fighting but the game
was over very quickly: } 28. Qxf6+ Bxf6 29. a3 a5 30. Kc2 Rb8 31. b3 Bf5+ { Collecting the harvest. } 32. Kd2 Rxb3 33. Ke2 d4! { Finishing the game. } 34. Ke1 Bg4 { White resigned. Fortunately I made up for this slaughter by beating
up David and Sherab in bughouse ;). } 0-1


