for advancing with his king. } { [%csl Gf7,Gg6][%cal Gd3e5] }) 37. Kxc5 { [%cal Gc5b6,Gb6b7,Gc7c8,Gd7c8] } 37... Kc7 (37... h4 { leads to similar play. } 38. Kb6 Kc8 39. g3 hxg3 40. fxg3 f5 41. h4 g6 42. a4 Kb8 43. b4 Kc8 44. Ka7 Kc7 45. b5 a5 46. Ka8! $40) 38. h4 { [%csl Gc5,Gc7,Gb3,Ga2,Gh5,Gh4,Gg7,Gf7,Gg2,Gf2][%cal Gc7d7,Gc5d5,Gc5b6] } 38... Kd7 (38... b6+ 39. Kd5 Kd7 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gb3b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5,Gd5c6,Gf2f3,Gg2g4] } 40. f3 Kc7 41. g4 hxg4 42. fxg4 Kd7 43. b4!? { White can afford not to be in a hurry. Before
starting advancing the kingside pawns he can bring his queenside pawns closer
to promoting. } 43... Kc7 44. a3 Kd7 45. a4 Kc7 46. h5 Kd7 47. g5 Ke7 48. Kc6 $18) 39. Kb6 Kc8 40. b4 Kb8 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4] } 41. f3 { Before deciding how to advance the a-pawn, it is
useful to provoke the freeing of the kingside. Other moves win, too, but the
way chosen by Gledura is the simplest from a practical point of view. } 41... Kc8 42. g4 hxg4 43. fxg4 Kb8 { [%cal Gg4g5,Gg7g6] } 44. h5 { [%cal Gg4g5,Gh5h6] } 44... f6 { [%csl Gg7] } 45. a4 { With the king on
c8 the winning move would be 45.a3, forcing a transposition to the game. } 45... Kc8 46. Ka7 { [%csl Ga7] } 46... Kc7 { White to play (P) } { [%csl Ga7,Gc7,Gc8,Gc6][%cal Ga4a5] } 47. b5 (47. a5 Kc6 48. Kb8 b5) 47... a5 (47... axb5 { [%csl Gb5] } 48. axb5 b6 (48... Kc8 49. b6 { [%cal Gb7c7] }) 49. Ka6 { [%cal Ga6b6] }) 48. Ka8! { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%cal Gb7b6,Ga8a7] } (48. Kb6 Kb8 $18) 48... b6 49. Ka7 1-0


