[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[FEN "1r1b3r/1P1bkpp1/R2p4/3Pp2p/1p6/1N5P/1PP1BPP1/3R2K1 w - - 0 23"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ While from an Australian point of view, Anton Smirnov's 23...Bxf3? against
Karjakin may be the most significant moment of the World Cup, for the rest of
the world the diagrammed position was a sliding doors moment. Had Anand played
quietly from the position, he would probably have beaten his bare-legged,
Canadian opponent. Then the world would have been spared the explosion the
next round, when Kovalyov forfeited his third round and returned home after
being abused and insulted just before his game by tournament organiser Zurab
Azmaiparashvili for not observing an imaginary dress code. }
23. Nc5? { An inspired positional piece sacrifice, but unfortunately for Anand it is
insufficient. Instead after the simple } (23. Rda1 Rxb7 24. Ra8 { White would
have a safe and serious advantage. }) 23... dxc5 24. d6+ Kf6 25. Bf3 Kf5! { The move Anand underestimated. Black not only threatens to cut off the f3
bishop with 26...e4 but also provides useful squares for the d8 bishop. } 26. Bd5 e4 27. Re1 Bf6! 28. Bxe4+ Kg5 29. Ra5 Bxb2 30. Rxc5+ Kf6 { Now the Black
king is surprisingly safe and Black can begin to lay siege to the d6 pawn. } 31. Re3 g6 32. Rf3+ Ke6! 33. Rd3 Rhd8 34. Ra5 f5 35. Bf3 (35. Bd5+ Kxd6 { offers
White no useful discovered check. }) 35... Bc3 36. h4 Kf6 37. g3 f4! 38. Be4 Bf5! 39. Bxf5 gxf5 40. Rb5 Ke6 41. Kf1 Rd7 42. gxf4 Rbxb7 43. Re3+ Kf6 { After beating Anand, Kovalyov shocked an interviewer by saying, “To tell you
the truth, I do not really want to stay here for long, because school is more
important to me, but if you have to, then you have to." With his pre-game rant
Azmaiparashvili solved Kovalyov's dilemma for him and, as usual for senior
FIDE officials, Azmaiparashvili escaped sanction when his behaviour was
brought before world body's Ethics Commission. } 0-1


