1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 b5 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 Qb6 12. Nf3!? { Usually White takes
on c6 but I believe it is very interesting to keep more minor pieces on the
board. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4f5,Gg2g3,Gf1h3,Gh3e6,Ge6e5] } 12... Qc5?! { While preparing I was thinking Black should first push ...b4
in order to avoid e5-Ne4 ideas, but when my opponent played 12...Qc5 after
some 5 minutes, I thought it may be some preparation and I should reconsider
13.e5. I thought for almost an hour (!) and became completely unobjective. I
evaluated some +/- positions as unclear and decided to go for 13.f5, which is
not that bad but deserves a question mark since it is nonsense to go wrong on
the first move I have to play by myself! } 13. f5? (13. e5! fxe5 (13... f5 14. exd6 (14. g4!? { seems interesting but after } 14... b4 15. Ne2 fxg4 16. Ng5 Qd5! 17. Qxd5 exd5 18. Rxd5 dxe5 19. fxe5 Bg7 20. Bg2 Rd8 { it seems like the
position is rather unclear. }) 14... Bg7 15. h3 { is just very good for White:
it is a question where the Black king will go and g4 will come very soon. }) 14. fxe5! (14. Ne4 Qb4 $132) 14... Nxe5 15. Ne4 Nxf3 16. gxf3 Qc7 (16... Qe5 17. f4 Qxe4 18. Bg2 $16) 17. Qd4 e5 18. Nf6+ Kd8 { and here I was calculating some
forced lines, with Qh4 or Qd5, and simply didn't realise that after a simple
move like } 19. Qd2 { my compensations for the pawn are simply awesome. }) 13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 (14... fxe5 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Qg5 $40) 15. Bd3 { Now that the
knights have finally been exchanged, the position is very similar to the main
line: the only difference is that the black queen is on e5 instead of c5, and
the black light-squared bishop is on d7 instead of c6. } 15... b4 (15... h5 16. Qf2 { followed by Ne2 is easier for White. }) 16. Ne2 a5 17. Bc4! { This move is
precisely the reason why I think the position after 15.Bd3 is anyway an
improvement compared to the main line. White is supposed to be better once the
bishop can reach this diagonal, since it is protecting the white king but also
putting pressure on the e6-pawn. } 17... Rc8 (17... Qxe4? 18. fxe6 fxe6 19. Nd4 { is killing. }) 18. b3 (18. Ba6!? { followed by Qd3 and Nd4 also makes sense. }) 18... a4 19. Nd4 axb3?! (19... a3 { seemed to me like the only move (at least
to prevent my knight from moving) but after } 20. g4!? { (in order to avoid ...
h5 and ...Bh6) I think White is better, e.g. } 20... h5 21. gxh5 Rxh5 22. h4 $40 { It will take White some time to solve the problems of the b2-square but in the
long-term Black has no plan. }) 20. Bxb3 { Now my bishop has reached its perfect
square. } 20... Be7 (20... h5 21. Rhf1 $40) 21. Rhe1 (21. Qh6!?) 21... Rc3 22. Qh6 Bf8 23. Qh4 { [%cal Ge6e5] } (23. Qh5! { simply wins: } 23... Ke7 (23... Rg8 24. Re2 { does not help
Black. }) 24. Nf3 (24. Re2!? { is even stronger according to Houdini. }) 24... Qf4 (24... Qb5 25. e5 $18) 25. e5! Qxf5 26. exd6+ Kd8 27. Qh4 $18) 23... Be7 (23... Rg8 24. Rd2 $16) 24. Qh6 Bf8 25. Qh4 Be7 26. Qg4 h5 (26... Kf8 { but after } 27. Qh5! { White is much better. } (27. fxe6 Rg8! { is not entirely clear. })) 27. Qg7 Rf8 28. Qh7 Kd8 29. Qxh5 Qc5 30. Qh6 (30. Qg4!?) 30... e5 31. Ne2 Re3 32. Nc1! { After this precise move
Black has no compensations at all for the pawn. } 32... Rxe1 33. Rxe1 Bb5 34. Qd2 Rh8 35. h3 Bf8 36. Nd3 Bxd3 (36... Bh6 { to be the only move, but
after } 37. Qxh6 Rxh6 38. Nxc5 dxc5 39. Bxf7 Rh4 40. Bd5 Rf4 41. g4 { White is
totally winning (especially since ...c4 will be met by Kb2 and Black has no
stay to stick the White king on b1. }) 37. Qxd3 Bh6 38. Bxf7 Ke7 39. Bb3 Rc8 40. Qe2 Qc3 41. Rd1 Qe3 42. Qh5 Rf8 43. Qg6 (43. h4 { followed by Qg6 is the
"tactical" win. }) 43... Qg5 44. h4 Qxg6 45. fxg6 Bg7 46. g4 Rh8 47. h5 Rc8 48. Rf1 Rc7 49. Kc1 Bh6+ 50. Kd1 Bg7 51. Ke2 Bh6 52. Rf5 Bg7 (52... Rd7 53. g5 fxg5 54. Kf3 $18) 53. g5 fxg5 54. Rf7+ Kd8 55. Rxg7! Rxg7 56. Bf7 Rxf7 57. h6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


