{ What You'll Face in Your Own Games Most Often (vs. what is happening at GM level) }
1. e4 { [%cal Gc7c5,Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 (3... Bc5 4. O-O (4. c3 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 4... Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 { Ready for lines that score well } { [%cal Gf6e4,Gf6g4,Gd8e7,Gd7d5] }) 4... Nf6 5. d4 { Very well for White in Lichess games (2000 and below) } 5... exd4 (5... Nxd4 6. Nxe5 O-O 7. Be3 { - Black can't avoid losing a pawn } { [%cal Ge3c5] } 7... Ne6 8. Bxe6 { [%csl Gf7] } 8... Bxe3 { [%cal Ge6f7] } 9. Bxf7+ { [%cal Gf8f7,Ge5f7,Gf2e3] }) (5... Bxd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. f4 d6 (7... Nc6 { Looks safe, but White actually has a tactic (White to play P) } 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. fxe5 Nxe5 10. Qd5+ Kf8 11. Qxe5 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gb1c3] }) 8. fxe5 dxe5 9. Bg5 { [%cal Gd8e7,Gc8e6,Ge8c8] } 9... Be6 10. Na3 { [%cal Gc2c3] }) 6. e5 { Check inferior moves with the Stockfish engine on Lichess } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gf6g4,Gf6e4,Gf6g8] } 6... d5 7. exf6 dxc4 8. fxg7 Rg8 9. Bg5! { Smerdon - repertoire is based on these principles (finding lines that are difficult to play against OTB) }) 4. d3 Bc5 5. O-O { [%cal Gh7h6,Gc1g5] } 5... d6 6. c3 { At club level, often the most common move isn't the best one - certain art to finding the systems with the best 'strike rate' } { [%cal Ga7a6,Gc5a7] } 6... Bg4?! 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Re1 h6 9. b4 { [%cal Ga2a4] } 9... Bb6 10. a4 { [%cal Gc5a7] } 10... a6 11. Nf1 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g3,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] } (11. h3 { [%csl Gg4] } 11... Bh5 (11... Bd7 12. Bb3 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd2c4,Gc1e3,Gb4b5] }) 12. Nf1 { [%csl Gh5,Gg6][%cal Gf1g3,Gg3h5,Gg4c8] } 12... Bg6 13. Ng3 { [%csl Ge4,Gd3,Gg6][%cal Gd6d5,Ge4d5] }) *


