1. e4 e6 { Tan Zhongyi remains faithful to her French Defence. } 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 { No more Rubinstein today! } (3... Bb4) 4. e5 (4. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8] }) 4... Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 { Steinitz Setup } 7... Be7 (7... a6 8. Qd2 b5 { Which side do you think White wants to castle on? } { [%csl Gb5] } 9. Be2 { [%cal Ge1g1] } 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 { [%cal Gb5b4] }) (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O { [%cal Gd4c5,Gc5d4] }) 8. Qd2 { This is one of the best known headaches for Black in this line! } 8... O-O { If you're ever Black against Gene Nakauchi - this is how to beat him } { [%csl Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gd4c5] } (8... a6 9. a3 O-O 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Qf2 Nd7 $146 { An interesting novelty worthy of thorough investigation. } 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 f6 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bxf6?! { I am not sure about this move
but it is not easy to assess it with one look at the board. } 15... Qxf6 16. g3 g5 17. O-O-O gxf4 18. Kb1 f3 19. g4 Ne5 20. g5 Qg7 21. g6 hxg6 22. Bd3 Bd7 23. Rdg1 Nxd3 24. cxd3 Rf5 25. Rg4 Raf8 26. Rhg1 Be8 27. Nd1 Rh5 28. h4 Re5 29. Ne3 Bb5 30. Rd4 Re4 31. Rxg6 Bxd3+ { 0-1 (31) Karjakin,S (2785)-Adhiban,B (2653) Wijk
aan Zee 2017 }) 9. dxc5 { [%cal Gd4c5,Ge1c1] } (9. O-O-O? c4! { [%csl Gc1] } 10. f5 b5 { [%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b1,Gc3b5,Gb5b4] } 11. Nxb5 Rb8 12. Nd6 Bxd6 13. exd6 Nf6 { Because of c4-pawn - White can't defend his king easily } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gf6e4,Gd8d6,Gc4c3] }) 9... Bxc5 10. O-O-O Qa5 { White wants to attack on kingside (Bd3/h4) } 11. a3 { Blacks' opening preparation was faulty } { [%cal Gc5b4,Gb4c3] } 11... Be7?! { Despite Sadorra's
victory against Wesley So and Nepomniachtchi's against Shomoev, I consider
this move a serious inaccuracy. } { [%csl Gc5,Ge7] } (11... a6 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] }) 12. Bd3?! { Could have been met with 12..
.Nc5. } { If you can prepare a Greek Gift, Black is often in real trouble } { [%cal Gd7c5,Gc5d3] } (12. h4 { appeals more to me. } 12... a6 13. Bd3 { and similar to the game the
threat of Bh7 is devastating. }) 12... a6?! (12... Nc5 { should have given
Black enough means to maintain dynamic equality. }) 13. h4 { Now the threat of
Bxh7 is imminent. } 13... b5?? { This loses by force. It is strange that Tan Zhongyi
was not aware of this 'Greek gift' sacrifice. All of these moves and the
sacrifice have actually been played before! } { [%csl Gh7] } (13... f6 { good or bad should
have been played. }) (13... h6 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gg4g5] } 14. g4 { h6-hook } { [%csl Gh6][%cal Gg4g5] }) 14. Bxh7+! { The Greek gift in the final of the women's
world chess championship! } 14... Kxh7 { [%cal Gf3g5] } 15. Qd3+! { The strongest according to
Houdini and colleagues! } 15... Kg8 16. Ng5 f5 { White to play (P) - how does White continue the attack? } (16... Bxg5 17. hxg5 { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gd3h7,Gd3h3,Gf8d8] } 17... Rd8 (17... g6 18. Bc5 { [%cal Gd3h3,Gh3h8] }) 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. f5 exf5 20. Nxd5 { leads to inevitable mate. }) 17. Nxd5! { Anna knows the
details to a T! } (17. Qe2! { Qh5 } { [%cal Ge2h5,Gd3e2] } 17... Bxg5 (17... g6 18. Nxe6 { White has too many attacking ideas } { [%cal Gc3d5,Gh4h5] }) 18. hxg5 { [%cal Gh1h8] } 18... g6 (18... Kf7 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. e6+ { [%cal Ge3b6] } 20... Ke7 21. exd7 Kxd7 22. Rxd5+ Kc7 { [%cal Gh2h7,Ge3c5] } 23. Bc5 { [%csl Gc8,Ga8] }) 19. Qf3 Ne7 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Rxd5 Kf7 22. Rdd1 { 1-0 (22) Zaas,P (2224)-Greig,S (2164) ICCF email 2014 }) 17... b4 18. Nxe7+ Nxe7 { [%csl Ge7,Ge6,Gg8][%cal Gd3d6,Gd6e6,Ge3d2] } 19. Bd2? (19. Qd6! bxa3 20. bxa3 { and the rest is
easy! }) 19... Rb8? (19... Nd5 20. Qf3 Ra7! 21. Qh5 N7f6 22. exf6 gxf6 $13) 20. Qd6 { Anna is winning, the rest is just a vain struggle by Tan to save the
game but the game was over long before she signed the scoresheets! } 20... Qc5 21. Bxb4 Qxd6 22. Bxd6 Ng6 23. Nxe6 Re8 24. Bxb8 Rxe6 25. g3 Bb7 26. Rh2 Nc5 27. Rd8+ Kh7 28. Bd6 Ne4 29. h5 Nh8 30. h6 Nf7 31. Rd7 Rxd6 32. Rxf7 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


