{ In this week's post I'll survey a simple but in my view quite annoying
antidote to the Winawer French. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 { The starting
position of the Winawer. } (3... dxe4) (3... Nf6 { . If you want something unorthodox I
can suggest } 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Qh5 { as a dangerous weapon. }) 4. exd5 (4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 { is the main line, but after } 6... Ne7 { , any moves other than } 7. Qg4 { fail to fight for an advantage, and then } 7... Qc7 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 { has been ultimately analysed to a draw by repetition. }) 4... exd5 (4... Qxd5 { is known to favour White after } 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bd3 b6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 Bb7 { because of his bishop pair and central control. }) 5. Bd3 { White's subsequent
setup depends on how Black plays - he has a lot of options here, but I think
White can fight for an edge or at least get a very interesting strategic
struggle after each of them. Now let's see some games. } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gc1f4,Gd1f3] } *


