{ I'll wrap up this post with a closer look at my 6.Bf4 suggestion. If you want
to examine this Anti-Winawer in more detail, I advise you to check out http://
www.chesspub.com/cgi-bin/yabb2/YaBB.pl?num=1391619848/0, which is an
interesting and quite involved discussion. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bd3 c6 6. Bf4 (6. Ne2 { was hotly debated on the
aforementioned thread. Personally, I like Korchnoi's fresher approach. }) 6... Ne7 (6... Nf6 { is the other placement for the knight, and definitely more
logical as there's no longer a Bg5 pin. Perhaps White should go for } 7. Ne2 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Ng3 { , though in all fairness Black can't be objectively
worse here after } 9... Bd6 10. Qd2 Bxf4 11. Qxf4 Be6 { and ...Nbd7. }) 7. Qh5 (7. Qf3 O-O 8. Ne2 Bf5 9. O-O-O Bxd3 10. Rxd3 { with attacking chances on the kingside
and the easier game is better. }) 7... Nd7 (7... Ng6 { should be fine for Black
after say } 8. Bg5 Qd6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O h6 11. Bd2 Nd7 { followed by ...Nf6. }) 8. Bg5 { Now it's too late for Black to play ...Ng6, and White has a good game. } 8... h6 9. Nf3 Rg8 (9... O-O 10. O-O { is naturally a bit better for White. }) 10. O-O { This is just crazy. } (10. Bf4 { with a big advantage was obvious and good. }) 10... hxg5 11. Nxg5 g6 (11... Rf8 12. Ne6 Nf6 13. Nxg7+ Kd7 { was the simplest
way to obtain a winning position. }) 12. Qh7 Nf8 13. Qxf7+ Kd7 14. Rae1 { Now White is just winning. } 14... Kc7 15. Re2 (15. Re5 Bd7 16. Rfe1 { is crushing. } 16... Nf5 17. Bxf5) 15... Bd7 16. f4 (16. Rfe1 Nf5 17. Qxg8 Qxg5 { is the key
difference. }) 16... Rh8 17. Rfe1 Nf5 18. Bxf5 gxf5 19. Qg7 Rh5 20. Nf7 Qh4 (20... Qb8 { was the correct defence - instead Black gets smashed. }) 21. g3 Qg4 22. Qe5+ Kb6 23. a3 (23. Na4+ { is decisive, e.g. } 23... Kb5 24. Qc7 Bxe1 25. Qxb7+ Kxa4 26. Rxe1 { and mate will soon follow. }) 23... Re8 24. Nxd5+ cxd5 25. Qf6+ Bc6 26. Rxe8 Bxe1 27. Rxe1 Nd7 28. Qd8+ Ka6 29. b4 Nb6 30. Ng5 { White has at
last consolidated and now it's a matter of technique. } 30... Rh6 31. Qf8 Rg6 32. Qc5 Nc4 33. Ne6 Rxe6 34. Rxe6 Qd1+ 35. Kg2 Qxc2+ 36. Kh3 Qa4 37. Kh4 Nd2 38. Qxd5 Qb5 39. Qxb5+ Kxb5 40. Re5+ Kc4 41. Rxf5 Nf3+ 42. Kh5 Nxh2 43. g4 Bf3 44. Rg5 Kxd4 45. Kh4 Ke4 46. f5 Bd1 47. Rg7 Ke5 48. Kh3 Nxg4 49. Rxg4 Bc2 50. Rg5 Bxf5+ 51. Kg3 Kf6 52. Kf4 Bd7 53. Re5 Bc6 54. Ra5 a6 55. Re5 b6 56. Re2 a5 57. Re5 axb4 58. axb4 Bg2 59. Rb5 Ke6 60. Ke3 Bf1 61. Rxb6+ Ke5 62. Rc6 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


[Event "1.e4 for Beginners (White Repertoire):"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/study/osV"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C15"]
[Opening "French Defense: Winawer Variation, Delayed Exchange Variation"]
[StudyName "Craze's Study"]
[ChapterName "Chapter 30"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/sf9IbZGs/sr3vX2N7"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. e4 { I have clumped the Caro-Kann (1...c6) and French (1...e6) Defenses
together, as in both cases Black is following up with ...d5, building a
light-squared centre. To keep it simple, we are playing the same 2nd and 3rd
moves in both cases. } 1... e6 (1... c6 2. d4 d5 { Black's development is slower
compared to the French, but he can easily activate his light squared bishop. } 3. Nc3 { Black should exchange on e4, since compared to the French he can't
easily increase the pressure on our e4-pawn, plus he wants to develop his
c8-bishop actively (unlike the French) and can't do that easily otherwise. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { You won't face the Caro-Kann much at lower levels, plus the play
is more slow in nature, so I'll just give a few ideas. Note that we will see a
similar structure in the French (when Black takes on e4). } 4... Bf5 { Developing
with tempo is generally a decent idea :) } (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ { is a favourable
exchange for White as either recapture leaves Black with doubled pawns. We can
then develop our kingside pieces for a small edge, but one tip is that we
should play c3 after either recapture: } 5... exf6 6. c3 { We will follow with Bd3
and Ne2 for a small edge - that way, if they pin our knight with ...Bg4, we
can, in the worst case, break the pin with f3. }) (4... Nd7 { This move prepares
...Ngf6 so that Black can recapture with a piece (avoiding doubled pawns).
However, White can be tricky with } 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Ng5 { avoiding the exchange
and eyeing that vulnerable f7-pawn. } 6... e6 (6... h6?! { doesn't actually force
our knight back! } 7. Ne6! fxe6 8. Bg6# { is a nice tactic that could win you
a game or two! }) 7. N1f3 { We will develop with Qe2 and 0-0, with a good
version of a French Defence, because we have more space and their bishop on c8
is quite passive. If you wish to research this more deeply, a good starting
point is to play through the Deep Blue vs. Garry Kasparov game in the next
chapter. }) 5. Ng3 { Our play over the next several moves should be targeted
against the opponent's light-squared bishop, as this piece is on a very strong
diagonal. } 5... Bg6 6. h4! { We threaten to win their bishop with h4-h5. } 6... h6 7. Nf3 { Now we are ready to attack their bishop with Ne5, activating our knight with
tempo. } 7... Nd7 { Now if Ne5 they will just take it, so we should hit their
g6-bishop in the other way. } 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 { Now we will
follow up with Bd2 and 0-0-0, since with our pawn on h5, the king would be a
bit exposed on the kingside. (In general, you want to have three pawns
covering your king after you castle) } 10... e6 11. Bd2 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 { For 95%
of players it would be fine to stop here, but I'll just add that if Black
castles kingside, hacking their king with Ne4 and g4-g5 tends to work well, e.
g. } 13. Kb1 O-O 14. Ne4 $40 { and we're ready to attack their king with the g4
gambit, since taking the pawn with ...Nxg4 tends to run into a strong g-file
attack after a subsequent Rhg1. }) 2. d4 d5! { Other moves give White too much
of a free hand in the centre. } 3. Nc3! { It's true that we could also place
our knight on d2 against the Caro-Kann and French, but this is the most
obvious square for our knight. Now Black has three major options, which lead
to quite different positions. } (3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Bg5 { is a playable choice if you really hate the closed positions arising
from 3.Nc3, but you don't give Black many chances to go wrong, which is why
most good players defend their e4-pawn with the knight on move 3. }) 3... Bb4!? { Pinning our knight leads to the most unbalanced positions, but I think you
will face 3...Nf6 slightly more often. } (3... Nc6 { or other weird 3rd moves
tend to be well met by keeping the tension with Nf3/Bd3/0-0, such as with } 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3! { and Black is unable to challenge our centre with ...c5,
which we'll see is a very important break in the French Defence. } (5. e5 Ne4 { is also possible, but I'd prefer to not let their knight reach the nice
e4-square. })) (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { We saw a similar structure in the Caro-Kann,
but here their options are limited as ...Bf5 is no longer legal. } 4... Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Bd3 { This setup works well against just about anything Black tries.
The position is quiet so you don't need to remember much, but I'll show one
way to get the pieces out: } 6... c5 7. O-O Nxe4 8. Bxe4 Nf6 9. Bd3 cxd4 10. Nxd4! $14 { and Black can't take our knight on d4, as then Bb5+! discovers an attack
on Black's queen. This is a very common pawn structure which you'll need to
learn deeply at some point in your chess career, but for the time being a
setup with c3/Qe2/Bg5(f4) and placing your rooks in the centre will get you by. }) (3... Nf6 { As a rule of thumb, if Black plays ...Nf6, e5 is usually the
best response. } 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4! { Often at the club level I see people
playing 5.Nf3, but this is important to remember, as whenever we play e5,
Black wants to destroy our centre with ...c5, ...Nc6 and ...cxd4 (possibly ...
Qb6 first). So we defend our e5-pawn with two pawns, then focus on covering
the d4-square with our pieces. } 5... c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 { Now we will castle
queenside or kingside, depending on the opponent's reply. As a rule of thumb
we will castle queenside unless they are getting a quick attack on our king
with ...b4 or ...c4. } 7... a6 (7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 { suits White, whose knight
occupies the d4-outpost. Now advanced players will want to commit the sharp 8..
.Qb6 variation to memory, otherwise } 8... Bc5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O a6 11. Qf2! { gives White a bit of an edge, as we have a space advantage, and for that
reason our kingside attack with h4-h5, Bd3 and so forth tends to be more
effective than Black's respective flank attack with ...b5-b4 (which still
requires some preparation). Most players won't need to remember subtleties
like 11.Qf2, but I've included a model game by Fabiano Caruana in case you
aren't comfortable in opposite-side castling positions. }) (7... Be7!? { As a rule of thumb, if Black develops their kingside, we should castle
kingside ourselves. } 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O $10 { White is by no means better by
force, but he can play Qd2, Nd1 and c3 to build a nice pawn chain to work with. }) (7... Qb6 { looks annoying, but we can cover the b2-pawn with } 8. Na4 Qa5+ 9. c3 $14 { , when 9...cxd4 10.b4 gets very sharp but favours White with best play. }) 8. Qd2 b5 { Here Black's three pawns abreast on the 5th rank are quite
imposing and give him a few options, so I recommend exchanging on c5
voluntarily, even though it helps Black develop his bishop with tempo. } 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bd3! { It looks like we are blundering a piece to ...d4, but that is
not the case: } 10... d4?! 11. Nxd4! Nxd4 (11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxd4 13. Be4 $14 { immediately regains the material with interest, as both d4 and a8 are under
attack. }) 12. Ne4 { and surprisingly Black is unable to keep his extra piece,
as ...Bb6 runs into a familiar Nd6 and Be4 discovered attack to regain the
material (this is the key detail to remember). And if } 12... Qb6 (12... O-O?! { fails to a discovered attack at the end of the exchanges. } 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Bxd4 Qxd4 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qxd4) 13. Nxc5 Qxc5? 14. c3 { We win the
d4-knight thanks to the pin, and after } 14... Qc7 15. Bxd4 $18 { White is a pawn up
with a winning position. Granted, we are not forced to enter such tactics, but
they are quite fun to analyse and there's no reason to avoid the tactics when
they work in our favour. }) 4. exd5!? { This is one of the few cases in the
repertoire where I'll suggest a move I don't consider to be the strongest, as
the positions after the main line 4.e5 require a lot of strategic
understanding and a good memory. } (4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 { is the
Winawer main line, where White has the bishop pair but Black's structure is
superior due to the doubled c-pawns. White does seem to be in good shape with
the aggressive } 7. Qg4! $14 { , but this is very sharp, requires a lot of
knowledge and allows Black to choose the nature and type of position. }) 4... exd5 (4... Qxd5 { just gives White a nice space advantage after } 5. Nf3 $14 { followed by normal development. }) 5. Bd3 { As promised in the introduction,
we'll be developing our kingside pieces quickly. One tip is that our knight
will be more flexible on e2 than f3, to nullify ...Bg4 pins. } 5... Nf6! { In
general, when the e-file opens up, the first priority of both players is to
get castled. } (5... c5?! { might look scary at first, but here we can see
another typical chess trick for dealing with a pin: } 6. dxc5 d4 { Aren't we
just losing the c3-knight to the pin? No, we can harass the pinning bishop :) } 7. a3 Ba5 8. b4! { This pivotal unpinning move is made possible by the
inclusion of a3/Ba5. } 8... dxc3 9. bxa5 Qxa5 10. Be3 $14 { and the position looks a
bit strange, but by considering both sides advantages, we'll realise that
White's bishop pair and faster development in an open position outweigh the
doubled c-pawns. } (10. Rb1!? { sacking the c5-pawn is even better to the
computer, but this isn't so important to remember. })) (5... Nc6 { is
historically the most common move, but it allows us } 6. a3! { to put the
question to their bishop. Retreating to e7 would leave Black a tempo down in a
symmetrical structure, so he usually doubles White's pawns: } 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nge7 { Now if Black can play ...Bf5, he will trade the light-squared bishops and we
will lose our bishop pair advantage. Therefore, we should fight against this
move: } 8. Qf3! { If Black plays slowly, often we can play Qf3 before Nge2 for
a more aggressive setup. } 8... Be6 9. Ne2 Qd7 10. Ng3 $14 { I feel White has a small
edge after 0-0 because of his bishop pair advantage. However, Black will count
on his healthier pawn structure to maintain a playable position. }) 6. Ne2 O-O 7. O-O { White has completed his basic setup, and now Black has the problem of
activating his c8-bishop, as ...Bg4 is well met by f3, but f5 is unavailable
and the bishop looks quite passive on e6. That doesn't automatically give
White an advantage, but he can claim his position is a little more pleasant.
I'll give a couple of continuations to show how White might place his pieces
in this structure. } 7... c6 (7... Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 9. Nf4 { lets White win the bishop
pair once again. }) 8. Ng3 { This is my recommendation, intending to bring our
knight to f5 at some point. } (8. Bg5 { is another way to get the pieces out. It
was recently played by Anand, as you can find in the Vishy Anand vs. Fabiano
Caruana game, but I prefer 8.Ng3. }) 8... Re8 9. h3! { The idea of this pawn
move is to prepare Qf3 without running into ...Bg4 with tempo. } (9. Nce2 { and c3/Qc2/Bf4/Nf5 in some order is another way to play the position. }) 9... Nbd7 { It's hard to see where else this knight is heading. } 10. Qf3 Nf8 $10 { I can't claim that White has any advantage, but he has a few plans to choose
from. I like } 11. Nce2 $10 { with ideas of Bg5 (or Bf4 if they anticipated Bg5),
with a balanced middlegame. } *


