1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bd3 Nf6 (5... Nc6 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nge7 8. Qf3 Be6 9. Nh3 Qd7 10. Ng5 O-O-O?! (10... Bf5! 11. g4?! { Kamran always has his own chess style. } 11... Bg6 12. h4 f6 13. Nh3 h5 14. gxh5 Bxh5 15. Qg2 O-O-O $15 { Shirazi,K (2403) -Vareille,F (2418) France 1999 0-1 (56) }) 11. O-O Rdf8 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Qe2 Nf5 14. a4 $14 { Vachier Lagrave,M (2788)
-Caruana,F (2795)chess.com INT 2016 1-0 (57). I don't think that Fabiano was
satisfied with his position. So he prepared another line. }) 6. Ne2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Bg5 (8. h3 Re8 9. Ng3 Nbd7 10. Qf3 (10. a3 Bd6 11. Qf3 (11. Nf5 Bc7 12. Qf3 Nf8 13. Bg5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Qd6 15. g3 h6 16. Be3 (16. Bf4 Qd8 17. Bxc7 Qxc7 18. Kg2 Re7) 16... Re7 17. Bf4 Qd8 18. Bd2 Ne6 19. Bxe6 Rxe6 20. Rfe1 { Medvegy,
Z (2474)-Hoang,T (2470) Budapest 2005 1/2 (26) }) 11... Nf8 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Rfe1 Ne6 14. Be3 g6 15. Nce2 Bf8 16. c3 Bg7 17. Nf4 Ng5 18. Qd1 Bd7 19. Nfe2 Nge4 20. Bf4 Qb6 { Andriasian,Z (2594)-Kovalenko,I (2680) Al-Ain UAE 2015 1/2 (53) }) 10... Nf8 11. Nce2 Ng6 12. c3 Bd6?! { Igor Naumkin, who has never had a
computer, because he doesn't know how to turn it on, immediately played 12...
Be7, which is stronger than ...Bd6. } (12... Be7 13. Nf4 Bd7 14. Be3?! Nh4 15. Qd1 Bd6 16. Re1 { 1/2 (16) Yudasin,L (2540)-Naumkin,I (2435) Montecatini Terme
1998. Igor could have won a pawn after } 16... Bxf4! 17. Bxf4 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Bxh3 $17) 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Nf4 Nxf4 (14... Ne4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Rae1 f5 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Qf4 Be6 19. h4 $14) 15. Bxf4 g6 16. Rae1 Be6 17. Re2 $14 { Bok,B (2562)
-Van Kampen,R (2609) Amsterdam 2015 1/2 (27) }) 8... h6 { A concession. Now
White can play Bh4. } (8... Re8! 9. Ng3 h6 { and Black has good chances to
equalise: } 10. Bf4 (10. Bd2 Nbd7 11. Nce2 Bxd2 12. Qxd2 Nf8 13. Nf4 Qd6 14. f3 Bd7 15. Bf5 Re7 16. Bxd7 Qxd7 17. Nd3 Ng6 18. Nc5 Qc7 19. Nf5 Ree8 { Shirov,A
(2755)-Ivanchuk,V (2751) Morelia/Linares 2008 1/2 (30) }) (10. Bh4? g5 $19) 10... Bg4 11. Qd2 Nbd7 12. a3 Bf8 13. h3 Be6 14. b3 { Ivan doesn't want to
admit that White has no advantage, so tries to prepare f4, f5, which leads to
a worse position. } 14... a6 15. Be3 (15. Rfe1 Rc8 16. Nf5 c5) 15... Rc8 16. f4 Nb8! 17. f5 Bd7 { After ...c5 White will have only problems with his f5-pawn. } 18. Kh1 c5! 19. dxc5 Bxc5 (19... Qc7! 20. Nge2 Bxc5 21. Bxc5 Qxc5 22. Qf4 Nc6 $15 { In order to avoid problems White needs to play very precisely }) 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Nge2 Qc8 (21... Qb6!? 22. Nd4 Rcc8 23. Nce2 Nc6 24. Qf4 Ne5 $15) 22. Rf4 d4?! 23. Rxd4 Bxf5 { Ivanisevic,I (2636)-Vallejo Pons,F (2705) Porto
Carras 2011 1/2 (30) }) 9. Bh4 Re8 10. f3 { Black's counterplay is connected
with preparation of ...Ne4, so White wants to get control over this square,
then he can play Qd2, Bf2, Ng3 with some chances to obtain an advantage. } (10. h3 Nbd7 11. a3 Bf8 12. Re1 Nb6 13. b3 Bd7 14. Bg3 Ne4 15. Be5 f6 (15... Nc8!? 16. Nxe4?! dxe4 17. Bxe4 f6 18. Bg6 fxe5 19. Bxe8 Qxe8 20. dxe5 Nb6 $15) 16. Bh2 f5 17. f3 Nxc3 18. Nxc3 Qh4 19. Ne2 c5 20. Bg3 Qf6 21. c3 f4?! (21... c4 22. Be5 Qf7 23. Bc2 cxb3 24. Bxb3 Nc4) 22. Nxf4 cxd4 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. cxd4 Bd6 25. Nh5 Qxd4+ 26. Kh1 $14 { Glek,I (2565)-Vaganian,R (2630) Netherlands 1998
0-1 (44) }) 10... Nbd7 11. Qd2 (11. Kh1 Nf8 12. g4 Ng6 13. Bg3 (13. Bxg6?! fxg6 14. Bg3 g5 15. Qd3 b6 16. Rae1 a5 $15) 13... h5 14. h3 Bd6 15. Qd2 Bxg3 (15... hxg4 16. hxg4 (16. fxg4?! Ne4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Qe3 Be6 19. Rae1 Bb4 20. a3 Ba5 $15) 16... Nh7 17. Rf2 Bxg3 18. Nxg3 Ng5) 16. Nxg3 Qd6 17. Nce2 hxg4 18. hxg4 Nh7 19. Rf2 Qf6 20. Nh5 Qe7 21. Nef4 $14 Nxf4 22. Qxf4 Nf8 23. Re2 Be6 24. g5 Ng6 25. Qg3 Qd7 26. Rae1 $16 { Ulibin,M (2562) -Prokopchuk,E (2470) Koszalin
1999 1/2 (70) }) 11... Nf8 12. Rae1 Bd7 13. a3 Be7 14. Bf2 Ng6 $146 (14... Bd6 15. Nd1 Qc7 16. Bg3 Nh5 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. g4 Nf6 19. Qf4 Qxf4 20. Nxf4 g5 21. Ne2 Re7 22. Ng3 Rxe1 23. Rxe1 Re8 24. Rxe8 Nxe8 { Fakhrutdinov,T (2161)
-Ponfilenok,V (2399) Kazan 2014 1/2 (43) }) 15. Bg3 { An ambitious plan. White
wants to put his bishop on e5 and gradually launch an attack by means of f4,
Ng3, f5. However in the following game Fabiano indicated the drawbacks of this
plan. } (15. Nd1!? Bd6 (15... Nh5 16. Bxg6! fxg6 17. g4! Nf6 (17... Bg5 18. Be3 Bxe3+ 19. Nxe3 Nf6 20. Nf4 g5 21. Nd3 Qc7 22. Re2 $14) 18. Nf4 g5 19. Ng6 Bd6 20. Bg3 Be6 21. Kg2 $14) 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3!? (17. Nxg3 Qc7 18. c3 Qf4) 17... Qc7 18. c3 Re7 19. Nf4 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Nxf4 21. gxf4 { with a slightly
better position for White. }) 15... Nh5 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Be5 Bh4 18. Rd1 { After this move White is almost forced to meet ...Bg5 with f4.18.Rb1 or 18.Ra1
with the idea to play 18...Bg5 19.Qd1 deserved consideration. } (18. Rb1 Bg5 19. Qd1 Be3+ 20. Kh1 g5 21. Qd3 Bf4 22. Nxf4 Nxf4 23. Qd2 Ng6) 18... Bg5 19. f4 (19. Qe1 Nf4 20. Nxf4 Bxf4 21. Rf2 g5 22. g3 Bxe5 23. dxe5 Qb6 24. Na4 Qc7 25. f4 Bf5 $15) 19... Be7 20. h3 Be6 21. Kh2 Nf6 22. Nc1 (22. g4!? Bf7 23. Rde1 Nd7 24. Ng3 a5 25. Qd3 { with a roughly equal position. }) 22... h5! 23. Nd3 Bf5 24. Ne2 Ne4 $15 { In the first part of the game Fabiano has played almost
perfectly and he has got a significant advantage. } 25. Qe3 h4 26. Rc1 Rc8 27. c3 Qb6!? { This is a strong move, which is connected with a wrong plan. } (27... b6 28. Rfe1 Qd7 29. Ng1 c5 30. Nf3 Bd8 $15 { with clear advantage. }) 28. b4 Bf6?! (28... Qd8 29. Nc5 Nd6 $15 { then Black will play ...b6 with ...c5 following. }) 29. Nc5 Nxc5?! { The black queen has nothing to do on b2. } (29... a5!? 30. Nxe4 Bxe5 31. fxe5 Rxe5 32. bxa5 Qa7 33. Qg5 Rxe4 34. Nf4 $13) 30. bxc5 { At least White has equalised the game. } 30... Qb2 31. Ng1 b6 (31... Qxa3?! 32. Ra1 Qb2 33. Rxa7 Ra8 34. Rxa8 Rxa8 35. Bxf6 gxf6 36. Rf2 Qb1 37. Nf3 $14) 32. Nf3 bxc5 (32... Be4 33. c4! { Only White has some chances to obtain an advantage: } 33... Bxe5 (33... bxc5 34. cxd5 cxd5 (34... Bxd5?! 35. Rxc5 Be7 36. Rc3 Bf6 37. Rf2 Qb7 38. Qd3 $14) 35. Bxf6 gxf6 36. dxc5 Kg7 37. Rg1 Bxf3 38. Qxf3 Rc7 39. Qxd5 Qxa3) 34. dxe5 g5 35. fxg5 Bxf3 36. Rxf3 Qxe5+ 37. Qxe5 Rxe5 38. cxb6 axb6 39. cxd5 Rxd5) 33. dxc5 Be4 34. Rce1 Re7?! { Now Black can get into trouble. } (34... Bxe5 35. fxe5 Re6 (35... Rxe5? 36. Rf2 Qb8 37. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 38. Kg1 $16) 36. Nxh4 Rce8 37. Nf3 Rxe5 38. Rf2 Bxf3 39. Qxf3 Qb8 40. Rxe5 Qxe5+ 41. Qg3) 35. Bxf6 gxf6 36. Nxh4?! (36. Rf2! Qxa3 37. Nxh4 { Probably Black should
have played } 37... Rf7 (37... Rce8 38. Qd4 Kf7 (38... Kg7 39. f5 g5 40. Ng6 Rf7 41. h4 gxh4 42. Nf4 $16) 39. f5 g5 40. Ng6 Rb7 41. h4 gxh4 42. Rf4 $16) (37... Rg7 38. Qd4 Rf8 39. f5 gxf5 40. Nxf5 Bxf5 41. Rxf5 Qb2 42. Rf2 Qb8+ 43. Kh1 Qg3 44. c4 $16) 38. Qd4 Qb3 39. Nf3 Qb8 40. Nd2 Bf5 41. g4 Bd7 42. Rfe2 $14 { White's
position is much better but Black's position isn't hopeless. }) 36... Rce8 37. Qg3 Rg7 38. Ra1 (38. c4!? dxc4 39. Re3 Qd4 (39... Qd2 40. Rfe1 (40. f5? gxf5 $17) 40... f5 41. Nf3 Qd5 42. Ng5 $14) 40. f5! (40. Rfe1 f5 41. Nf3 Qxc5 42. Ng5 Qd5 43. R1e2 c5 { White has enough compensation for the pawn }) 40... g5 (40... gxf5 41. Nxf5 $18) 41. Ng6 c3 42. Rfe1 Rb7 43. Qg4 c2 44. Rxe4 Rxe4 45. Rxe4 Qxc5 46. Rc4 c1=Q 47. Rxc1 Qxc1 48. Qd4 Qxa3 49. Qxf6 Qc5! { Black makes
a draw. For example } 50. Qh8+ (50. Qxg5 Qd6+ 51. Ne5+ Rg7 52. Qf4 Re7 53. Qg3+ Rg7 54. Qf4) 50... Kf7 51. Qh7+ (51. Ne5+ Ke7 52. Qg7+ Kd8 53. Qxg5+ Re7 54. Ng6 Qd6+ 55. g3 (55. Kh1 Qd1+ 56. Kh2 Qd6+) 55... Qc5! 56. Nxe7 (56. Qxe7+?? Qxe7 57. Nxe7 Kxe7 58. h4 a5 $19) 56... Qf2+) 51... Kf6 52. Qxb7 Qd6+ 53. Kh1 Qd1+) 38... g5! { Fabiano has found a reliable way to make a draw. } 39. fxg5 Rxg5 40. Qf2 Qxc3 41. Qxf6 (41. Rae1?! Rf8 42. Nf3 Rg7 43. Qe3 Qxe3 44. Rxe3 f5 $15) 41... Qg3+ 42. Kg1 Qxg2+ 43. Nxg2 Rxg2+ 44. Kh1 Rf2+ 45. Kg1 { ½-½
The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


