1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Be3?! { When I went through the French
phase of scoring nearly 100% against weaker players with the French, I
considered this move a mistake in view of Black's next. } 5... Nh6! { Now White
cannot play the equaliser Bh6 since this would cost him a vital tempo, and the
other lines are just slightly worse for White. } 6. Nf3 (6. Bd3 Qb6 7. Qd2 { may have been the lesser evil. }) 6... Nf5 7. Bd3 Nxe3 (7... Qb6!?) 8. fxe3 Qb6 9. Qc2 g6! { I preferred Black's game here in view of the bishop pair. White
can't really try for e4 because the d4 pawn would then be chronically weak. } 10. O-O Bg7 11. Kh1 O-O { The importance of fianchettoing the bishop over
playing ...Be7 is that White's d3-bishop is biting on granite, and ...f6 now
gains in strength. } 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Rae1 Rac8 { Retaining the tension, and it
can't hurt to line up a rook against the enemy queen. } (13... f6 { feels like
the right move, but } 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. e4 { can't be worse for
White. }) 14. a3 Ne7 15. b3?! f6 16. Qb2? fxe5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 c4 19. Bc2 cxb3 20. Bd3 Rxf1+ 21. Bxf1 Ba4 22. e4 Qf2 { White can resign, although he
fights on some more before giving up. } 23. Re2 Qf4 24. exd5 exd5 25. c4 Rxc4! 26. g3 Rc2 27. gxf4 Rxb2 28. Ne4 Rb1 29. Nc3 Rxf1+ { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


