1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 { - if we understand it as White, we can also apply that as Black } (3. e5 { How to respond to e5? } 3... c5 { 2v1 central majority (if they have to take back on d4 with a piece) } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] } 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 { [%cal Ga2a3,Gf7f6] } 6. Be2 (6. a3 { Several good options for Black } 6... f6!? { [%cal Gf6e5,Gg8h6] }) 6... Nh6 { Typical plan ...Nh6-f5 } { [%cal Gc5d4,Gh6f5,Gc1h6,Gb6b2,Gb2a1] }) (3. exd5 exd5 { [%cal Gg8f6,Gf8d6,Ge8g8] } 4. Bd3 (4. c4 Nf6 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] }) (4. Nf3 Bd6 { [%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] } 5. Bd3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc8g4] }) 4... Nc6 5. c3 Bd6 { ...Nge7/...Bg4/...Qd7/...f6/...0-0-0 } 6. Nf3 Bg4 (6... Nge7 7. O-O O-O { [%cal Gc8f5] }) 7. O-O { [%cal Gd8d7] } 7... Nge7 { Castling on the opposite side to opponent is a way to mix up the game and make a decisive result far more likely } { [%cal Gd8d7,Gf7f6,Ge8c8] }) (3. Nd2 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 3... c5! { [%cal Ge4d5,Ge6d5] } (3... Nf6 { Victorian juniors - the strongest ones are just following some opening book - e.g. Tiviakov had a nice win this year }) 4. exd5 exd5 { As long as you don't allow some nasty Re1 check - get into a solid middlegame (IQP) } { [%cal Gb8c6,Gg8f6,Gf8d6,Ge8g8] } 5. dxc5?! Bxc5 { [%csl Gd6,Gc5][%cal Gf8d6] }) 3... Nf6 4. e5 (4. Bg5 { French and Sicilian have in common - in many cases you have quite a few good moves } 4... Bb4 5. e5 h6 { Usually they end up with doubled pawns, your knight goes to e4, ...c5/...Nc6 to attack their centre } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gg5h4,Ge5f6,Gg5e3,Gg5d2,Gc7c5,Gc5d4,Gb2c3,Gb8c6] }) 4... Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O? (9. Be2 { Black is fine } { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Gd8b6,Gc8b7] }) (9. dxc5 Nxc5!? { Ganguly interpretation } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd3h7,Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] }) 9... c4! *


