{ If you master the art of 'being' - of playing improving moves and timing your
transformation of the position correctly CT-ART 6 - CT-ART 4 (on mobile)
Sometimes it's best to get all the pieces into play before forcing the issue
In principle, we want to get every piece into the action before our opponent
Is there a clear follow-up? }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bf5 { Chinese Petroff (...Bf5 line) } 7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. c4 c6 (9... Nc6 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Rfe8 { Drawing weapon }) 10. Nc3 (10. Qb3 { ...Bf5 - leaves b7 undefended (Qb3 is a thematic reply) -
Bf4 Qb6 (London) }) 10... Bb4 (10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nd7 $10) 11. Qc2 Bxc3 12. bxc3 { Dark squares weak } 12... Bg6 (12... Nd7) 13. Ne5 { Model example of you playing the improving moves well (getting the balance
right) } 13... f5 14. Rb1 Qc8 15. Nxg6 (15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Qb3 Qxc3 (16... Rd8 17. Bxe4 fxe4 18. Bg5 Rd6 { W to play (puzzle) } 19. Be7! Re6 20. Qxd5 Nc6 21. Nxg6 hxg6 22. Rxe4) 17. Qxc3 Nxc3 18. Rxb7 { White is winning because of the b8-knight
not being able to move }) 15... hxg6 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Bxe4 (17. c4) 17... fxe4 18. Qb3 (18. Rb5! Qc6 19. Qb3 Rd8 20. Rxe4) 18... Qf5 19. Rb2 b6 (19... Nd7 { [%csl Gb7,Gd5][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] }) 20. Rbe2 Nd7 21. c4 Nf6 22. cxd5 { [%csl Ge4,Gd5] } 22... Qxd5 (22... Rad8 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d5,Gc1a3,Gd5d6] }) (22... Nxd5 { [%cal Ge2e4,Gf5f2] }) 23. Qxd5+ Nxd5 24. Rxe4 { Black has the better minor piece } { [%csl Gc1,Gd5] } 24... Nc3 (24... Rad8 { [%csl Gd5] }) (24... Rac8 { [%csl Gc4,Gc2][%cal Gc8c2] }) 25. Rg4 Rf6 (25... Nxa2? 26. Bd2) 26. Bd2 Nd5 { Re5/Rg5 - too forcing (Black wants to place rooks on teh d-file anyway) } { [%cal Ge1c1,Gc1c8,Ge1e5,Gg4g5] } 27. Re5 { [%cal Gf6d6] } (27. Rge4 Kf7 { [%csl Ge7] } 28. Rc1 { [%csl Gc1][%cal Gc1c8,Ge4e8,Gf2f3,Gg1f2,Gf2e2,Ge2d3] }) 27... Rd6 28. Rgg5 Rad8 { Worst-placed piece (King) } { [%csl Ge5,Gg5,Gd2] } 29. h4 { here is where I lose it,
I'm just stuck or a plan and despite having time on the clock started paying
less attention instead of more. } (29. Kf1 { [%cal Gf1e2,Ge2d3,Gf2f3,Gh2h5] }) 29... Kf7 { Do not hurry (Shereshevsky) 'Endgame Strategy' } { [%csl Gd4] } 30. h5?? (30. Kf1 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd2e3] } 30... Ne7 (30... Nc7 31. Be3 Ne6 { [%cal Ge6d4] }) 31. Bb4 { [%cal Gb4e7,Ge5e7] }) (30. Be3 Nb4 (30... Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4] } 31. a3 Ne2+) 31. a4) 30... gxh5 31. Rxh5 Nf6 { and whites
advantage is gone. } 32. Rh4 Rxd4 33. Rxd4 Rxd4 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { [%cal Gd4a4,Ga4a2] } 34. Re2 { [%cal Ge2a2] } 1/2-1/2


