{ To fully understand an opening, not only do we have to know the correct moves,
but we should also appreciate how to punish common mistakes. For this purpose,
I will briefly analyse various historical games, starting with the stem game
of the Two Knights. }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 (2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 { , the Capablanca Variation, is a major line of the Caro-Kann,
but our version is very different! }) 2... d5 3. Nf3 { Two Knights Caro-Kann } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5?! { Now this is a mistake, as White has an extra developing move compared to the
previous line. } { Main idea of Caro - Black wants to develop his light-squared bishop actively (often before the other pieces)
Common club player mistake } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gc8f5] } (4... Nf6! 5. Nxf6+ exf6 { is correct, with the setup ...Bd6,
...0-0 and ...Bg4 in mind. }) 5. Ng3 { Both get out of the threat and make a threat of our own } 5... Bg6?! { The bishop proves a target on g6,
but } { Demonstration of White's initiative } (5... Bg4 { also favours White after the simple } 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 $14 { winning the bishop pair. }) 6. h4! { It is important to not give Black time to
consolidate his position. } 6... h6 { Other moves allow White to win the bishop or
the bishop pair with h5. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gg6h7] } (6... Nd7 7. h5 { trap the bishop } { [%cal Gh5g6] }) 7. Ne5! { White has a strong initiative, and Black
is forced to make concessions. } { [%cal Ge5g6,Gf7g6] } 7... Bh7? { Already the decisive mistake, as the
f7-pawn is now too weak. } (7... Qd6 8. d4 Nd7 { is necessary, but } 9. Nxg6 Qxg6 10. c3 $16 { is obviously very pleasant for White, who has the bishop pair
advantage and more space. He will also gain more time on Black's exposed queen. }) (7... Nd7 8. Nxg6 fxg6 { Weak g6-square } { [%csl Gg6,Gg7,Ge7][%cal Gf1d3,Gd3g6] }) 8. Qh5! g6 { Lasker playing a simul } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gh5f3,Gf3f7] } 9. Bc4? { This flashy move gives Black some hopes for
survival. } { [%cal Gc4f7] } (9. Qf3! { is a complete refutation, as we'll see in
Bogoljubow-Antze. }) 9... e6 (9... gxh5 10. Bxf7#) 10. Qe2 { Black missed the idea/threat behind this Qe2 move } 10... Bg7? { Missing White's threat. How does
White win? } { [%cal Ge5f7] } (10... Qe7 $16 { allows Black to fight on, though his position
remains miserable with the locked in h7-bishop and little development to
support his position. }) 11. Nxf7! { Black gets mated if he takes on f7, but
otherwise he loses the exchange, so he resigned. } 11... Kxf7 (11... Qe7 12. Nxh8 Bxh8 13. Qxe6 $18) 12. Qxe6+ Kf8 13. Qf7# { Mate } 1-0


[Event "Capablanca sim"]
[Site "New York,NY"]
