{ Our next game feels remarkably modern, with both players showing some typical
plans before Capablanca finally outplayed his tenacious opponent. }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6! { I could imagine the peanut gallery saying
at the time 'are you a fool, why would you double your own pawns against the
great Capablanca?' But it's the right move! } 5. Nxf6+ exf6 { Now Black is ready
to play ...Bd6, ...0-0 and ...Bg4, pressuring White on the kingside. } 6. d4 (6. Bc4!? Bd6 7. Qe2+ Qe7 8. Qxe7+ Kxe7 { has been popular in recent games,
but the endgame looks safe for Black. }) 6... Be6?! { A bit passive - the
bishop is more active on g4. } (6... Bd6) 7. Be2 (7. Bd3! { is in turn a
better post for the bishop. }) 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 Qc7?! { This makes
sense with the bishop on g4, but here I would prefer } (9... Re8 10. Be3 Nd7 11. Qd2 Nf8 { is the correct setup for Black, intending ...Ng6 and eventually ...
Nf4. Meanwhile, central play with } 12. Rfd1 Ng6 13. d5 cxd5 14. cxd5 Bd7 { doesn't offer White anything, as the d-pawn is firmly blockaded. }) 10. h3 (10. Be3 Nd7 11. Rc1 { is the correct setup, when d5 can be annoying in some
positions. If } 11... c5!? 12. d5 Bf5 13. g3 $14 { should be a tad better for White
due to his protected passer. }) 10... Rd8?! { A mistake, as the rooks belong on
e8 and d8. } (10... Nd7 11. Be3 Rad8 { would be normal. }) 11. b3?! { It's not clear what purpose the bishop serves on b2, as opposed to } (11. Re1 Na6 12. Bd2 Re8 13. Bd3 $14) 11... Nd7 (11... Qd7 12. Re1 Re8 13. Be3 Na6) 12. Bb2 Nf8 13. Bd3 { The correct square for the bishop, but then we should
have played Bd3 in one go. } 13... Qd7 (13... Ng6) 14. Re1 Re8 { In such
positions, Black can already think about the piece sacrifice on h3 - hence
White's next. } 15. Bf1!? (15. Nd2 Bxh3! 16. Rxe8 Rxe8 17. gxh3 Qxh3 { Black is clearly trying to mate our king White to play (Puzzle) } { [%csl Gh3,Gd2,Gf8,Gd6][%cal Gd2f1] } 18. Qf3! { Qf3 offers a trade of queens - very good way to beat back their attack } { [%cal Gh3h2,Gg1f1] } (18. Nf1 { [%csl Gh2,Gf4] } 18... Ne6 { [%cal Ge6g5,Gg5f3,Ge6f4] } (18... Ng6 19. Bxg6 { [%cal Gg6h4,Gh3g2] } 19... hxg6 { Rook lift (...Re4-g4) } { [%cal Ge8e4,Ge4g4] } 20. f3 Bf4) 19. Be4 Ng5 20. Bg2) 18... Bh2+ (18... Qh2+ 19. Kf1 { [%cal Gf3h1] }) 19. Kh1 Bg3+ 20. Kg1 Bh2+ { would be an immediate repetition - far
from ideal in a simul game. } { [%cal Gg1h1,Gh2g3] }) 15... Rad8 (15... Bb4! 16. Re3 Bf5 { even gives
Black chances to fight for an advantage with ...Ng6-f4. }) 16. Qd2 Ng6 17. Rad1 Bf4 18. Qc3 Qc8 (18... Bf5 { is the most natural, fighting for the open e-file. }) 19. Bd3 Bb8 20. Re3 { I would have preferred to avoid Bxh3 ideas, but I guess
Capablanca couldn't find a better plan. } 20... Nf4 (20... Bxh3 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. gxh3 Qxh3 23. Bxg6 Qg4+ (23... hxg6 24. Re1! { maintains the balance. }) 24. Kf1 Qh3+ 25. Kg1 Qg4+ { is a draw if Black wants it. }) 21. Bf1 Bf5!? { Black wants to win! } (21... Bxh3 22. gxh3 Rxe3 23. Qxe3 Re8 24. Qd2 Nxh3+ 25. Bxh3 Qxh3 26. Re1!) 22. Rde1 Rxe3 23. fxe3 { White wanted to change the
position, but } (23. Qxe3 { seems best. }) 23... Nh5 (23... Ne6!? 24. Bd3 Bg6 { could lead to a funny square structure if White took on g6! }) 24. e4 Bd7 (24... Bg6!? { is probably more accurate, so the bishop has a nice diagonal
after e5. Perhaps Black wanted to avoid } 25. Nh4?! Bg3 26. Nxg6 hxg6 27. Rd1 { , but this is superb for Black after } 27... Qe6 $15 { as White's central pawns are
vulnerable. }) 25. e5! { Now the momentum is with White. } 25... Be6! { A strong
move, keeping the tension. } 26. exf6 (26. g4 Nf4 27. exf6 Bxg4! 28. hxg4 Qxg4+ 29. Kf2 Ne6! { gives a full attack for the piece. }) 26... Nxf6 27. Ng5?! (27. Bd3 { is more natural. }) 27... Qc7?! 28. Nf3 Qg3 29. Qa5 (29. Ne5 { seems the best way to enter an endgame, cutting off the queen. }) 29... Qc7 (29... Bc7! 30. Qg5 h6 31. Qxg3 Bxg3 32. Re3 Bf5 33. Re7 Rd7 34. Rxd7 Nxd7 { is about equal, but Black can claim some small chances due to White's cut off
king. }) 30. Qxc7 Bxc7 31. Ng5 Re8?! { Black gives up the bishop pair for no
real reason. } (31... Bf5) 32. Nxe6 Rxe6 33. Rxe6 fxe6 34. Kf2 $14 { The
rest of the game is not really relevant for our topic, but as one might expect,
Capablanca's endgame technique proved far superior to his opponent's. } 34... Ne4+ 35. Ke3 Ng3 36. Bd3 g6 37. b4 Kf7 38. a4 Nf5+ 39. Kf3 Bb6 40. c5 Bc7 41. b5 Ne7 42. bxc6 Nxc6 43. Bc4 h5 44. Ke4 Ne7 45. d5 exd5+ 46. Bxd5+ Nxd5 47. Kxd5 Ke7 48. c6 bxc6+ 49. Kxc6 Bd8 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


