{ The following game is not theoretically relevant, but it certainly is fun! } { Guess the Move (White POV) - right arrows to see the next move }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e5 Ne4 5. Qe2 Nxc3 6. dxc3 b6?! { Not a terrible
move, but it's easier to play ...Bg4. } (6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 { is very solid for Black. } 9. Bf4 Nd7 10. O-O-O b5 11. h4 h5 12. g4 hxg4 13. Qxg4 Qc7 14. Re1 O-O-O { is then the viral castling video from 1-0 (48)
Nepomniachtchi,I (2703)-Karpov,A (2616) Moscow 2013, where Karpov touched his
rook first when castling. Nepo looked for the arbiters to report touch move,
but couldn't get their attention, and let it go. }) 7. Nd4!? (7. Qe3 { is the
other way to cover ...Ba6. }) 7... c5?? { Already a decisive mistake! } (7... e6 8. f4 c5 9. Nf3 Ba6 10. Qf2 Bxf1 11. Rxf1 Qd7 { should be close to equal,
as Black exchanged his two main problem pieces for the French structure. }) 8. e6! $18 { A beautiful move. } 8... fxe6 (8... cxd4 9. Qb5+ Nd7 10. exf7+ Kxf7 11. Qxd5+ Ke8 12. Qxa8 { picks up the exchange. }) (8... a6 9. Qf3! fxe6 (9... f6 10. Bc4! Bb7 11. Nf5 g6 12. Ne3 $18) 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qe5 Rg8 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 13. Qxe6 Rg7 14. g3 $18 { is a complete mess for Black, who will
have to jettison material. }) 9. Qh5+ Kd7 (9... g6 10. Qe5 Rg8 11. Nxe6 { is pretty agonising. }) 10. Nf3 Kc7 11. Ne5 (11. Bf4+ Kb7 12. Ng5! { is the
most clinical, as Nf7 can't really be avoided. }) 11... Bd7? (11... g6 12. Nxg6 Rg8 13. Qxh7 Rg7 14. Qh5 { is still winning for White, but Black can
struggle on. }) 12. Nf7 Qe8 13. Qe5+ Kb7 14. Bf4! c4 15. Qc7+ { White could
take the rook, of course, but this leads to a comedic king hunt. } 15... Ka6 16. Nd8! Nc6 (16... Qxd8 { is the only way to avoid a fast mate. }) 17. Qb7+ Kb5 18. a4+ Kc5 { Can you find the mate in two? } (18... Ka5 19. Nxc6+ Bxc6 20. b4+ cxb3 21. Qa6#) 19. Qxc6+! Bxc6 20. Nxe6# { A nice finish. } 1-0


