{ Guess the Move }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. d4!? { This move sets a devilish trap, which
Black falls right into! } 4... dxe4 (4... e6 5. h3 Bh5 6. g4! Bg6 7. exd5 cxd5 (7... exd5 8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. Be3 $16 { is a bit awkward for Black, as White
develops much faster. }) 8. h4! { is White's idea, when h5/Ne5 will give White
a strong initiative. }) 5. Nxe4 Bxf3? { This pawn grab is much too ambitious.
But it's also the most common move, so we clearly have the makings of a good
trap! } (5... e6 6. Bd3 Nf6 { is best, with a solid game for Black. }) 6. Qxf3 Qxd4 7. Be3! $16 { A great move, sacrificing more material for the initiative. } 7... Qe5? { Black should at least have a second pawn for his suffering. The
queen will continue to be harassed in the centre. } (7... Qxb2 8. Bc4! { , in the spirit of the Romantic era, is very strong, as Black has no time to
take both rooks: } 8... Qxa1+? (8... Nf6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rfd1! $16 { is also very
strong for White, who has a massive lead in development. }) 9. Ke2 Qxh1 (9... Qe5 10. Qxf7+ Kd7 11. Rd1+ Kc7 12. Bf4 $18) 10. Qxf7+ Kd7 11. Nc5+ Kc7 (11... Kd6 12. Qf4+ e5 13. Qxf8+ Ne7 14. Qxh8 $18) 12. Bf4+ Kb6 13. Na4+ Ka5 14. Bd2+! Kxa4 15. Ba6 Qb1 16. Qc4+ Ka3 17. Bc1+ Qxc1 18. Qb3#) 8. O-O-O Nf6 9. Ng5! $18 { A very strong move, threatening Rd8. } 9... Nbd7 (9... Qa5 10. Bc4 e6 11. Qh3! { sets up deadly sacks on f7 and e6. }) 10. Bc4 e6 11. Rxd7! { A total
hammerblow. } 11... Ba3 (11... Kxd7 12. Nxf7 { wins the rook in the corner, but }) (11... Nxd7 12. Qxf7+ Kd8 13. Nxe6+ { is even worse. }) 12. Rxb7 { White is up too
much material, so Black resigned. } 1-0


