1. a3 a6 2. e4 c5 3. Nf3 (3. b4!? { Improved Wing Gambit } 3... e5! (3... e6 4. bxc5 Bxc5 5. d4 Bb6 6. c3 $14) 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bb2 Nf6 6. Nxe5 cxb4 7. axb4 Bxb4 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. f4 $13) 3... d6 { [%cal Gf1b5] } (3... Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 e5 { Ndb5 has been prevented, but things aren't that simple! } 7. Nb3! { [%cal Gf8b4] } 7... d6 8. Be2 Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Be6 11. Qd3 { We have transposed to a variation of the 6.Be2 Najdorf considered equal after } 11... d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 $10) (3... e6 4. c4! (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 { - White would not play a3 like this in the Paulsen Sicilian. }) 4... Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Nc3 $14 { - Bb4 was prevented. } { [%cal Gf8b4] }) 4. d4 (4. Nc3 e5!?) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 (5. Qxd4 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1b5] }) 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 { Transposing to the harmless 6.a3 Najdorf } 6... e5 7. Nf3 b5 $10 { We can conclude that the Sicilian Defence is stronger than usual with the inclusion of 1.a3 a6. } *


