[Event "1.a3 a6 Opening Theory: Conclusion"]
[Date "2017.07.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A00"]
[Opening "Anderssen's Opening"]
[StudyName "1.a3 a6 Opening Theory"]
[ChapterName "Conclusion"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Yh4LK3Jc/7iTd2UWE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/Craze"]
[UTCDate "2017.07.17"]
[UTCTime "14:04:51"]

1. a3 a6 { We can say that the inclusion of a3 a6 is in Black's favour, as it makes the Sicilian and QGA much stronger. The English is probably White's best try for an edge, but here too Black has ways to make White's a3 look nearly useless.
The above conclusions would suggest that the often proposed solution of avoiding opening theory by changing the starting position with a3/a6 would taint the } 2. e4 { purity of the royal game and limit the scope for creative expression. } *


